Archer is a young, 9-month old dog who has recovered well from his ortho surgery on his broken leg in Oct. 2020 and has ventured out w/his foster family on many several mile hikes/walks/run and LOVES it!

Archer is a strong, highly active dog. IF you have small children, he may not be a fit (several families w/small children loved him but were concerned of his energy level w/their kids.) He IS a puppy whose life has been crated due to his broken leg/surgery/recovery, so WILL have high energy.

Archer is so sweet and so loving. He loves to play/walk/hike/run! He was not well socialized with other dogs but is much better now that he's with a foster who is a dog trainer. We would like Archer to continue that life - with another playful dog.

Archer is getting some training w/his dog trainer foster person so is better than he was a week ago (this bio revised 1/25/21).

Archer is SUCH a GEM! All that meet him say "I love him." Current foster said "he's such a smart dog and listens well and learns quickly!"

animal.description:
***All animals listed on our website are in private foster homes. To arrange a meet and greet with a dog, you MUST fill out the adoption application so that it can be sent to the foster parent for review to determine if your home is a match for the dog. If a dog receives multiple applications, we operate on a best-fit basis, not first come first served.***

Hi! My name is Novacora, but foster mom usually calls me Nova or Novabear! I am a very sweet, loyal, and snuggly girl once I bond with my people. I am the biggest snugglebug! My favorite pillow is my foster mom or whatever pillow she's using -- sometimes both! I love to curl up next to her, and I can't wait to do the same with my forever family!

I came to my foster mom with heartworms and have received treatment through Second Chance. I am now finally able to run around, which I still only do from time to time. You see, foster mom says I am a medium to low energy girl, with random spurts of energy.

I love to go for walks, take naps, do zoomies (every now and then) around the yard, and most of all, spend time with my loved ones. 

I am looking for a forever home where I can be the only four-legged princess in the house and get all of the attention. I've been around kids and like them a lot! 

I am spayed, up-to-date on vaccinations, microchipped, have been dewormed, and am current on my monthly heartworm and flea/tick preventatives. My adoption fee is $300. If you think I could be the one for you, please fill out an adoption application on our website: www.secondchancenc.org. Thank you!

animal.description: Petunia is the sweetest girl you will ever meet! If you are looking for a lapdog - she is your girl. She loves to snuggle up to you anytime she can! She loves to play fetch in the backyard, and she is fast as lightning! She would love to accompany you on a run, walk, or a trip to the store. She is the perfect companion. She gets along great with kids and adults. Although she is extremely energetic and crazy at times, she also LOVES to take naps. Petunia snores like a human and wow is it cute! While she enjoys playing with other dogs, Petunia does not realize how strong she is, and can get over-excited, especially on walks. She would be best in a home with no other animals because she loves to be the center of attention! She does wonderful with every human, and meeting new people is one of her favorite activities! If the home does have another dog, it must be a female - no males, please. Petunia is such a smart girl and ready for continued training. She catches on quickly. She is the most loyal companion and would be the perfect fit for someone who is active outdoors but likes to snuggle occasionally too. Fill out an application at cfp-nc.org/adopt! If you are interested in this animal please start by filling out an adoption application at CFP-NC.org/adopt and we will get in touch with you.

animal.description:
Meet Noah! Noah is one of about 50 dogs rescued from a neglectful hoarding situation in South Georgia back in early July. Some of the dogs on the property had been living inside and were more socialized, able to be adopted quickly. But sadly, there was another group that had lived their whole lives outside with little human interaction. It has taken a couple of months of living in a foster home for them to start realizing that there are good people in this world who will love and cherish them. These dogs have come amazingly far since being rescued but do still carry the weight of their previous life with them. As such, they have very specific adoption requirements listed below. Please understand, we have taken 3 months to get to know these dogs and what they need to succeed. The adoption requirements are not arbitrary but are what is needed for them to lead happy, healthy lives and as such no exceptions to these requirements will be allowed. 

 

Noah is about a two and a half years old and under 25 lbs. Hes a sweet, playful boy but still a bit on the shy side. He needs a patient adopter who is going to give him the time and space he needs to adjust and get comfortable in a new home. Given that the best teachers for dogs lacking confidence are other dogs, Noah also must have other confident dogs in the home with at least one of them being under 30 lbs and playful. He is learning to walk on a leash but has yet to gain enough confidence to go to the bathroom on leash and does require a SECURELY fenced yard - solid wood privacy fence only (minimum 6 ft); chain link, wrought iron, or other types of fencing are not sufficient. Lastly, given that Noah is still learning to trust people, he will not do well with the unpredictable nature of children. Homes with teenagers may be considered on a case by case basis, depending on the experience level of the family. 

 

We do understand that the above requirements greatly narrows the pool of potential adopters and may even scare some people away. Noah is most definitely a work in progress but we cannot even begin to explain how rewarding it is to watch the transformation of a dog like this who has never known love before. Once they learn to love and trust, they are so very very grateful and the amount of love they have to give and their loyalty knows no bounds. If you are interested in becoming part of Noahs continuing story, email adrienne@rescuemega.org or fill out an adoption application on our website- www.rmgdogs.org

animal.description:
Rossi is an amazing dog who knows a wide variety of commands and is obedience trained very well. He loves playing ball and has been good with dogs big and small as well as with kids. (We recommend no young children because heelers have a classic nipping tendency to herd children and some children may view this as aggressive. Older children should have no problem.) He is obviously incredibly intelligent and he has a huge personality. He loves attention and lives to please.

He is a border collie/heeler mix and favors the heeler personality. He cannot have ivermectin based heartworm preventative as he likely has the MDR1 mutation that makes him sensitive to it. 

Rossi is up to date on all of his shots including Bordetella and rabies. He has 6 months of HW preventative and obviously is HW negative. The lump on his hip was tested. It is a harmless cyst and nothing to worry about. His prior owners recommend no small animals due to food agression but has been fine (when food isn't involved with cats and other dogs both big and small). 

His prior owners say....

He always alerts us of copperheads. The intensity and pitch of his bark changes. He has done it three time this year alone. He got bit once several years back and is extra vigilant about alerting his family to them He is inside while we are home and outside while we are gone because if there is food left out or to be found, he will find it. He knows how to flip up the lid on his dog food bin so we put something heavy on top when we leave him in because of rain.

He respects his fenced yard. Before we replace it the fence that was here it was really lose fitting horse type fencing. He could push the fencing out at the bottom and squeeze under. He got out while we were gone and when we got home we had a dead chicken, he was covered in dirt and debris but he was waiting on our front porch when we got home (but he had been places). It happened a few times. We put up a good solid fence and he has never dug under or tried to climb it.

He has always slept inside in his crate in our room. He actually likes it. There are times he beats us upstairs and will push up the door and go in on his own.

Boyd Animal Hospital and TCAP have been the other places he has had vacations and HW tests. He has never been to the vet due to illness or injury. They lump on his hip was the only concern and they tested it in Denton...it is just a cyst nothing to worry about. 

We have camped several times with him and have taken him to public places. I would obviously say the handler should confident and understand heelers. He did wonderfully.

Very obedient. Energetic and so so funny. He loves to play with his toys and his people. My daughter has a large lab/shepherd mix. She and Rossi absolutely love one another so she brings her over so they can play. He just needs people who know heelers and no small animals to avoid food aggression issues.
animal.name: Rossi

animal.description:
Hey fans, Elvis here. What's that? I'm a hunka, hunka burning love. Well, you got that right. Just look at me. My mesmerizing eyes, my gorgeous amber coat, the cutest ears ever and muscles that don't quit. The volunteers say I am the complete package and I'd have to agree. WOOF! Boy, they know me from nose to tail.

I am a little aloof, but love to be loved. Rub my ears, give me a treat and I melt, but spending quality time with my family means the world to me..

I look forward to my daily walks and start off cautiously checking out my surroundings and sniffing all the fabulous smells. Move slowly, give me a little time and space and once I feel grounded it's giddy up and go, go, go. I do have a little, secret, I also like to jog. When I get the urge, off I go trotting along with the wind in my ears, a smile on my face and you in tow. These short bursts, often called High Intensity Training (HIT), make me one good looking pup and is great for your health too. It's a win, win for you and me.

Another little secret.. I do need to be the only pet in the home. No dogs or cats and no dog beach/dog park. You see, I'm ok being around other dogs, but I'm not one to share my personal space! I have even worked with a trainer on how to be well behaved, and you will definitely need to be on board to continue my awesome training!

So dear friends, if you are looking for a hunka, hunka burning love who has it going on, I am the family member for you. Trust me, you won't regret it. I will fill your hearts with endless love, wags and kisses and you get to say, " Elvis is in the house!"

*no other pets/adult home only/no apartment! Need big dog experience, no first time dog owners!

*Please complete our online application for further consideration. We do best fit for both dog and family, and completing an application is not a guarantee of approval.

animal.description: Amble, 5, is a long-limbed GSD-mix girl who was rescued from a cemetery.  We don’t know her backstory, but we imagine being left to take care of herself wasn’t easy.  Amble was quite fearful of strangers when she came into our program, but she allowed our veterinary team to check her out and vaccinate her without even the tiniest growl of protest.  She would love to have someone who either has some experience with shy dogs or someone willing to pour a little extra love and patience into her to help build up her level of comfort.  She would thrive in a quieter adult home with a strong routine she could settle into with you.  She is gentle and seems very much to want to foster a connection with you.  She just needs a guide who can show her how to feel more comfortable in the world.  As someone with a very shy dog from a similar background, we can tell you these dogs can — and do — love you back, with a depth of love and appreciation that is hard to describe but amazing to experience.  Amble just needs someone willing to take time and build trust.  The payoff is as sweet as it gets, friend.
animal.name: Amble

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. All of our dogs and cats are in foster homes and we have no paid staff. If you have questions concerning a specific animal, PLEASE fill out an application and the foster parent will be in touch. We will not arrange any home visits with any of our dogs and cats until your application is processed. Please understand our foster parents are precious to our 2nd Chance family; without them we cannot function, so we do our best to not burden them with multiple appointments. Our foster parents will choose their top 3 applications and arrange home visits with these applicants. The adopter will be chosen at that time. The process can take anywhere from a week to a month. We want to make sure our little furry ones are placed in their 'forever home' and never have to go through a rehoming again!My name is Murphy. I was kept outside all my life in a fenced in area with rats as big as rabbits :( My owners never touched me. I am partially blind. The officers finally came to the house and took me and my 3 brothers. One of them died at the shelter :( Now 2nd Chance has the rest of us. I want to be in a home where I get to be your one and only. I am already potty trained! Don't worry about my blindness I get around just fine :)Please fill out an adoption application:
Adoption application (Dog)
Adoption Application (Cat)

Please understand we do not adopt out dogs to
families with children under the age of 5. We do not adopt dogs to renters. Some dogs will have fence requirements while others may not.

A pet is a lifetime commitment. The dogs and cats in our system find themselves there, for the most part, because their humans did not have the same loyalty to them as they did to their owners. We do not take the adoption process lightly, and will do everything in our power to make sure the animal is placed correctly the first time around for your sake and theirs. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description: . Scrappy Doo is a 3-to-4-year-old, 21-lb rat terrier mix currently being fostered in Bradenton,FL. She is very shy and timid in new situations, but will blossom if given a day to get used to her new situation. She is a bit untrusting with new people, and again needs a bit of time to acclimate. It took her two days in my home as a new foster. She is great with other dogs, great with people once she knows you. If given the chance, she can be a velcro dog, but she is not given that opportunity here. She will do well with another kind quiet dog of any size. She loves to run outdoors and gets the zoomies frequently. She would need a fenced yard. She does know basic commands, has no issues crating. I have seen no resource guarding. She does have prey drive, no cats or small furry creatures. She is learning to explore water so swimming may be in her future. I have had her a week so we have not explored toys yet. Quiet and unassuming. Great dog for an older couple or folks that want an easy going pup. She will take advantage if you are not the boss as with any terrier. Would prefer someone with terrier experience please. She has had a bad case of flea allergies and demodex, the hair on her back is filling in nicely.

animal.description:
Meet Shelby!

"Hi everyone! My name is Shelby and I am a pit bull mix.  I realize you may not think this, but I truly am a lap dog!  I am fully house trained, and don't mind a crate, but my favorite spot is either on my bed, or snuggled on top of a blanket on the couch with you!  I love to dig and run, and can not wait for it to snow! Playing in the snow is something I really enjoy!  I also look forward to daily walks, as long as I am on my leash.  I love to do "work" by sniffing out treats, and practicing different commands like sit, wait, and down.  I also really enjoy working to get some mashed sweet potato and peanut butter out of my Kong! I am a bit nervous when I first meet you, unless you have another dog that is a bit more confident, then I am much more comfortable.  I would do best in a home with no children, and at least one other dog to play with.  I can take my cues from them, and know that I have nothing to be nervous about!  I have been to a board and train, and understand "place", as well as the proper way to walk with a leash.  I am such a snuggle bug, and truly love those I am around."

Shelby is a 5 year old female and weighs about 70 pounds. She is gorgeous and will make a wonderful new BFF ! She is house trained, healthy, up to date on her shots and is spayed. Shelby is currently in CT and can travel to her new home ASAP.  Shelby would love to join an active person looking to add a second dog to their pack.  Her adoption donation is $350. 

*Unless stated otherwise, all dogs will be spayed or neutered, on flea/tick product and heart worm prevention medicine (if older than 5 months) and micro chipped prior to adoption.

*Please note that while we do our best to accurately state the breed or breed mix of a dog, we often have very limited information to draw from. Identifying the breed without pedigrees and information on heritage can be very challenging! 

If you are interested in adopting one of our animals, please go to www.angelsamongusanimalrescue.org and fill out an online adoption application. Thank you!

animal.description:
Aspen is a precious puppy who is a part of a litter of 5 who were all saved from a local kill shelter. Their estimated date of birth is 8/13/20. At 3 months old,  Aspen currently weighs 13.3 pounds. Friendly & sweet, Aspen loves everyone she meets. She is used to being crated at night and playing in a safe, fenced yard during the day. Aspen is fine with other dogs and will be fine with cats and other animals if introduced as a puppy. Aspen is crate trained, trained to a potty box and has lots of toys and a fluffy bed in her crate that she does not chew. She is now fully vetted and ready for her forever home. Aspen's wish list consists of an inside forever home with a big fenced yard for playtime, a home with lots of toys and another doggy friend for play time and pet parents who understand the time commitment that a puppy requires. Adopters who are retired or work-from-home parents are ideal as they have the time to spend with the pet. Adopters committed to doing a 6 week basic obedience class to ensure Aspen's continued success at being a good canine citizen would also a plus. If you think you have the perfect home for Aspen, contact us at info.caresga@gmail.com for an adoption application. We adopt up north and all over so please ask for details. $400 adoption fee and a vet reference is required to ensure a great home (this means you have had a pet so we can call to verify their level of care). Eligibility for adoption means your current or past pets are spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccines and on monthly heartworm and flea prevention. Please be aware that we do not allow shock collars (ie underground fences) or "pens" as an alternative for a fenced yard.

We do our best to place our rescue pets in the very best homes. Please be aware that we have an application which also includes required vet records showing your existing pets are current on preventative medical care. Puppy adopters please take note that we generally try to place our puppies into homes where at least one parent is retired/stay at home/works from home to ensure the puppy gets enough attention and training (puppies cannot hold it all day in a crate) so please have a plan ready when contacting us. For safety reasons, we try not to place small dogs or puppies in families with children under 5 (there may be exceptions depending on situation).

Typical adoption fees for puppies are $350, juvenile dogs $300, adults dogs are $250, senior dogs are $150. Some pets, smaller dogs for example, may have a higher than normal adoption fee but we will alert you if there is a variance. Dogs rescued from China always have a higher adoption fee. Adoption fees help our group offset PART of the cost of rescuing, rehabilitating, and getting the pet healthy so they can go on to find a loving home with someone willing to give them a second chance at life. This amount includes each animal being current on age appropriate vaccinations including DHPPL, bordetella, influenza, rabies, and boosters when appropriate. De-wormed for any internal parasites (round worms, hook worms, tape worms and whipworms) with Drontal Plus, 4DX tested heart-worm negative (if positive, they are treated), tested negative for tick borne diseases, spayed/neutered, implanted with a micro-chip and have been examined by a veterinarian to certify that they are healthy. Any other known health issues are treated as well prior to adoption (examples: UTI, broken bones, contagious infections, dental cleanings, etc). All animals are also on a regime of flea and heartworm medication every month. Lifetime registration for the micro-chip is included in each adoption fee. In addition, each adopter will go home with a fitted collar, tags, a bag of dog food the pet has been on, copies of all vet history, and an adoption kit filled with valuable information and coupons as well as other various treats or toys as promotions become available. All puppy adoptions include two puppy training books, the Puppy Primer & Way To Go by Patricia McConnell, and all adult adoptions go home with Love Has No Age Limit by Patricia McConnell to help ensure a smooth transition for your new family member.

We ask that you consider an additional donation on top of this pet's adoption fee. This money will go directly into our Adoption Fund to be used exclusively for rescuing and caring for other pets in need. Many pets we take in have very high vet bills to get them healthy and adoptable for the public - much higher than their adoption fees. We receive no government funding and rely solely on donations from our community and caring adopters to continue our rescue efforts!

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Old man Champ is a senior boy with a super cool personality who wants nothing more than to live out the rest of his years loving his human and taking naps. He loves to greet you when you come home from running errands and follow you from room to room when you are home. He has gotten better at being left alone for longer periods of time but would still enjoy an adopter who is home more than they are not. Champ is such a good boy that he doesnt need crated when you leave, which is good because hes not fond of the crate at all. We actually think that his prior owner likely kept him crated a lot because he will gnaw on the wires and his front bottom teeth are ground down :( He is currently being fostered with other dogs in the home and does well with them but hes not much of an endurance playmate. He would be fine as an only dog or with another low energy dog in the home. He has met a cat outside from the other side of a fence and was interested in sniffing but did not try to go after him. So a dog savvy cat would likely be ok. He is able to do carpeted steps at this time but his strength matches his age so that may change sooner than later. He is great on a leash and should be leashed to go out if there is not a fenced in yard because he does like to sniff and is a little hard of hearing. He loves laying on fluffy dog beds, blankets and on the couch next to you. When his blanket falls off the couch he will make eye contact with you and let out a raspy bark to let you know it needs put back on the couch lol. He is completely house trained and will go to the door when he needs to go out. Sometimes he likes to lay like a frog on the floor with his back legs out to the sides lol! If you have your heart on a senior dog or would like to open your heart and home to champ, please apply for adoption through our website www.onedogatatime.us

animal.description:
Hi, there!  Cruz here!  I am over 10 years old and a big boy at 71 pounds.  I was running around near the city park when the Animal Control Officer picked me up!  She took me to the city shelter, but my family never came for me.  Unfortunately, I have heartworms and have to go thru a treatment. Due to my age, it was decided the monthly prevention is safer and will slowly kill off the remaining heartworms, but it is a slow processs.  So I  will need to be walked and not do any running until everything is clear.  That's OK because I just want to be a lazy boy anyway.    I really like people and just want to be loved so bad!  I'm keeping it a secret as to my exact ancestry! 

Cruz is currently in foster care.  To see him, please contact Ward-Wiseman by phone or email and arrange a meeting.

Adoption fee $100 includes neuter, vaccinations, microchip

animal.description:
Hi, My name is ACE and I am a Two-year-old PUGGLE MIX with a soft Tan coat. I weigh 16 pound  

 Here is my story...
 I  came here with  7 other dogs from Texas, and we had a rough start. We lived outside in someone’s enclosed yard and weren’t shown any love or attention. No one interacted with us, so we thought that humans were scary. 

 But that’s the past and now that I have been rescued and am constantly told that I am special and Posh, I’m leaving my past behind and ready for a new, happy life with a loving family. 

 I am in a wonderful foster home in New York where I am learning  to trust 

 My foster mom has been very patient with me as I was very skittish when I first arrived. Their kindness and patience and living with OTHER DOGS  is really helping me thrive and I copy them so Our rescue feels that ANOTHER$ SMALL DOG in the home is required, as it is very good for me to live with a stable dog I can play with.

  I  also have discovered how much I love to be touched and get belly rubs  but this has taken the time and any new person must realize it's going to take time and patience 

 I am still skittish of strangers coming into the home and will run and hide. But  I love to come and play with the other dogs and love car rides and going for walks 

 The leash is left on me as I still have a tendency to hide when I am scared, and that makes it easy for my foster parents to get me and take me for a walk 

 I hope your heart is open to giving me a chance at having a loving family to call my own. I promise I’m worth getting to know. I NEED ANOTHER DOG in the home to also keep showing me how to be a great family member. 

 A home in the suburbs is best for me with a fenced in yard also as I am still nervous of loud noises

 I am neutered now and have all my shots. Heart Worm tested negative

 Please fill out this application by copying and pasting the link into your browser

 https://poshpetsrescueny.org/dog-application/

animal.description:
Available for adoption in Texas: meet Scarlett!

Scarlett is 2 years old and weighs 58 lbs. 

Scarlett is a sweet, cuddly girl who loves to give kisses. She loves to curl up next to her foster mama and lay her head in her lap for pets. She's really a dog that just wants to be wherever her family is!

An ideal home for Scarlett would be one with a confident fur sibling to play with. One that can show her the ropes and be her best friend! 

Scarlett does great with other dogs and grows in confidence herself when she has one to follow. She's really taken to one of the male dogs in her foster home and follows him everywhere.

Scarlett prefers female humans over males, but she has warmed up to the males in her foster home given time. 

She is a timid dog that needs a patient forever home that will accept her for who she is. She may take a while to warm up in new situations and when meeting new people, but she's very sweet when she does. 

Scarlett came into the rescue scared, timid, and pregnant. She was a wonderful mama to her six beautiful puppies, and now she's ready for a loving family of her own!

She is now spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, and housebroken. 

If you think Scarlett is the girl for you, please apply now at www.luckylabrescue.com

animal.description:
CAPTAIN AND TENNILLE, MALE AND FEMALE, 5 YEARS OLD, 20 POUNDS

CAPTAIN AND TENNILLE ARE BEING FOSTERED IN THE RICHMOND VA AREA. IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN THEM, PLEASE GO TO WWW.MOMSVA.ORG AND COMPLETE AN APPLICATION. 

These two are best friends and need to stay together in a home without small children.  It would be easier to keep them together because they keep each other entertained all day playing and then snuggle together all night.  Tennille is very shy and Captain helps her to be brave.  They are small in stature for beagles so the two of them basically make up one dog.  And really, two dogs are always better than one!  

Captain – estimated to be 5 but may be younger, about 20lbs
Captain is a funny, sweet, energetic, handsome little man.  He generally spends all day wrestling with Tennille.  He loves to snuggle with his beagle sister Tennille or with humans.  He gets very excited to go on walks; however, he is very vocal when he catches the trail of something or when he sees bicycles – his sworn enemies.  Walks with Captain can be a handful especially on a nice day.  He is very smart and learned how to sit for treats very quickly.  He’s very food motivated.  He has not shown food aggression unless there’s a special treat involved.  He does not seem to care for playing with toys but loves to chew/play with rocks (which explains his teeth).  Captain does well with dogs his own size up to large beagle size.  He growls and snaps at dogs larger than him while on a leash, but given time to work things out off-leash, he has gotten along with larger dogs.  Captain likes most people but he will growl at new people if they approach while he’s sitting with his favorite human.  He does have a very bad habit of eating poop and digging holes.  He’s quiet in his crate when left during the day and through the night.  He is about 90% house trained, just don’t make him wait too long to potty or he will go in the house.  Captain is pretty brave and is not scared of most sounds including thunder and fireworks and seems to be relatively unphased by the vacuum.  He’s a flight risk and needs to be watched around open doors and gates.  IMPORTANT: Captain does have a seizure disorder and takes medicine twice a day every day with a cost of $30 a month.  He will need this medication his entire life to control his seizures.  He has not had a seizure since starting the medication.


Tennille – estimated to be five but may be older, about 20lbs
Tennille is a happy, cute, pudgy little lady.  She loves all people, kids, other dogs, and even the one cat we met on a walk.  She gets SO excited when she sees someone, she does a little dance.  She generally spends all day wrestling with Captain or burying her stuffed toys. She does not like to cuddle or be held very long by a human.  However, she does love to snuggle with her beagle brother Captain.  She gets really excited to go on walks but she is very vocal when she sees squirrels or bunnies – her sworn enemies.  Otherwise, she walks very nicely on a leash.  She has not shown food aggression unless there is a special treat involved.  I have not been working with her on sit because she just naturally sits nicely and patiently for her treats or meals.  What a good girl!  She also has a bad habit of eating poop and dirt.  Tennille never had an accident in the house until we had long spans of rain so I’d say she’s about 90% house trained too.  Tennille is quiet in her crate while I leave the house and through the night.  She is pretty timid and is scared of inside house noises like the blender, vacuum, and plastic bags rustling.  She does not seem to be scared of thunder or fireworks.  She is also nervous/apprehensive when eating and going in and out of doors.  Most of the world scares Tennille but she remains a happy little dog.      


If you think you're a match to Captain and Tennille, please go to www.momsva.org and complete an application.

animal.description:
This is Jaguar!

Jaguar is sleek, and when he prowls he looks exactly like his namesake. Jag isn't always great meeting other dogs on leash, but has been in multiple play groups here and is a social guy! He's a hiking buddy, a snuggle partner, and a winery regular. Jaguar is 9 years old and weighs 69 lbs. He came to us from Baldwin Park Shelter on October 4th.

Jaguar went on a two-week Frosted Fling and is now in Foster with his Fling dad! It's pretty special when someone who has done multiple Frosted Flings comes back to foster a dog through to adoption, because they see how special the dog is. Jaguar is well-behaved, knows basic commands, and is perfectly potty trained, but what really makes him special is his sweet and silly personality.

His Foster Dad shares, "Jaguar is a sweet soul, who just wants a human he can love. This beautiful boy actually walks like a Jaguar, creeping along with an athletic stride, low to the ground, with his tail tucked down. And yet he's a total goofball - I think it's the Great Dane in him. Jag loves to play, sometimes throwing toys up in the air to himself, and he still gets the zoomies after his baths. It makes me laugh every time!

Jag initially acts a bit aloof with new humans. During our three-week foster, he seemed to prefer sleeping on his bed on the floor. Then on our last night together, he finally found the courage to jump onto my bed. He sheepishly fumbled his way up and looked around for approval before sprawling out for the night. He's as sensitive as he is loyal and he deserves to be with one lucky family for the rest of his life."

Looking for a devoted best pal? Apply to meet Jaguar: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

animal.description:
Meet Kodiak!

10-year-old Kodiak was surrendered to Baldwin Park Shelter by his family. We don't know why he ended up there, but right away we noticed he had hind end weakness and when you try to help him he says, "I can do it myself!" with his mouth and a big bark. The shelter's rescue coordinator reached out to say what a great dog Kodiak is, and we agree! Kodiak has liked every dog and cat he has met, and enjoys sleeping under the big pine tree in his play yard.

It's no wonder this sweet old man shares his name with a bear - Kodiak is as fuzzy as a grizzly and sounds a bit like one too! His back end is weak, but once he's up, he's up and ready to go! Kodiak loves to go on our weekly Frosted Fakers hikes. The volunteers who walk with Kodiak keep his hikes shorter, and he does great! If anything, it takes some negotiation to convince him it's time to stop walking and head back to the FFF van! He's perfect on leash, sticking close to his partner's side, never pulling, and occasionally checking in with a glance of his big soulful eyes.

We know that our big bear needs a special family with big hearts and no stairs, so we sent him on a two week Frosted Fling to see what else we could learn about him in a home environment. Kodiak earned rave reviews from his Fling Mom for being amazing with her five small dogs, including not even minding a bit when the tiniest one (3 lbs.) would walk over him! She also reported that Kodiak is potty trained and barks while standing at the door to let you know when he wants to go out. Our favorite bear is very mellow, enjoying slow strolls around the neighborhood, wandering around the yard, and taking naps.

Kodiak quickly learned to trust his Fling Mom and was a good boy about getting his eye drops and accepting her help if he needed it when getting up. He loves to eat and takes his medications easily. A fun fact about Kodiak is that he enjoys music! While with his Fling Family, he would gaze at their guitar and sit close when it was played.

We think Kodiak's Fling Mom summed it up perfectly when she reported, "Kodiak is seriously the best dog. He's the most gentle giant!" Please consider making him part of your family, he is so deserving!

Stop by to meet our special bear during the next Open House!

Visit during Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm

Learn more about our programs at: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family No adoption fees and we help with medical costs!

animal.description:
FCIA rescued Boris, a rottweiler mix, from the shelter after his previous owner surrendered him due to his medical needs.  He is 5 years old and weighs 82 pounds. He was suffering from chronic fungal and bacterial skin infections that had left him nearly bald, underweight,  and with severe ear infections. Despite this, he remained very sweet and loving.  After almost a year in our care that included intense and frequent medical tests and treatment, he is finally medically stabilized.  He is happy, healthy and his coat is full and lush.  Boris will require lifelong medication and routine vet checks.  He is now on thyroid meds 2 times a day, iron supplements daily, an autoimmune shot every 10 days, and a special diet that controls his allergies.  He remains sweet and loving and very playful with most other dogs .  He does tend to guard his yard and person so needs an adopter with Rottweiler experience and one who is prepared to continue his health routine.  

Boris is so ready and deserving of his forever home.  If you are that person, please contact us at FCIAadoptions@aol.com for more information.

As we are currently not having any adoption events, we are asking interested people to please fill out our application at www. FCIAnimals.org and if it looks like a good match, we will arrange an introduction. 

We suggest a home with children over the age of 10 for this dog. This dog cannot be adopted out of state. Please see our home page for a list of our Saturday adoption sites. Every potential adopter is required to fill out an adoption application and the dog is placed in the home that would be most suitable for the dog. We do not place our dogs in homes with unfenced swimming pools. Generally we don't release the dogs at the adoption site that day except on occasion to former adopters.

animal.description:
Jezzy was rather shy when she first came to the shelter, not sure what to think of the place and everyone here. After her owner had to surrender her, she was lonely and sad. Now, after some time, she is coming around! She loves to play, chasing balls in the yard, and zoom zoom zoom to get all her energy out. She loves human attention and would prefer to be able to keep all her humans to herself so she doesn't have to share time and space with other animals. Jezzy is a smart dog that is very food driven and will be easy to train. ----
Please call the shelter at (706) 795-2868 to schedule a meet and greet. Madison Oglethorpe Animal Shelter is a non-profit shelter serving over 720 square miles. We are open intake, meaning we can not turn away animals from either county we serve. Our shelter intakes double or triple it's capacity every month so it is essential we place animals quickly into adoptive homes. Since so many animals enter the shelter we often don't have enough volunteers to write an individual bio for each. Please feel free to call the shelter Wednesday-Sunday to inquire about the animal you are interested in. 706-795-2868. Viewing and adoption hours at our shelter are Wednesday through Sunday from 12 PM to 5 PM. All adoption fees include age-appropriate vaccinations, flea treatment, deworming, and spay or neuter, microchip, and adoption packet. Fees: Dogs over 4 months old: $100 Puppies under 4 months: $125. Cats and Kittens are $75 ($65 without microchip). For your convenience you can fill out an adoption application for any of our current residents at www.moaspets.com. Join us on Facebook at https://www.facebook.com/moaspets. It's a great way to stay up to the minute on the furry 4 legged friends we have looking for a loving forever home. We are located at: 1888 Colbert Danielsville Rd Danielsville, GA 30633 706-795-2868 NOTE: Our adoptions are first come first served, simply filling out an application does not mean the animal will be held for you, you must come meet the animal in person in order to be considered for adoption. If you rent you must bring your lease or a letter from your landlord stating you may adopt.

animal.description:
IMPORTANT: Please do not do an inquiry through Petfinder, our volunteers do not have time to reply to the inquiries. Please visit our website to learn more about our adoption process at newhoperescue.org. 

This dog is being fostered with New Hope Dog Rescue (Saskatoon).  If you are interested in adopting please fill out an Adoption Application. Meet and greets are by appointment only and done so after an adoption application has been submitted. A successful applications will be contacted by the foster home to discuss further. We are volunteer run so please be patient.

Hi, my name is Nova and I'm a pretty shy girl. I am just over 1 year old and I am a mixed breed. At my last vet appointment I weighed 21 kg. 

Once I get to know you we can be best friends. I'm the happiest girl once I've settled in and my whole body wags with my tail. In my foster home my best friend is another dog named Willow. We love to wrestle and play.

During the day, I can be crated and I like my wire crate that i can see out of. I absolutely shouldn’t be left out of my crate when you can’t watch me as I can get into things, I am still a young dog so I am still learning! 

Nova will need a patient home to work with her nervousness. Older kids who can respect her boundaries and give her time to bond would be best. If the house has another dog, the dog must be fairly calm and friendly. She is a sweet girl who needs a home to give her time to adjust, she’ll be your best friend within a few days!

Nova has been spayed, microchipped, dewormed, current on age appropriate vaccines and has received a health check from a vet. adoption fee is $295.

To view more dogs go to http://www.newhoperescue.org/adopt/available-dogs/

Disclaimer: in most cases we are guessing the breed mix. These are best guesses on our part. For puppies it can be extremely difficult and we are also guessing on what size they will be. 

NEW HOPE DOG RESCUE is not a shelter. Our dogs are placed in loving foster homes. WE NEED FOSTER HOMES TO HELP MORE DOGS - CONTACT US TODAY!!!
Definitions:
Pending - means that we are working through the adoption process with the 1st applicant. We usually don't add the pending until we are pretty sure the adoption will go through (like at the home visit stage)
Adopted - you know!! A happy ending for a homeless dog.

animal.description:
Everybody loves Raymond...and Raymond loves everybody!! Meet the world's cuddliest senior puppy around. He is such a friendly soul that he actually jumped  in the UPS drivers' van once! Raymond is very social and enjoys attending every birthday party available :) 

Raymond is wonderful with the little kiddos, and his foster sisters include a 5 year old and 3 year old girls. He enjoys being a part of  the action, even if that means he has to play dress up! He has been known to steal a few Dinonuggets from time to time. 

Ray is a stage 4 clinger, and has to be next to you pretty much half of the day! He loves to give kisses as well, although his old man breath makes it very enduring :) Ray loves to stay close to you outside as well, and frequently has to be bribed into going outside in the snow. 

He seems a bit excitable toward kittens, and he is not a fan of those big creatures they call horses, but Raymond would most likely do well in a home with another calm senior dog like himself. 

If you're looking for good laugh, a good hug and a great friend - look no further than Raymond!

animal.description:
Hey Ya'll I'm Chuck, aka Chucky-Boooooyyyyy!!! My friends here tend to refer to me as a speedy ball of muscle, and they are always begging me to slow down so we can snuggle, sometimes I let them, I'm such a tease!   I am hoping to find someone to love me that has the ability to reign in and help me drain my 1 year old puppy energy and curiosity.  I'm working on being patient in my crate, I just get so bored after a few hours, and I really work hard to let you know when I have to go potty when we are chillin at home.   I don't love being tied outside the house unattended, I do best when my people are with me so I feel safe and I don't have to bark at the people walking by.  See, sometimes new people can be concerning to me so I'm also hoping my people will be cautious as I learn to be more confident in new situations, I promise I mean well and I just need to know how to react appropriately.   My friends at the shelter always tell me how darn cute I am and that I am the most entertaining dog they have ever met so if you are an active person who is looking for someone to rock and roll with I'm your guy!!  
You can find an application on our website www.whsadopt.org, and once that is approved our adoption team will be in touch so we can hang out!  www.whsadopt.org, click on adopt, then dog adoption questionnaire.

Hazel is about 2 years old and her breed is somewhat of a mystery (your guess is as good as ours).  Hazel is a sweet girl and LOVES people.  That being said, she is incredibly smart and will need owners committed to keeping up on training.  Her foster says she is too smart for her own good. She would also to best in a home with kids 8 and up as if they run she likes to herd them as well and may try tip nip at their heels.  She is a perfect sized dog at only 45 pounds.

Hazel's adoption fee has been partially sponsored in hopes of finding her a home and is only $100, which includes all her vet work.

animal.description:
Max is 6 years young and currently in a loving home. He's been with his family for a couple of years, but from the start they always knew that Max would be better suited for a life with someone more active with the time, ability and interest in hanging with a really cool, playful and intelligent dog. He loves walks, sunbathing, belly rubs and playing ball.
A couple of years ago he had surgery, leaving a pin in one of his hind legs, but it doesn't slow him down a bit; just something to be aware of when exercising. Max is great with other dogs, though best to keep toys (especially balls) out of play as he tends to resource guard.With training the issue is gradually improving, so his new owner will need to commit to working through that process.
If he's going to live with another dog, a confident female would be ideal (he's currently and temporarily living with a female pittie).
We don't recommend Max live with a family with young children, though he shows no sign of aggression with humans, even around the ball, he is an exuberant greeter and player, best suited for those who can match his powerful energy.
Max goes out on 'doggie adventures' multiple times a week. He knows all the basic commands, as well as some of the tougher stuff necessary for dogs to know when out on the streets. He walks great on leash, though gets pretty pumped when encountering other dogs, easily managed by a dog-savvy walker. With consistency, and a positive approach, Max can take on anything. He's a co-pilot kind of dog, happy and lovable, especially when he's guided along the journey and confident of his expectations.
Adopt Max and he'll come with all the training support you need from Diamond Dogs in the Ruff. Jason has been coaching Max for the past few months and is committed to finding the perfect forever home for the guy, and doing whatever it takes to ensure a smooth transition and happy life for Max and his new best friend(s).
Max was born approximately 10/2013 and weighs 68lbs
Max is fully vetted, neutered, HW neg, vaccinated, dewormed and microchipped
Adoption Fee for Max is $50
Watch Max's video to learn more about him! https://drive.google.com/file/d/17Ha-rQMze3HfBCgHO-_bn4-Whc_VCtCV/view?usp=sharing

PLEASE READ ALL THE INFORMATION IN THE DOG'S PROFILE, AS WELL AS THE INFORMATION ON OUR WEBSITE, niagaradogrescue.com , BEFORE EMAILING US WITH QUESTIONS. OUR VOLUNTEERS USE UP VALUABLE TIME ANSWERING QUESTIONS WHERE THE ANSWERS ARE READILY AVAILABLE ON THE WEBSITE.WE ARE FOSTER BASED, THEREFORE WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY.  MEETS WILL NOT BE ARRANGED UNTIL ADOPTION APPLICATIONS APPROVED. IT CAN TAKE 10-14 DAYS FOR AN ADOPTION LEAD TO RESPOND TO YOUR APPLICATION. PLEASE BE PATIENT.Thank you!!!
	
Please visit our website @ https://www.niagaradogrescue.com/ or apply for adoption @ https://niagaradogrescue.com/adoption/.  

Name: Miss Bull
Weight: 60 lbs
Age: 3 years
Gender: spayed female
Breed: American Bulldog/pointer mix
Color(s): White/black

Good with adults: yes
Good with kids; yes, 10 and up as she is playful and stocky build
Good with other dogs: has lived with other dogs she was slowly introduced to (2 females/1 male) , no dog parks for her
Good with cats: Unknown, but I would guess no
House-trained: Yes if let out regularly.
Crate trained: Not a fan of the crate
Energy level: medium
Can be handled/touched: Yes
Barker: can be if left alone too long
Flight risk: unknown
Food aggressive: possibly. Have seen her protect her food and keep others from eating
Good on a leash: yes, but pulls at first from excitement
Rides well in a car: yes
Destructive: No
Needs a home with a yard: Yes, loves outside.
Needs another dog: NO, loves attention and loves to sleep with her human. She will lay on top of you to show her love. Best as a ONLY dog.
Can live in an apartment: No

Backstory: Miss Bull was brought into a high kill shelter as a stray. She had been hit by a car and was very underweight. She was released to be euthanized and saved by the rescue.

Foster comments: Miss Bull knows her name. She is very loyal to her human to a fault. Someone who works from home and wants a true companion would be a great match for her. She LOVES to chew bones so keeping those available to her is recommended. She is very trainable and eager to please. She will give her heart so needs an adopter who will also give her their heart. She LOVES people.

Foster update: Are you ok not to use a crate … because all she wants is love … to let your dog on the couch .. because all she wants is to cuddle … to sleep with you because all she wants is more love? And in return get a fully housetrained, loving, respectful, non-barker, a dog that loves going for walks, going in the car, kids and dogs? Then Miss Bull is for you. She is a 60 pound very solid, very strong American Bulldog mix that is a gentle love bug. She needs someone who will be strong enough to walk her because she’ll pull you along, but she is smart enough to eventually learn to slow down. Anyone with a good heart and a loving nature will be lucky to adopt Miss Bull.

Rozar will of course be going to a vet to be thoroughly examined and the road to recovery has begun. He will be getting fed a lot of smaller meals to help him gain weight correctly. In the meantime, his foster family will be loving him, caring for him and helping him get well before they begin working with him on any house manners he may need. Rozar's journey has just begun - are you his happy ending?

animal.description:
Introducing is absolutely gorgeous girl named Pandora! This super sweet girl did not have an easy start in life. She was used for breeding and was likely not treated very well. She managed to liberate herself and was picked up by a wonderful animal lover who found her roaming. Every effort was made to contact her previous owners however nothing came to fruition. So, fortunately for her, she was free to find a much better life! Our organization was contacted as we have experience with this breed, and everyone wanted to ensure that she find a home that was absolutely perfect for her, and will cherish her always!
She was immediately taken to a vet where she was estimated to be about four years old. We had all of her vaccines done and had all of her medical work completed including spay. She was given a clean bill of health and she weighs about 100 pounds. She went to her foster home where she slowly showed them that she is truly an incredible, wise old soul. she is exceptionally intelligent, and equally as loyal. When she knows that you are her parents and will truly love her, she will be your Velcro dog for life. She has probably spent every day longing to finally have someone who would love her, and reciprocate to her the devotion she had been longing to give and receive. 
Pandora should go to a home that has similar breed experience. She has not displayed overly protective behaviors, but it is absolutely possible that once she is settled into her forever home that she might. Therefore, parents who are confident with an extra large protective dog are a must! The other must is parents who absolutely want to snuggle with her dog as much as possible! She is the type of girl who will mosey on right next to you when you’re walking around in the yard or doing anything in the house. She will be sure to follow you, longing to be as close to as possible as well as making sure you’re always OK. She is exceptionally devoted, and has such a pure heart of gold. She will do better in a more reclusive setting, where she can watch the birds and there’s lots of trees and yard space. She’s more of a country dog who likes to relax and have an easy-going lifestyle. A low traffic home with relaxed, nurturing, confident, loving parents is her dream come true! She would probably be best as an only dog, however she could live happily with a mature mellow similar large male companion dog as well. Interestingly, she has shown no reactivity to cats at all! Given the opportunity, she would rather curl up with you on a couch than chase a cat! Her foster parents have grown to love her deeply and see what an incredible dog she is. She is a girl who is for people who want an incredible connection with her dog, who understand dogs, and can respect and adore everything about her. She has paid her dues being bred and bred her entire life. It is time for her to relax in a warm soft loving home, where she can feel peace, security, and the connection with parents she has always longed for. If this girl has touched your heart and he would love to make her dream come true and welcome her into your home please visit our website and submitted application for adoption today! www.greatdivideanimalrescue.org

Zeus has come back to us. After a little over a year of being with a very loving family, he just wasn't jiving well with the other dogs and family anymore. Anxiety seemed to be a huge issue for him. It took finding the right type of meds, but it seems like Zeus is coming around. Zeus is finally able to be a dog. He has life in his eyes now and is happy. Now that he can finally relax, Zeus loves to enjoy all the things he couldn't before like people, food, and drinking from the toilet. Zeus's fear of new people has also lessened. Zeus can still be stubborn, but he is working on it with his foster and we are seeking further training to help Zeus to become an even better dog. 

Zeus is up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, and neutered. His adoption fee is $200.

If you are interested in meeting Zeus or learning more about the adoption process, please submit an adoption application at careforanimals.org. Thank you!

animal.description:
Pia is considered special needs as she is diabetic and requires insulin and prescription food.

Pia is our sweet senior chihuahua.  She is about 8 years (possibly older) young.  Crate- trained and Potty-trained (outdoor and will use wee wee)!  Likes dogs and ignores cats.
 Pia was out of time when FWFP stepped in. 

Interested in becoming a forever home for Pia? Fill out our online adoption application: http://www.friendswithfourpaws.org/adoption-form.html This is the first step in our process, and we don't go any further without an application.

Find more adoptable pets, news and information on Instagram @friendswithfourpaws or our Facebook page Friends with Four Paws .

We put a lot of time and energy into processing our adoptions to find our babies the best fit home for them and you.  Please do not submit an application if you are not serious about adopting Pia.
We are so excited to work with you to find you a new forever friend, and Pia the perfect forever home, and appreciate you working with us.  
For immediate consideration, please attach your application to the initial inquiry to help us expedite the process.

Our adoption fee is $475. This includes their spay/neuter surgery, full (age appropriate) vaccinations, microchip insertion and registration, deworming, heartworm testing and prevention, flea and tick prevention and travel expenses.

All of our dogs are rescued from local shelters and the general public. Each dog is then placed in a foster home where he/she is kept for quarantine, to ensure if the dog gets sick it can receive proper treatment. We have foster homes in the NJ/NY area waiting to receive their fosters. Once an animal has received an application or there's an adopter interested, we make arrangements for transport. If a dog is already in foster care in NYC/NJ, an adopter will be put in touch with the foster home AFTER an application is being processed.

Thank you in advance for your patience with our process and for making adoption YOUR option!

animal.description:
Genny is a young lady, between 1 and 2 years old, is up to date on all her vaccines and spayed plus already started on monthly heartworm preventative. She has some issues with being kenneled and crated meaning she does not make a good first impression inside so an experienced dog owner is required to help her adjust. She craves attention once she’s out and is very playful and energetic.  She wants you to think she is a tough girl but open her kennel door and see her real personality!! Genny is bouncy, playful, and LOVES attention!! She also enjoys walks and passing out kisses!  Genny does well with male dogs but a home with older children and NO CATS is recommended. If you can provide Genny with the loving home she is waiting for email below! 

FOR ADOPTERS: please contact Kelly, our Adoption Coordinator, with any questions at taylorcodogs@gmail.com or inquire directly via Petfinder. There is a link to our online ADOPTION APPLICATION on our Petfinder home page. You may also request an application via email. Paper copies are available at our shelter.
We always recommend a meet and greet with our dogs available for adoption. We are not able to assess dogs with cats since we are set up for dog intakes only. If you have cats, we advise a proper introduction while keeping the dog on leash in your home.
We are volunteer-based, so please be patient with our response time.

FOR RESCUES: Taylor County is rescue friendly! If you are a rescue, please contact our Rescue Coordinator, Diana, at deed1123@aol.com

DONATIONS: We are always in need of donations to help care for our dogs. We feed IAMS Adult Mini Chunks (green bag) and IAMS Smart Puppy. If you can assist financially, please mail a check payable to Taylor County Humane Society at PO Box 4045, Grafton WV 26354 or visit our website to donate via PayPal. http://www.tchswv.com/donations/

animal.description: Roo was rescued from a hoarding situation outside of Wichita. She was pregnant and due soon after. She has since had her pups and they were weaned recently and she was able to go into foster with other dogs and cats. She is a petitle little girl. She is getting "house dog life figured out. She can be spotted in the back of every activity now. (She's bringing up the end of the love bug couch train). Her first vet experience went as expected..she was terrified but handled it as well as a feral dog can. She's an awful car rider. She is a very particular treat taker, no fruits and veggies so far just meat. She is still being leashed inside and outside but is less frantic when approached. Roo currently has no interest in lovins or animal interactions but she is starting to be very interested in EVERYTHING going on. She accepts .2 seconds of pets then scurries off, then returns .5 seconds later to give very sloppy licks and scurries back off but it's something. We love her and can't wait to see what her personality brings. Fingers crossed

animal.description:
Ready for a sugar high?! I'm Sugar, the sweetest girl around. As you can see by the smile on my face, I love people SO MUCH. My favorite thing in the world is getting pets (especially on my belly!) and giving kisses. Other favorite things include cuddles, bones and deer antlers. 

At 44lbs, I'm a young and adorable pocket pitty. I'm the perfect size to sit with you on the sofa and sleep beside you in your big bed because we can cuddle and I won't take up too much room. I love meeting new people and getting lots of attention. I'm happiest when I'm with my people, so a family or owner who wants to take me on walks and adventures would be awesome! I would loooove a family with kids who enjoy playing and cuddling. Although I'm petite, I do get excited when around people, so kids over five might be best so I don't accidentally knock anyone over!

I have some separation anxiety, so a patient owner who can help me gain confidence and trust will be a great fit for me. I am a smart girl and I catch on easily! I can be dog-selective, so let's do a slow meet and greet to make sure I'm a perfect fit in your pack. TLP can help! (I'd also enjoy being the only dog in your life because I would then get ALLLLL the attention!) No cats for me, please.

Do you love kisses and smiles and cute snorts and the kind of adoration only a dog can show? I will be your best gal and can't wait to share my love with you. Apply to meet me today!

animal.description:
11/2/2020
Shippensburg is looking for an understanding family that wants to love him and enjoy his company for however long they can have a nice life together.  Shippensburg has degenerative Myelopathy --It is an incurable disease and is progressive. Shippensburg really wants a family of his own for as long as he may have (could be months could be years--it is unknown but we do know he is a love and deserves a family of his own).  To make this happen for him, his adoption fee is being covered by our Angel fund so that he can be adopted to an approve family that is a good fit for him.  Are you that special family?

10/24/2020
Shippensburg is doing well in foster.  He is not recommended for cats, small dogs or small children as he is not as aware of his size as he would need to be.   
10/6/2020

Shippensburg is an approximately 2 year old 66 lb Newfie mix who could stand to gain some weight.  He is Heart worm positive and will be heartworm treated at a Wags designated Vet.  He can be adopted prior to HW treatment.  
!!! Meet Shippensburg, AKA ‘Shippy’!!  This gentle mini giant deserves so much more than he has been given in life so far. Shippy did once belong to an owner down south, however he was left behind in the house once the owner moved out and just decided to let this sweet soul fend for himself.  The new owners of the home did not want a dog, and so this loveable ball of fluff was brought to the shelter.  He is listed as a ‘Bully Breed”, so adopters would need to meet that criteria, but he is the farthest thing from a bully.
Although he had clearly been neglected and malnourished, this beautiful fella has not let that stop him from being an absolute sweetheart or lose his trust in people.  He has likely never slept on a dog bed before, and so for now he prefers the floor to a crate or soft bed.  His foster mom has an Xpen set up connected to an open crate, and Shippy will just lay down quietly in the Xpen portion and sleep on some blankets.  He never makes a peep.  That could change as he gets more familiar with his surroundings, but so far he is a very quiet dog.  He also has done very well with house training, and has only had one oopsie in his foster home.
Shippy needs to put on some weight….don’t let his pictures fool you! He is all head and fur right now.  He is currently approximately  65-70 lb, but you can still feel his ribs and hips through his fur.  He eats well and has not shown any food aggression, which is amazing considering he was probably starving in his old ‘home’.  He is learning that treats are AWESOME and will follow you around if he thinks there’s a treat involved. (He loves cheese, Dentasticks, and Pepperidge Farm goldfish )  ?
He will pull on the leash a bit when walking, but certainly not enough to drag you down the street.  It seems as though he just really likes being outside and wants to explore.  He would do best with a fenced in yard, so that he can roam around and have some freedom.  He also has trouble walking on hardwood and/or laminate, (picture a deer on ice) so a home with carpeted rooms or area rugs/runners would be ideal. His foster parents currently have hardwood stairs to go up to the second floor, and he does not even want to attempt them.
Shippy has been around many dogs and has done great with all of them.  Slow intro’s are always best with any dog, but this guy seems more interested in his surroundings than interacting or playing with other dogs.  Again, that could change once he feels more settled in a secure new place.  Unknown how he is with cats, but he is interested in squirrels during his walks, so he might chase.
He might pace around the first few days, which is not uncommon with the stress of moving from place to place.  But after he feels safe and understands that he won’t just be left alone in a dark home by himself ever again, Shippy warms up quickly and is very affectionate.  He’s even starting to sit on his foster mom, a very clear sign that he is ready for a forever home where he will be spoiled with lots of walks, kisses, brushing, TREATS, and love. And a drool rag. ? 

Shippy is heartworm positive and begins his treatment soon. He will need restricted activity for a period of time afterwards.



  To begin the adoption process please, fill out our online application. Go to wagsrescue.com and click on adoption form.
Please call Susan @ 267-312-3372 if you have questions.

animal.description:
This sweetie is Darla, and she is ready to find a family to be her everything! She is 2-3 years old and about 40 lbs with short legs and a big smile! 
Darla is treat motivated and will sit patiently for a snack. She loves to hug you, cuddle, and give you kisses! 
She came to Take Paws pregnant, neglected, and heartworm positive. Now that her puppies are weaned and all in forever homes, she has completed her heartworm treatment and will be spayed soon. 
Darla is house trained and crate trained. She has not lived with a cat before, and says she wants all your love to herself - no other doggos please. She is great with all people and kids!
She’s a bit greedy, with your love and with her food! She loves to eat! She will follow you everywhere and sit when told.
She’s super excited though about the possibility of joining your family! We think she’d even love to have some small humans around to love on! 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

* SPECIAL NEEDS - PARALYZED BACK END *
Several weeks ago, Satchel's got a call from a neighboring county shelter about a sweet girl in need. Poppie is guessed to be about a 6 year old terrier mix and is paralyzed from the waist down. We aren't sure what caused her injury but it's not stopping her. Since her arrival at Satchel's, Poppie has caught the eye of volunteers and staff who are always there to support her special need. In the first month of her arrival she has been given her personal wheelchair, stroller, car seat, drag bag and has a massage therapist making visits. Poppie is a vibrant social girl who loves spending time with her human companions. She is very treat motivated with one of her favorite treats being the homemade frozen peanut butter yogurt treats she gets from her favorite volunteer. Poppie seems to be okay with some dogs and could possibly live with a cat. Poppie's perfect home would be with someone who spends a lot of time at home and sees her abilities, not her disability.

animal.description:
Welcome to the Wonderful World of Rescue Dachshunds. Look around and read their bios. Find a few whose personality seems to fit well. Consider one of our Well Seasoned Seniors who are truly wonderful and have so much to offer. Need help finding the best fit? We'll help with that too. Please fill out an application and let's get you all matched up with a loving new "furever' companion and friend. You'll find the application on the "Available Dogs" page.

NOTE:

Adoptions to Central/South Texas residents only

Standard Adoption Fee Adult Dog: $250 ea. Puppy Adoption Fee: $300 ea. Reduced rates for Seniors dogs (10 and up). Reduced rates for pairs (when adopted together). All adoption fees are subject to sales tax per the State of Texas. DDRTX only adopts in Central/South Texas.

Email: ddrtxinfo@gmail.com Primary Website: www.DDRTX.org
Pioneer Puppy #6 - Teagan is momma
Hello folks my name is Marie Curie. And I have been in Rescue since I was born and I am a very mature six months old. I was part of Pioneer Puppies and have been with the same foster family since I was a baby.

I have never gotten my very own forever home but foster mom keeps telling me that I'm going to one day. I've just recently had a new photo shoot. And you can tell that even though I don't have short legs and down ears, and they don't call me a Dachshund...I am a small, dainty, trim and frankly very pretty little girl dog. My mother was a small dog weighing around 20 pounds. My foster mom tells me I'm not going to be any bigger than my mama.

Marie Has learned so much in the last six months. She has become housetrained. She has learned to sleep quietly on her own bed in the bedroom overnight. She can be kenneled easily for errands. She has a sweet nature once she meets and learns she can trust you. She gives sweet kisses and can lay quietly in your lap. Marie rides well in the car snapped in on her own seat. She has been visiting the creek, park playground, the pet store, vet and even went to the local brewery recently. She walks well on a leash and lays and/or sits quietly very near you when you sit to visit with friends.

Marie can be shy at first and has a little fear when out of her comfort zone. Being young and with our social restrictions its been hard for her to become more social. But at home in her environment she is outgoing and loving. She just needs a forever home with patient folks that she can give her heart to. She is good with children. And she loves to chase a ball or a stick outside in her yard. She is very content to spend time outside in the yard.

Marie is hoping someone will fall in love with her soon. She has been black but is now changing colors. She has a beautiful silver white hair coloring along her neck. Marie used to be the ugly duckling but not anymore. She is truly unique and a one of a kind dog. Please don't miss out on her!

Love dachshunds and not ready to adopt or circumstances won't permit having a dog? How about being a sponsor or making a donation. Every one of our dachshunds receives excellent medical care along with day to day food, love and housing. Being non-profit, we rely on generous individuals like yourselves to help save these fur babies. You can do this specifically for one dog with the sponsor button on their webpage or a general donation on our "How To Help" page. Easy and quick through Pay Pal or your debit/credit card. You generosity is sincerely appreciated by all and is tax deductable. Need other ideas? You'll find tons of them on the How to Help tab. All contributions are tax deductable.

Diamond Dachshund Rescue of Texas is a non-profit 501(c)(3) volunteer organization with focus on rescue and adoption of pure breed Dachshunds. All dogs are fully vetted and housed on private property. Meetings are scheduled upon adoption approval. Thank you for your continued support to the rescue and shelter communities!
Opt to Adopt!

animal.description:
Rowena is a 5ish year old small lab / maybe beagle mix -- about 50 lbs. She is house/kennel trained, and definitely wants to learn how to dog! She was found in 2019 living in a wood pile in Oklahoma protecting her puppies, so has some trauma there that needs worked through and a dedicated adopter will do so much for her. She needs a very structured living environment and a strong dog-savvy owner. She loves to be outside so would enjoy a nice physically fenced yard (no invisible fencing with her history, sorry). She will not do well in an apartment setting since she has a fear of strangers and needs muzzled on walks in strange places. She has been through heartworm treatment and will require an adopter who will keep her on preventatives and regular testing. She does well with dogs as long as they aren't tiny/can't be mistaken for squirrels or rabbits. She chases cats. She is food protective with other dogs, so will need to be fed separate / in kennel as a precaution. Once she is comfortable with you, she likes to snuggle and give kisses and hugs -- but it may take a few weeks for her to warm up fully. No kids for Roe -- fast movements and small creatures with her don't mix, sorry. Her adoption fee is $250. If you have an easy-going and patient lifestyle that will give this girl the structure she needs and are interested in meeting Rowena, please put an application in at www.foreverhomedogs.org and we will set up a meet with you!All adoptions are $200 per dog which include spay/neuter, micro-chipped and up-to-date on required shots. 

Senior dogs, at our discretion, are adopted out at $100 per dog because we know they will have less time with your family and may eventually have more needs as they get older. But we feel these dogs deserve to live out the rest of their lives as part of a loving family.

Despite his size, he still has a lot of pep in his step! He may need a few lessons in "basic training" to become his very best, but is a good-natured kind of guy. Will he walk pretty well beside you? Dipz is also a cute guy with dark spots splashed across his coat! He is currently in a foster home, so please contact the shelter if you are interested in meeting him. We hope you’ll meet our happy boy, Dipz! He will welcome you with open paws!

ID# A072459

We APPRECIATE you for considering adopting a shelter pet. We are open Monday-Saturday, 10:00 am to 4:45 pm (closed Sundays and major holidays). The adoption fee is $40.99 ($30 + $10.99 microchip kit), which includes spaying/neutering, microchip, deworming, initial vaccinations, and a voucher for a wellness check at a local vet clinic. A rabies vaccination is not included. We do not run a heartworm test unless by request. Upon adoption, your new pet will be scheduled with Angelina Animal Hospital for its required spay/neuter surgery and microchip implant. You may pick up your new pet directly from the vet's office (average wait time is 1-3 days post adoption). The surgery must be completed before pick up.  Feel free to call the shelter or email us with any questions.
“Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.”
