Meet Bella! This cute Pittie mix is estimated to be a little under a year old and around 40lbs. Bella  was rescued off the streets of Texas, not much is known about her past prior to her rescue. After being fostered down in Texas while she healed she came up to RED September 25, 2020 as a medical rescue She  is currently in foster care in Poulsbo where she is working on her basic obedience, leash skills and crate training. 

In playgroup Bella has been around multiple dogs, she can be pushy so would need a dog friend who is tolerant of that. Bellawould do best in an adult only home or home with older children (13+) that can focus on her training and provide her structure. She required a fully fenced yard with a visible fence. 

If you are interested in meeting Bella please fill out an application here: http://www.rescueeverydog.org/Adoption.php
Answers to the application can be emailed, or sent via message on Facebook. 

Please note, Bella is in foster care in Poulsbo, WA and meet and greets will take place in Poulsbo as well. 


Mandatory fenced yard. No apartments. Some Condos and homes with a private use fenced yard maybe considered. No children under 9 years of age. Adoption donation for this companion animal is $450. Donations cover some of the care costs for R.E.D. animals. Like housing, supportive care, medical needs and food. All R.E.D. animals are spayed or neutered and vaccinated. Most are micro chipped with adopter registration included. R.E.D. is a 501 C3 and all donations support our life saving missions. For more information and to complete the on line adoption application on R.E.D., please, see our website at www.rescueeverydog.org. 
PLEASE READ ALL OF THE FOLLOWING TO APPLY TO ADOPT: Not all applicants will be approved for requested animals. R.E.D. reserves the right to refuse service and adoption without explanation. R.E.D. is the companion animal's advocate and will select the most suitably matched home/environment for the the companion animals emotional needs and management requirements based on each companion animal's breed(s) general needs and the unique needs of each individual animal in our care. R.E.D. requires all applicants and adopters to conduct themselves in a respectful and courteous manner. R.E.D. updates it animals adoption postings daily. If you wish to apply to adopt this companion animal go to the on line application at R.E.D.'s website www.rescueeverydog.org. and look under adoption. Before applying, please, read the following information. 
(1) Application, Phone interview, Home visit are required. Adoption Donations are generally $350.00. to 800.00 or as posted. Donations support R.E.D.'s life saving missions and medical and other care given.(2) R.E.D. Dogs are spayed or neutered prior to adoption, vaccinated for Parvo Distemper and generally are micro chipped. (3) You must be at least 18 years of age to complete the application or to apply to adopt a companion animal. For the safety of children and dogs and limited information on dog the dogs interaction with children- R.E.D generally prefers/requires children in adoptive home to be approximately 5 or 6 years of age and up unless otherwise noted in the dog profile. All children must be behavior appropriate with animals. (4) R.E.D. does not a ship animals to out of state adopters. Out of state adopters must come to meet the animal in person in Washington if approved for a meet and greet with a R.E.D. companion animal. Thank you.

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

MEET BETHESDA!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show. We have been told that you can go straight to the shelter and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog. From what we understand, the shelter will squeeze you in except between 12-3PM and near the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog. We hope your adoption process is smooth and full of happiness!

This amazing pup is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4471829.

Bethesda is a shy and scared girl. The shelter staff is working with her and she is improving, however, she still needs improvement. Bethesda won't walk on a leash and thrashes about when she is leashed. The kennel staff put her in a building close to a play yard and she will walk to the yard without a leash. She is still hesitant around the staff in the yard but they did find that Bethesda is very treat motivated. The last time the staff worked with her, they were able to get her leashed while rewarding her with treats.

Bethesda was brought to the shelter because she bit a person in the leg while they were skateboarding. She cannot go to a home with children. She is going to need a patient adopter that understands her behavior and can provide the obedience training that she needs. She is a young girl at a year old and has a long life ahead of her if given the chance. At her age, she can be taught the behavior she needs to be a pet in a home. If you're the person that can give her that chance, come and meet Bethesda today!

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

animal.description:
This senior guy has a story to tell. Kodi was literally dumped out of a car at night on I 95. The fact that he is alive is a miracle in itself if you've ever driven that thruway. He ran off but after multiple attempts over the next couple of days was able to be caught. We were asked to help him which of course we did. Kodi was clearly neglected in his previous home. He tested positive for 2 tick borne diseases which have been treated and for heartworm disease for which he likewise finished the treatment. It's all behind him now!

?Kodi LOVED car rides, hanging with humans, attending barbecues with friends of his foster and was a super friendly boy. He always wore a smile on that sweet face. Kodi was fabulous on leash, a total gentleman. 

Kodi was adopted but returned the next week for behaviors we hadn't seen in all the months he was with us for his vetting needs. Kodi presented with threatening body language toward the adopter's company and on leash when encountering strangers with or without dogs. We had explained upfront to give him time to bond before introducing new people, basically the 'two week shutdown' for adjustment which we ask all our adopters, and they in fact didn't do that, but still, it was so uncharacteristic of him. We were stumped but were fortunate to have him spend time in foster care in the home of trainers, Misguided Mutts Dog Behavior Training, who are also good friends of ours. We no longer felt like we knew this boy. What was going on?. 

?Well, as we suspected would happen, we again saw the sweet Kodi we knew and loved. After a one week transition period to earn his trust, they began to introduce visitors. Kodi was slightly distrustful at first, but a quick verbal cue and he relaxed. Next came a walk where he would be immersed in an environment with triggers for them to observe any reactivity as seen by the adopter. Here are their exact words:

"He did great. The park was crazy busy. He was a gentleman on leash, walked past dogs and people fine. The one thing I noticed is that he got a little cautious when he was positioned on the side of the people but I just coached him along. No reactions at all. He saw doodles, a German Shepherd, two Rotties. Then we went to Starbucks to get him a pup cup and he didn't react at all then either even with the two ladies gushing over him at the drive thru. It's really fun to watch how young and carefree he acts or how he just wants to laydown, chill, and take in the sun"

So here is our conclusion of his needs in an adoptive home!

1. Kodi needs time to develop trust in his new family during an adjustment period. He is a submissive, moderately fearful boy until he has time to feel comfortable. Then, you can't contain his joy and capacity to love.

2. After the adjustment, initially, his new family will need to be cognizant of his expression and body language which may be subtle. A quick verbal to him because of the trust that was built prior will give him confidence that everything is okay. 

3.His new family must be sufficiently experienced in that they will recognize this sweetheart is just afraid, not mean.

4. Kodi will take advantage of a gap in fencing or a gap under the fence between the ground and bottom of the fencing. He has been known to squeeze through the space where the fence gate attaches to the fencing. He has not challenged a privacy fence that does not have the 2 prior escape routes.

5. Kodi is fearful of sticks. Brooms as well. If you pick a stick up to play fetch, he will cower. It seems he may have been abused as well as neglected.

If you feel that you can provide this senior, who has experienced nothing but neglect up to his being thrown out of that car on I 95, and then misunderstood by his adopter, with the loving home he deserves, please submit our application. Some patient, understanding person will be very lucky to enjoy Kodi's loyalty and playful, fun personality. 

**If you are serious about adopting , you must head to our website at www.kodisclub.org and submit a completed application. There are also additional photos!  We will not do anything without an app. Due to the small size of our volunteer-run rescue, only the approved adopter may be contacted. It is not first come first served, but the best match **

Sara - Beagle/Hound Mix - Female - 13 Years - www.twyla.org

If you'd like to know more about this dog please visit our website at www.Twyla.org

My name is Sara, &  I was adopted almost 13 years ago from Twyla's Friends.. My  Owner passed away, & now I'm back to Twyla's Friends in search of a loving family that will take care of me until my days are done on this Earth.. The lump you see on the side of my shoulder is a fatty tumor, so it's not harmful, &  It really doesn't bother me so far.. I'm in good health & heart worm negative, but I do take 1/2 of a Proin tablet Twice A-day since my bladder isn't what it used to be.. I really don't have any accidents cuz the Proin really helps.. My Foster mommy has lots of dogs around so I am used to other dogs...

I can still jump up on the couch and lay on top to look out the window.. Overall, I am very loving & would like to find a Family that would love me  For the sweet, older baby that I am. I can still go on walks, but I don't go very far.. I enjoy being loved on, Getting treats & hanging out with the rest of my brothers and sisters in my Foster home..
Hope to meet you soon, And thank you for your consideration...

***Please note: All dogs are fostered in private homes of volunteers, so to meet a dog please fill out an Adoption Application on our website (http://www.twyla.org/adopt/our-adoption-process) so we may setup a private meetup with the dog or coordinate for an Introduction at the next general Adoption Meet  and Greet (as listed on our website: (http://www.twyla.org/upcoming-events), as not all dogs attend all Meet and Greets***

Howard

 

Located in Sidney NE area

Chihuahua and Terrier mix

3 years old

Good with dogs that mind their business 

Cats unknown but he has a live and let live attitude, if they left him alone he would likely leave them alone

Older kids with dog manners would be fine

Hates MEN, he's not warming up, he doesn't like them 

House trained but does mark at first

Crate trained and knows command

Has a lot to say 

Fully vetted

5-7 lbs

 

Howard aka Howie aka Bitty Wolf is a chihuahua mix that wants nothing but to snuggle and watch Netflix all day and keep cozy under the covers. He was an owner surrender from an older woman who was very sad but could no longer keep him as she was transitioning to an assisted living facility. When Howie arrived he was very out of sorts, it is possible his transition to his new home could also be rough but we hope not. He absolutely loves females but he isn't a fan of males and he doesn't seem to be budging on that. He doesn't attack or bite but he will growl and air snap as a warning that he's not comfy. This being said he is an absolute doll to women. He has the funniest personality and loves love! He also howls like a wolf, in his mind he's 100% wolf ! He also has a mohawk, which he feels, and we agree, makes him a total rockstar. We know his perfect home is out there and we would love to find it so he could spend the holiday in his FURever home!

 

If interested in adding this unique tiny lil dude to your home please contact us! 

 

 $200.00 Adoption Fee 

(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.)

animal.description:
Our strong and courageous Conrad is finally ready for his forever home!

A sub-human attacked Conrad with an axe, breaking his leg and slitting his neck!  Red Collar Rescue rushed Conrad to the ER and then to the orthopedic vet for surgery.  Conrad spent months on medication and bed rest.  He’s been healing with his foster parents and foster K9 siblings, and has finally been able to go on walks, play, and just be a happy boy!

Conrad is independent and strong willed, but loves to lean on his foster parents when he wants attention.   Incredibly smart and silly, he loves to make his foster family laugh with his goofiness and fun!  He plays hard, but also loves his cuddling and nap time!  Conrad is house trained, and will stand by the back door when he needs to go out.  He also loves to chase toads, which his foster mom does not enjoy, as he wants to bring them in the house!

Conrad has been through a lot in his short life, and still gets uneasy around some new people. Because he’s been social distancing, he hasn’t been able to socialize with new people and dogs as much as normal.   But, he’s learning a ton from a trusted trainer who has helped numerous Red Collar Rescue  pups!

We know Conrad will bring joy, love and fun to his forever home. He deserves only the best after everything he’s been though.  If interested in giving Conrad lots of TLC and a loving forever home, please submit the adoption application which can be found at www.redcollar.org
	
Age: 2 years
Weight: 45 lbs
Good with Dogs: Yes
Good with Cats: No
Good with Children: possibly high school age +
Vaccinated: Yes
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Microchipped: Yes

www.redcollar.org
www.facebook.com/REDCollarRescue

animal.description:
Belle is a sweet, fun-loving, active, Redtick Coonhound.  She is about 2 years old, weighs 45lbs, is house broken, and loves to play most of the day, but knows the fine quality of a good nap.  Belle would do best in a home with a fully fenced yard, kids over the age of 12, and no cats.  She would also prefer to be an only dog.  Belle does have some separation anxiety and boundary anxiety but it is manageable as she becomes comfortable in a new space.  She is crate trained and prefers to sleep in her crate at night.  Her perfect situation is someone with Coonhound experience that is home most of the day and can give her the attention and continued training she needs.  She is smart, loving and very cuddly.  Belle listens very well to commands and she knows "Sit, Stay, Leave it, Come, Down, and Off".  She is going to do best with continued training and plenty of activity.  She is good on walks with a harness and could be a great running partner.  Belle's favorite thing to do is run around the back yard with her favorite toy in her mouth for a while, then sit by your side at night while you watch TV.  Belle is in MA and available for visits.

If you’d like to apply to adopt, please submit an application using the link below.
Application link (please copy and paste into your browser's address bar)

https://ws.ishelters.com/application.php?k=coonhOUnd&t=Coonhound%20Adoption

About our rescue
We are a foster based rescue. Our dogs are in foster homes throughout the area or in some cases in the south waiting to be transported north. We do not have a physical shelter. However, meet and greets are set up for approved applicants.

Our Adoption Process
Visit our website www.necoonhoundrescue.org for information about the Coonhound and Beagle breeds. Read ‘Is a Coonhound Right for You’. 
If you'd like to apply, our application is available at the link above. Once we review your application one of our Adoption Counselors will be in touch to review it with you. Once the phone interview is completed, we will check your vet reference as well as a personal reference and conduct a home visit.

animal.description:
This is a referral please contact the shelter directly   charlene.fournier@spamauricie.com


Hello everyone, my name is Max and I have been waiting for too long for my perfect owner. I am a mix of Husky/Malamute and a Pitbull according to my former owners. I am 3 years old, in excellent health and I am already neutered, vaccinated, dewormed and microchipped.
I'm about 95 pounds of muscle and love, so I'm looking for an owner who knows how to manage me well and who will also have good strength to hold me down when I go for walks. However, I am used to wearing the Gentle Leader and have made a lot of progress in learning not to pull the leash too much. I can't live with children because I can be impatient with certain manipulations and can be possessive of my things. And yes, although I am very close to my favorite human, I am also grumpy in some situations. My new owners won't have to plan to have children in the years to come either, because I will still be here! I'm looking for a family with a house with a fenced yard, so I can play ball safely. I also love swimming in a plastic children's pool. However, since I am very reactive to other animals, it will be safer if my yard is fully fenced. For these reasons, I also cannot live with another dog or cat or have dog friends visiting. A family living in the countryside would be perfect for me, it will prevent me from barking because I am a very good janitor, especially if there are other animals around! In fact, if my new family is looking for a big, brave dog to keep wild animals away from their property, I am up for the challenge. However, I'm not cut out to live outside 24 hours a day, because I love the comfort of a sofa too much! I am housetrained and I am able to stay wisely alone (free in the house) while my humans work. I'm not a good dog to live in an apartment because of my big voice! I also have an average energy level. After a 30-60 minute walk and some ball games in the yard, I like to fall asleep on the couch next to my human and watch Netflix! My human will have to understand my limits and know how to respect them (I grunt to warn if I am uncomfortable in a situation), educate myself with lots of positive reinforcement and also know how to avoid situations that could put my safety or that of other animals at risk. I need some time to adjust to strangers, but once I am confident, I am a good dog who benefits from being known. I'm getting more and more depressed at the shelter, please help me find my family!  Max ??
Max is currently in Trois-Rivières, Quebec. Please contact the person responsible for his adoption if you have any questions or if you wish to meet him. charlene.fournier@spamauricie.com


Bonjour à tous, je m'appelle Max et j'attends depuis trop longtemps mon parfait propriétaire. Je suis un mélange de Husky / Malamute et d'un Pitbull selon mes anciens propriétaires. J'ai 3 ans, en excellente santé et je suis déjà stérilisée, vaccinée, vermifugée et micropuce.
Je suis environ 95 livres de muscle et d'amour, donc je recherche un propriétaire qui sait bien me gérer et qui aura également une bonne force pour me maintenir lorsque je vais me promener. Cependant, j'ai l'habitude de porter le Gentle Leader et j'ai beaucoup progressé pour apprendre à ne pas trop tirer la laisse. Je ne peux pas vivre avec des enfants parce que je peux être impatient avec certaines manipulations et être possessif de mes affaires. Et oui, bien que je sois très proche de mon humain préféré, je suis aussi grincheux dans certaines situations. Mes nouveaux propriétaires n'auront pas non plus à prévoir d'avoir des enfants dans les années à venir, car je serai toujours là! Je recherche une famille avec une maison avec une cour clôturée, pour pouvoir jouer au ballon en toute sécurité. J'aime aussi nager dans une piscine pour enfants en plastique. Cependant, comme je suis très réactif aux autres animaux, il sera plus sûr si ma cour est entièrement clôturée. Pour ces raisons, je ne peux pas non plus vivre avec un autre chien ou chat ou avoir des amis chiens en visite. Une famille vivant à la campagne serait parfaite pour moi, cela m'empêchera d'aboyer car je suis un très bon concierge, surtout s'il y a d'autres animaux aux alentours! En fait, si ma nouvelle famille recherche un gros chien courageux pour éloigner les animaux sauvages de leur propriété, je suis prêt à relever le défi. Cependant, je ne suis pas fait pour vivre à l'extérieur 24 heures sur 24, car j'aime trop le confort d'un canapé! Je suis éduquée et je suis capable de rester sagement seule (libre dans la maison) pendant que mes humains travaillent. Je ne suis pas un bon chien pour vivre dans un appartement à cause de ma grande voix! J'ai aussi un niveau d'énergie moyen. Après 30 à 60 minutes de marche et quelques jeux de ballon dans la cour, j'aime m'endormir sur le canapé à côté de mon humain et regarder Netflix! Mon humain devra comprendre mes limites et savoir les respecter (je grogne pour avertir si je suis mal à l'aise dans une situation), m'éduquer avec beaucoup de renforcement positif et savoir aussi éviter les situations qui pourraient mettre ma sécurité ou celle de autres animaux à risque. J'ai besoin de temps pour m'adapter aux étrangers, mais une fois que j'ai confiance en moi, je suis un bon chien qui profite d'être connu. Je suis de plus en plus déprimé au refuge, aidez-moi à retrouver ma famille! Max ??
Max est actuellement à Trois-Rivières, Québec. Veuillez contacter la personne responsable de son adoption si vous avez des questions ou si vous souhaitez le rencontrer  charlene.fournier@spamauricie.com

animal.description:
Chaco and Oreo are a sweet senior couple that have been together their whole lives and love each other lots. They lost the only home they’ve ever known when their owner could no longer care for them and decided to drop them off at a shelter where they had little chance of being adopted at all much less together.
At Paws4Rescue we love our seniors so much and are happy to help these sweethearts find a forever family.
These pups are quite spry for their age. They are about 11 years old and weigh about 75 pounds. They are spayed/neutered and up to date on all of their vaccinations.
Chaco is a the female and Oreo is the yellow male. His silly ears are enough to make your day! Chaco and Oreo are friendly with other dogs, love to play, and adore attention of course.
Please contact BigYellowDog.wendy@gmail.com if you’d be interested in giving Chaco and Oreo a forever home and the best years of their lives. Or you can send an application from our site at paws4rescue.org,

animal.description:
UPDATE: Danny is doing very well, getting quite playful and loving his toys!


Meet Danny!

Danny is a "Mini" male Spitz, 4 years old. (White)

 PHOTOS SOON! 

*With Adults: yes, good with adults.
*With Kids: no experience with kids, protective of his food, will not be placed with children.
*With Other Dogs: he was okay with other dogs at the shelter (not playing, but shared his space in peace). However, in former foster home, he seemed to have some issues, foster did not have another dog, whenever he would see another dog on walk, he would bark at them, and if another dog tries to sniff his bottom, he will growl. We will be working on this now that he is in the Chicago area.
*With Cats: no experience. 
*Housebroken: yes, in former foster home, however, there will be a new learning curve when moving into a new home.
*Energy Level: medium level.
*Can he be handled/touched: he can after he gets to know and trust his people. He will do "biting motion" and jerk of his head when/if someone tries to touch his bottom. Care should be taken when grooming.
*Barker: not a barker inside, but as said above, he will bark at another dog while on a walk, especially if relatively close. 
*Escape Artist: he has tendency to get excited and run out the door to go out for a walk, extra care, namely a held leash, needs to be place so that he doesn't get loose. 
*Food Aggressive: yes, he is protective of his food. He will go into a "biting motion" aka a warning (not actual strong bite though) if someone is messing with his food/bowl once it is given to him. 
*Walks on Leash: yes, enjoys his walks.

If you are interested in Danny, please complete an adoption application! Thanks!

animal.description:
Hiya,

My name is Nina, aren't I a pretty girl???  I didn't used to be.  :(

You see, I was found in the middle of nowhere starving to death. All yucky and dirty.  The person that found me picked me up and took me to the vet to check and see if I was chipped.  Lo and behold, I was!!  How awesomely amazing!

Then the unthinkable happened.  The vet came back and said that I had 4 different owners registered to my chip.  You know what happens next??  It's awful and not for the faint at heart.  Each of those listed as an owner kept passing me off to the next person and then ultimately I was dumped.  

I just don't understand why???  I wasn't that bad of a puppy.  I mean I had a lot of energy because I was young, but geez...I wonder if they would do that to a hyper human child as well??  People, us pups need boundaries set and taught what we should do and how we need to act.  A little instruction, attention, and love is all we need.  It's so sad.

I was so upset.  Here I thought I found my home and BAM, kicked to the curb like a bag of garbage.  Anyway, my finder was kind enough to keep me for a little while until Lucies could make a space for me.

The people here are wonderful and they have taught me all kinds of fun things.  As a bonus, I get to run and play with other dogs and make friends!

I have a docked tail and it sure is cute!  I'd really love to be someone's running or hiking partner.  Oh yeah, and I love to swim!  Splish splash I was taking a bath.....sorry I digressed a bit :) Isn't music fun though??

I am leash and crate trained and I'm super duper smart.

So, what do you say??  Come visit me and you'll see that I'm the dog for you!!

*** We strive to ensure our dogs are going to a safe, loving and caring home. Phone interviews are required for all adoptions****

Jess says hey!  This girl is a beauty, and is very, very sweet.  She is a black and tan coonhoundy kinda gal, and loves to play with other dogs.  She loves people too.  Jess loves to run and needs a pretty spacious yard that is securely fenced with a six foot fence.  Hounds are very good at climbing short fences, so a taller fence for her is needed.

Jess loves to eat, and loves treats and is very well mannered.  She learns fast and is very bright and curious.  She is spayed, fully vaccinated, good on a leash, and looking for her forever.

Her adoption fee is $150.  She is also microchipped.  Please call Lori at 405-620-2411 to set a time to meet this lovely lady!!!

animal.description:
Hi my name is Fluffer! I’m 7 years old and 25 lbs!  When you meet me, you’ll probably fall instantly in love. I know I’m cute and I wag my tail and shake my butt happily to win you over even more. That’s me....about 95 percent of the time. I walk great on a leash, get along with other dogs, and LOVE treats (especially peanut butter bones).
BUT- there’s another 5 percent of me that you MUST know about before you consider adopting me. I have a bite history. It is mostly food aggressive behavior, but not all the time. I’ve been adopted 3 times by ODHS and each time I’ve been returned for my biting. Not nipping, but biting. ODHS is committed to finding me the right home, but knows that my future people should be 
1) incredibly dog savvy
2) be willing to feed me and let me sleep in a penned in area or separate room (like a laundry room, mud room, etc). I don’t especially like crates and got mad and bit about that before too. 
3) be committed to not leaving human food out for me to access, including the garbage can. If I get a hold of something that I want, I will NOT easily give it up.

So that’s me, Fluffer, in a nutshell. I’m a happy guy who loves belly rubs and human attention. But it’s very important you know all about me before we meet. 


Hope to see you soon! 

Educational articles:
3/3/3 Rule;
https://www.rescuedogs101.com/bringing-new-dog-home-3-3-3-rule/?fbclid=IwAR2iv5m7fqk3FieO7LOsstGeGsYYV_F1rJOd1BPxaImofLpcinpYsUbFRWs

Adoption Donations are $250 for an adult, $350 for puppies (a dog under one year of age), and $125 for a senior dog (based on the age of the dog). Adoption donations are to be made via cash, and credit/debit card. There is a $5 fee to run cards.

Please remember to bring a collar and leash (non-retractable) with you the day of the adoption. Note: Martingale collars and slip leads are strongly recommended.

Due to COVID19, we aren't having as many open, public adoption events.  Current schedule is pre-determined meet and greet appointments are Wednesday evenings and on Saturday from 12-2.  

Our adoption center is located at 3602 Lafayette Blvd, Suite 102, Fredericksburg, VA 22408. It's important that you keep an eye on your emails for any changes or updates during the adoption process.

Visit our website for an application to adopt. 
https://www.olddominionhumanesociety.org/adoption-application

Old Dominion Humane Society is a volunteer based organization. We are run completely by volunteers, who also have full time jobs, so we appreciate your patience.  Currently, the average timeframe for a response to your application is 1 week.

Like us on Facebook "Old Dominion Humane Society"
and be a part of promoting forever homes for dogs in need.
#Adopt #Donate #Foster #Volunteer 

Note: ODHS only adopts to Virginia and surrounding states (including D.C.). A $50 out of state fee applies.

animal.description:
Hi there, I’m Trixie! I’m having some trouble finding my forever home but my foster family can’t understand why! I am a female Bluetick coonhound around 40ish pounds, somewhere between 5 and 7 years young and I love to have fun! I am goofy pup who loves to run and play. 

Being a coonhound, I am occasionally intense, especially around smaller animals but I promise I usually just want to play! I love doggie daycare! It helps release me energy & make me less nervous. 

I don’t always understand what the tiny humans called kids are doing and that can stress me out, so I need a family without them. If your cats don’t like to play with dogs then I don’t think we would work out. 

I deal with some of the normal dog anxieties such as nervousness during thunderstorms and new environments. These anxieties can sometimes cause me to be a bit vocal (I am a CoonHOUND after all) but I am able to settle with some love and treats after a time. Maybe a home without shared walls would be best. 

I do know how to jump 4 foot fences, so a 6 foot would be necessary if my family has a fence! I enjoy long naps in the sun and also love long walks and taking the time to smell the flowers. Come take me for a walk maybe we’ll be the perfect match.

animal.description:
CONTACT: dog.sos@yahoo.com to Helen G.

Meet amazing Eloise! She is an active senior at 9 1/2 years young. Adorable and a lovely mix of a terrier with chihuahua to make for a cute and compact 40lb. medium-sized doll.

Eloise has such a bright spirit, is ready to go anytime. She will get you out for walks, make you laugh, give you love, and cuddle with you! If you have a more quiet household, that will work just fine for her. She doesn't need a yard if she gets her walks in. If you have a yard, she will love it.

She will do best with an experienced owner rather than a first-time pup parent. A quiet household with no kids is best for her.

Eloise really wants you to herself and is not into dogs and gets a bit overly excited, just as some people are more homebody. She is great on the leash, fully trained (and comes with a transition session!), and makes it easy to move to the other side of the street so she can enjoy herself and not be forced to go nose to nose when pooches are not her thing.

This cutie pie loves human companionship, will be your best friend, and will take ear scritches and belly rubs as often as you will give them. She will take time to settle into your home, and we will give you tips on how to ease her in.

She is in great health, well trained, and really fun.

She is now updated on all shots, spayed, and will be chipped.

ELOISE IS A COURTESY POST, follow the email at the top of this bio.

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
I'm Lilly and I'm an 11 year old Feist (Fice) mix.  My Dad went into a nursing facility, his children didn't want me, and there was no place else for me to go.  I am in a great foster home but am longing for a home of my own,

Don't let my gray hair fool you! I'm still pretty feisty and I love to snuggle! I am a little overweight, but my foster Mom got me on a great nutrition plan and best of all - I have a fenced in yard to run around in and explore!  

I'm still a little reluctant to take the plunge of using the doggie door - but I'm getting there!.  My foster Mom says I listen very well.

I like other dogs just fine as long as they aren't big dogs!  I will pester a cat to play a bit too much if there isn't another dog to hang out with.  I was recently on a trial adoption but the resident cat could not get used to me being there and wanting to play.

I am not used to the activity levels of children - I'm an "adults only" dog!

I have been spayed, am heartworm negative, and am up to date with vaccinations.  My adoption fee is only $100 - a bargain if I do say so myself!  

Take a chance on me - you won't regret it!

To request an adoption application, please visit https://www.udranch.org/contact.  Please allow 24-48 hours for a response!

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Sweet Ruthie was found running into oncoming traffic in San Bernardino and a Good Samaritan got her off the streets and asked us to hold her. No chip and no tags. She was held for stray hold until 10/17 and was spayed, chipped and vaccinated, and now Ruthie is looking for a new home!

She was scared when she first came to us, but never nippy and was playing with the dogs within a few hours and trusted us by the next day. She gets along with all dogs big and small but can be food possessive with other dogs so needs to be fed separately. No food aggression with people.

animal.description:
Hello! My name is Felix and I am 14 years young. I have no grays though, because I am all white ? Don’t let my age fool you, I am still a healthy, active boy. I love to go on walks, but I get very excited when I see other dogs or a cyclist and will pull on my leash. Mom says I’m pretty strong, so make sure you are too. Traffic causes me anxiety, so I’d prefer more leisurely walks without the hustle and bustle of cars. I’m very loving and am great with kids and cats. I will bark at the neighbor’s dog through the fence, but am not aggressive. I LOVE cleaning up the floors after my foster skin siblings’ meals and mom wouldn’t put it past me to counter surf, even though it hasn’t happened yet. Stairs are a little rough for me, so I’d prefer to not have to use them. I like to sleep in my crate with the door open, but please don’t close it as it gives me anxiety. I’d really prefer to be with someone who is home most of the time so I can snuggle and follow you around, especially since I don’t like being in a crate. One more very important thing, I have selective hearing (I’m deaf), but mom says I’m smart and has already been able to teach me signs. I’d love to find a family to call my own and live out the rest of my days with.


If you are interested in adopting me, please fill out our adoption application to begin the process at http://savetheboxers.com/adoptionapp.php.

If you aren't able to adopt at this time, please consider making a much needed, tax-deductible donation to Legacy Boxer Rescue at http://savetheboxers.com/donate.php.

animal.description:
Hi there my name is Louie and I'm a 10-month old lab-pit mix.
I have been at HALO K9 Behavior Center though the Shelter & Rescue Partner Program. The shelter thought I would be a good candidate for this program because when I was surrendered to the shelter, I was very fearful and showing fear aggression (growling at the shelter staff). 
At HALO, I learned that people aren't so scary but actually very nice. I also have many, many dog friends who have helped me overcome my fear of people. I am currently working on: walking nicely on a leash (I am still afraid of bikes), respecting items in my room (I still chew on things I shouldn't), and greeting people properly (sometimes I bark at them). Even though I am a work in progress, I am the sweetest boy with the cutest personality. I would do best in a home with someone who has another confident, well adjusted dog who can teach me how to overcome my issues. I've only been at HALO since August and have made amazing strides. The people at HALO are confident that I will be a perfect companion given the chance. 

Love, Lou-Lou 
 Primary Color: Tan Secondary Color: White Weight: 55.3lbs Age: 1yrs 1mths 2wks Animal has been Neutered

animal.description:
Meet Pickles! The biggest, slobberyist goober ever. Pickles is about 2 years old and had a rough start to life. This special boy needs an experienced handler, with mastiff experience and/or training experience to ensure he is set up for success. He is looking for a home with structure and NO children. He loves being outside, throwing his toys up in the air, and snoozing on the couch. A fenced in yard would be ideal because this baby beast loves to sunbathe and sit outside taking in the world. His facial expressions and goofy floor acrobatics will keep a smile on your face. 

Because of his past, Pickles is fearful of men and strangers- slow introductions and an acclimation period are needed, but then he will charm your socks off! He has been through a board and train with Sit Means Sit and has a lifetime membership of free group classes. He is very well trained on the e-collar system. He loves playing with other doggos but is selective when it comes to his home environment and his humans. He may do better as an only dog, but its really on a case by case basis as he does enjoy a fur-sibling to play with. No cats for this boy. As a protective breed, P tends to guard his handlers until he feels safe and comfortable with new faces. This is something Pickles is working on in his current foster home where he is doing fantastic. He sleeps well in his crate at night, and this structure is really good for him. This angel is worth the wait to get to know, and deserves an amazing furever home. 

If you think you may be a good fit for Pickles, submit an application using this link: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSfC2mVkqTTzPJQK74MJQWetUQUcMURow4gvuCxs1nVT4KYXvA/viewform?usp=sf_link

*PLEASE READ: NC applicants only. Dog being rehomed through private owner, this is a courtesy post on behalf of Freedom Ride Rescue.

animal.description:
Rosie, oh Rosie - a sweet brindle Boxer girl who is looking for a pawsome home to call her own. For a girl who is just about 2 years old, Rosie's story is a very sad one. Her owner passed away and believed to have been alone in the home for several days near him when family found them. She was clearly stressed but our volunteers took tender loving care of her until she was placed in foster. She is doggie selective and likes to be in control so best placed as an only dog in her forever home. Our Rosie is crate trained, house trained, does okay on leash , likes to play with toys which keeps her busy. A stable, very quiet home without a lot of activity in and out of the home is best for Rosie. She can be nervous around new people in the beginning until she knows you. Rosie is not a companion animal that should be brought to dog parks, coffee shops, or a home with people in/out of often. She does best with her familiar home surroundings and people to call her own.

Rosie must be placed in the Phoenix area so that she can continue her BLR sponsored training. We will only place in the Phoenix Metro area and only with an experienced Boxer family who will commit to continue her training (already paid for)! Email us at info@boxerluv.org if you believe you're the right fit. 2/2/21 4:05 PM

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

I'm starting to wonder if I will ever find my forever home.. Can anyone help me?Date into Rescue: 2/28/20107
Reason for being in rescue: Lovingly surrendered by owners
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms in Pacolet, SC
Special Needs? Brielle had surgery in February 2020 to remove some masses around her anus. She'd experienced challenges going to the bathroom that resulted in her rectum protruding. Brielle has recovered and is now ready for a home with a very experienced owner.
Weight: 62 lbs
Height: 24 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Brielle needs a quiet, more reserved home with owners that have a soft spot for timid dogs. She is comfortable by herself and would be fine with another dog in the home. Brielle feels safe in her crate and needs to know she will always have a spot of her own. Brielle will trust the right people in her own way and her own time. She would like an owner who can meet her on her level and let her know the world is safe. Brielle will not be adopted to a first time dog owner or into a home with children under 10. Her ideal home has experience with timid dogs and has another dog that Brielle can continue to learn from.

What is my personality like? Brielle arrived in rescue as an owner release with a few others. From day one she has always been timid and scared while her other siblings have come out of their shells and found homes. Brielle is the type of dog that will need plenty of one on one time to get her where she needs to be in life. Everyone at the rescue has worked with her and she will now take treats out of our hands, but she could really use help in a permanent home to help her grow. She has great potential with a sweet and gentle nature and just needs a special person to help her along her way.

Brielle has come a long way since she first came to us. She is sweet and trusts the people she is with everyday. She does perfectly fine with all dogs, and they help her relax and learn that we people are not so bad. Brielle needs an understanding human that has a soft spot for dogs with troubled souls. Brielle is reportedly a 3rd generation Shepadoodle - German Shepherd and Standard Poodle, but since she looks so much more like a Labrador Retriever, we've put that breed instead. Brielle is ready for a home of her own after 3 years of learning humans are good.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Cautious but warms up

Other tips and tidbits: Brielle's estimated birthday is 01/02/2010

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
Shea is a fun, friendly, exuberant girl! Currently living in a foster home, we have gotten to know Shea as an active, smart lady. She would do best in an active household that would enjoy going on all sorts of adventures together! Shea loves to go for hikes and walks, and even has potential as a running partner. She LOVES the water and swimming! Shea can be a little shy and reserved at first, but once she settles in she shows that she is a cuddly, affectionate girl but not overly clingy, though she does have a bit of FOMO if she sees you having fun without her! Shea is a little picky with her dog friends, but seems to have potential to get along with many with proper intros. Shea has taken some lessons with Sits N' Wiggles Cleveland to polish her manners on leash and when excited and has shown she is really bright and good at picking up on routine. Shea seems to have potential to live with cats, again with proper intros. She can be exuberant greeting them and wants to give them kisses, but backs off when told. Shea would love to be the life of the party in her forever home and she'll certainly add loves of love and entertainment. She is around 3 or 4 years old and weighs 48 lbs.
Due to COVID-19, CITY DOGS is currently doing adoptions by APPOINTMENT ONLY. Please visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to request a meet and greet! 

Questions? Email: citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us | Call: (216) 664-3476
Visit: 9203 Detroit Avenue Cleveland, OH 44102

Hours:
10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.

Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. You must schedule a meet with a dog in advance - we are not currently accepting walk-ins. Please look online first to see if there are any dogs you think would be a good fit for your home before scheduling a meet. To get the process started, visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog and fill out the form. One of our adoption counselors will get in touch to schedule and confirm your meet! At the kennel, an adoption counselor will introduce you and your family to the adoptable dogs, share information we know about them, and discuss our suggested ways for successfully integrating a new dog into your home. You are welcome to meet multiple dogs. If the dog you adopt is already fixed, he or she may leave with you that day - otherwise, the dog can go home after receiving the spay or neuter surgery.)

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog once they are in the home. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.

Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DAPPL, Rabies, and Bordatella vaccines, though you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.?

animal.description:
Barry is a BEAUTIFUL husky and his temperament makes him even more handsome.  Barry and his Mom Sasha (also available) came to us when one of the elderly owners passed away and the other had to move in with family.  Barry, while he has the quintessential Husky looks with the beautiful coat and striking blue eyes, he has a much more soft, affectionate and attentive personality that alot of Huskies have.  He LOVES to be petted and will sit at your feet and lean across your legs to get as close as possible, and even when he is out running in our fenced in play yards he will check back in frequently with the volunteers.  Barry also doesn't appear to have the Husky "escape artist" trait - he doesn't try to jump our fences nor dig under!  Good boy!

Barry is housetrained and walks pretty well on a leash (unless he sees a squirrel or cat running past - so no small critters in his home).  He lived with other dogs so could live with another dog in his forever home, he seems to like the females the best (maybe because he lived with his Mom and 2 female small Peke mixes in his prior home.).  Barry so deserves a safe, loving, active forever home.  Please come meet this handsome guy.

animal.description:
Frisko is a very well behaved pup. He stays off furniture unless invited, knows many basic commands (sit, stay, come, etc.), doesn’t bark when his foster mom is home and doesn’t shed much at all. He’s friendly towards all people and greets any visitors at the door calmly. His foster mom has been walking him about 4-5 miles a day. He seems happy and calmed by that amount of exercise, and he could probably hike 10+ miles easily.

Frisko is working hard on his socialization skills with other dogs and is showing marked improvement. He has gone on walks with a few different medium/large dogs and does well walking next to them; he’ll sniff/allow them to sniff him. He is also getting more comfortable walking next to smaller dogs but moves away from them if they get too close. He is prey-driven towards small animals so isn’t a good match to live with cats or small dogs. He doesn’t like to be left alone. Frisko willingly goes into his crate on command; he whines when his foster mom leaves the house and barks a bit when he hears her return. 

Frisko is smart, super loyal and cuddly. He will be a great addition to a family that’s experienced with larger dogs (ideally huskies) and interested in training him. Frisko will thrive with adequate physical and mental stimulation. If you're looking for a stellar walking or running companion, here he is!

Frisco’s adoption fee includes neuter, basic vaccinations, rabies vaccination, and heartworm tested negative.

You can find his application here:

https://forms.gle/5eSBjHrWv7pTEEzUA

Questions? Contact us at connellpetrescue@gmail.com 

Thank you! And Frisco thanks you!

animal.description:
Boris is a 7.5 year old Border Collie mix (and maybe shepherd) who weighs 45 pounds. He is up to date on vaccinations and neutered. Boris is house and crate trained.

Don't let the premature gray fool you. Boris is smart, spunky, animated and has a young, playful spirit. He loves to play with toys and will toss them in the air and jump enthusiastically to catch them. He needs sturdy toys because he will completely destroy the soft stuffed toys. He loves a Kong filled with peanut butter and will run to his crate to receive his treat and gently takes them from your hand. He waits patiently next to his person for a good back rub and then rests peacefully on a dog bed. His favorite thing to do is to ride in the car and will eagerly hop in the car for a ride around town.

To understand Boris's needs, it helps to know a little bit about his history. Like many rescue dogs Boris was dumped by his owner. However, this happened to Boris twice. When he was a cute little fuzzy puppy of eight weeks old someone handed him to an employee in a pet supply store and never came back for him. He found his way to our rescue where he had dozens of interested applications and was adopted. Seven years later Boris was dumped in the parking lot of a shelter. It took the shelter a week to catch him. Fortunately he is microchipped and he found his way back to us. What happened to him in that time is a mystery, but we have some clues as to what may have happened. He most likely lived outdoors for some period of time. It is no surprise that he developed some anxiety issues from being neglected and abandoned. Boris needs time to adjust to his new environment and can be anxious and snap if pushed into something uncomfortable. This is very predictable and has been easily managed in his foster home.

His biggest need is that he must have time to get to know you on his own time frame and get to know his new home. He is comfortable in a crate and can use that space to decompress and adjust. A trip to the vet is going to make him anxious and he will most likely need to be muzzled and sedated for vet visits. He loves car rides and can be taken on rides, but he does not need to go in stores, friends' homes, dog parks or bars. Boris needs to be protected from situations that cause him anxiety.
Boris has made great progress in his foster home and behaves like a normal happy dog. He is good with the routine and structure and behaves lovingly and sweetly. The situations that may cause him anxiety are very predictable and preventable. He has started to go on outings with his foster Mom and did great meeting a new human friend in their yard. He displayed no anxiety and was relaxed and happy.

Boris deserves a chance to be in a home that is committed to love and care for him for the rest of his life. He needs a home where he is kept from situations that cause him anxiety and provide him with a structure within which he can shine and receive love. He is a funny and charming dog who is easy to love. He tilts his head to the side and flops his ears into awkward positions which will make you laugh often. He has a consistent routine in his foster home and his funny and loving personality has emerged. Because of his anxiety issues Boris needs a home with no other pets or children. He is not suitable for apartment life and will do best in a home with a fenced yard where he can exercise off leash in the yard.

If you are interested in adopting Boris please submit an inquiry directly with Greater Charlotte SPCA by visiting charlottespca.org/adopt.

***Because our rescue is composed entirely of volunteers and we require a home check for each of our adoptable pets prior to them going to their new homes, local applications will take precedence. We will accept out of town applications, but any family further than 60 miles from Charlotte is responsible for finding a representative of a rescue local to them that is willing to perform the home check. All out of town applicants will also have to be willing to drive to Charlotte to meet/pick up the pet as soon as the application is approved.***

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Essie Scott! I'm a 2 year old, 57 pound pitbull mix and a bundle of joyous energy. Everything in life is sooooo exciting! My excitement and zest for life is contagious. You can't help but smile around me!

Sometimes my excitement gets the best of me and I go hopping and jumping around like a bunny rabbit. I just can't help myself because I love people so much! I've been working on my training though and learning how to be a well-behaved girl. I love the treats I get when I do a good job! For now, I'd do best in a home without small children that I might accidentally knock over.

I can sometimes be choosy about my doggy friends. I like dogs around my size who will play with me and not take it too seriously. I just wanna have fun! I might be a bit too much to handle for smaller dogs or senior dogs, and I don't think cats would appreciate my antics either.

I hope I find my family soon. I have so much love to give and just know I'll make a great pet!

animal.description:
Roddie is around 2 years old and weighs approximately 60 pounds. He was adopted from the Devore shelter and found to be overly playful with a smaller dog not possessing the same energy level. Not wanting to return him to a shelter and knowing what would happen to him if returned, he was relinquished to Poochmatch. His bunk mate is a female husky named Pearl (also available for adoption), who loves to play with him. Roddie is active and energetic. He likes people and playing with other dogs. He would do best with a medium or large dog who is able to wrestle and play with him to get his energy out, or adopters who are willing to refine his leash training and are active to take him on lots of walks/jogs and occasional hikes. He is loving and sweet and will make an excellent companion! Roddie's adoption fee is $385 and covers the cost of his neuter, all core vaccines (Rabies and Distemper/Parvo), microchip and microchip registration. If you’re interested in adopting, the first step is completing an adoption application which is available on our website, Poochmatch.com, under the adoption tab. Please read the following paragraphs for additional information about our process.

If this listing is still posted, we are still accepting applications for him/her. We do not do out-of-state adoptions on highly adoptable dogs; we would only consider out-of-state adoptions for dogs that prove hard-to-place locally. We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

UPDATE: ADOPTION EVENTS CANCELLED DUE TO PANDEMIC AND SOCIAL DISTANCING. If you are interested in meeting any Poochmatch dog at our weekly adoption event on Saturdays at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda, CA (5521 Mirage St.) between 1-5 PM, please fill out an application from our website, poochmatch.com, and submit it no later than 11 AM on Fridays. Upon receipt AND approval, the dog you are interested in meeting will be made available to meet on a Saturday. Due to the high volume of dogs and puppies in our foster homes, it is impossible to bring them all every Saturday. The only way to ensure that the dog that you are interested in will be at the adoption event is to FILL OUT AN APPLICATION AND BE APPROVED. Otherwise, we cannot guarantee that the dog you are interested in will be at our adoption event. If you cannot make the time frame of our events, appointments can be made at another time and location solely at the discretion of the foster parent. Please understand that private appointments will be coordinated to meet the convenience of the foster parent/transporter. We cannot hold dogs, please submit your application when you are ready to adopt.

All adoption fees cover the mandatory and non-negotiable spay/neuter, rabies, microchip, microchip registration, full sets of core vaccinations (rabies and 1 set of distemper/parvo for adults, 4 for puppies) and deworming. Adoption fees vary based on age, breed, size and the costs incurred on the dog's behalf by us i.e. medical, behavioral training, etc. and they range from $225-$495.


COVID-19 PROCEDURE:
In an effort to create a safe environment for our potential adopters and our staff, we have changed our protocols and procedures during these difficult times. Starting immediately, our procedures will change from what’s written on our website and other social media platforms. Our weekly adoption event at the Petsmart in Yorba Linda is temporarily cancelled due to COVID-19 and social distancing. The only way to meet one of the dogs/puppies we have available for adoption is through completion of our adoption application through our website, poochmatch.com, before 11 AM on Fridays. On Fridays when we review the applications, we will pick the best fit for each dog or puppy applied for and coordinate mutually agreeable appointment times for the applicants who are approved that week. Private appointments are currently only scheduled on Wednesday, Thursday or Saturday of each week. Masks or bandanas are mandatory; faces must be properly covered.

With the overwhelming desire of the public to adopt at this time, we have received as many as 30 applications for one dog in just one week. Working with a staff of volunteers, we are only able to reach out on Fridays to the people we have approved to adopt. If you have not heard from us by Friday, we have selected a different applicant. If you have multiple dogs/puppies that you are interested in, please indicate each dog/puppy of interest on the application at that time so we don’t rule you out for another dog/puppy available for adoption.

Please understand, we have an influx of texts, phone calls and emails that makes it impossible to get to each and every one of you. Not just for adoption interest, but also from veterinarians, people who must relinquish dogs, people who have found a stray dog in need of pick up, etc. We are currently not in need of fosters. Due to the fact that there is such a high demand, we are sticking with strict protocol to not adopt out of Southern California. We apologize for this inconvenience and difficulty to be able to get in touch with us while there is an overwhelming desire and demand to adopt at this time. We appreciate your understanding and patience as we navigate through these difficult times with every intention to keep the public and our staff safe.

animal.description:
*ADOPT ME!*
Sugar - 6 years old, located in Texas
Dog ID#: 201251-P-B-TX
Intake Date: 09/06/2020
Available Date: 10/20/2020 

Sugar is a middle aged girl (about 6 years) and weighs about 50 pounds.  She is currently located in Texas.  We don’ know much about her previous life, except that Sugar has had multiple litters of pups.  She was more than likely kept in a kennel and bred for most of her life, so she has not lived in a house or been exposed to a lot of the finer things in life, until now. 

Sugar gets along well with other dogs, although she prefers the company of people, and loves the foster family's cats.  She can be timid and anxious when exposed to new things, but seems to adapt quickly.  She will need patience until she gains familiarity and trust. 

Sugar was heartworm positive and has completed the treatment protocol. She has been in foster care since the first week in September and is already making great progress. 

Sugar is happiest and most at ease when curled up on the couch, relaxing with foster mom and dad or sleeping in their comfy king sized bed.  She has benefitted greatly from the influence of living with other calm, well socialized, and well-behaved dogs, but would do well as an only dog with an adoptive family that would love and cherish her. 

We have been working on potty training and she is doing well. She likes to go outside for short periods and prefers her humans to be close by.  Sugar does very well on a leash and would enjoy slow, leisurely walks with her people.  She is good in the car, although you may have to pick her up and put her in.  Inside the house, she is calm and doesn’t chew things or counter surf.  We are working on using the dog door, but have not pushed it because of her heartworm treatment required her to be supervised and calm.  She is fine in the crate, although you may have to coax her in at first.

Sugar is a wonderful companion and an easy dog to live with. She is exceptionally gentle, calm, and quiet.  She hasn’t learned any of the typical obedience commands, but is well behaved.  She can be trusted to be left alone in the house for short periods of time. She has not been vetted with small children. Given time with a loving, patient home, Sugar will be an awesome dog.  She is a precious, sweet couch potato, but she still has a ways to go until he is fully socialized. She needs someone who has experience with timid dogs, or has a willingness to learn, and is 100% committed to Sugar, because she will love you unconditionally. 

Want to learn more about one of the dogs we have up for adoption? Fill out our adoption application (http://www.pointerrescue.org/adopt.html)!!

TRANSPORT AVAILABLE TO APPROVED HOMES! (currently within 600 miles)

animal.description:
Meet Bandit! Bandit is one of about 50 dogs rescued from a neglectful hoarding situation in South Georgia back in early July. Some of the dogs on the property had been living inside and were more socialized, able to be adopted quickly. But sadly, there was another group that had lived their whole lives outside with little human interaction. It has taken a couple of months of living in a foster home for them to start realizing that there are good people in this world who will love and cherish them. These dogs have come amazingly far since being rescued but do still carry the weight of their previous life with them. As such, they have very specific adoption requirements listed below. Please understand, we have taken 3 months to get to know these dogs and what they need to succeed. The adoption requirements are not arbitrary but are what is needed for them to lead happy, healthy lives and as such no exceptions to these requirements will be allowed. 

 

Bandit is about a year and a half old and under 25 lbs. Hes a sweet, playful boy but still a bit on the shy side. He needs a patient adopter who is going to give him the time and space he needs to adjust and get comfortable in a new home. Given that the best teachers for dogs lacking confidence are other dogs, Bandit also must have other confident dogs in the home with at least one of them being under 30 lbs and playful. He is learning to walk on a leash but has yet to gain enough confidence to go to the bathroom on leash and does require a SECURELY fenced yard - solid wood privacy fence only (minimum 6 ft); chain link, wrought iron, or other types of fencing are not sufficient. Lastly, given that Bandit is still learning to trust people, he will not do well with the unpredictable nature of children. Homes with teenagers may be considered on a case by case basis, depending on the experience level of the family. 

 

We do understand that the above requirements greatly narrows the pool of potential adopters and may even scare some people away. Bandit is most definitely a work in progress but we cannot even begin to explain how rewarding it is to watch the transformation of a dog like this who has never known love before. Once they learn to love and trust, they are so very very grateful and the amount of love they have to give and their loyalty knows no bounds. If you are interested in becoming part of Bandits continuing story, email adrienne@rescuemega.org or fill out an adoption application on our website- www.rmgdogs.org

No appointment necessary for pets that are located at the rescue center. Appointments must be made to visit pets in foster homes. Questions can be emailed to troyanimalrescueproject@gmail.com or call 334-508-2367.

animal.description:
Oliver, a 4 year old Boxer/Staffordshire terrier mix, is such a sweet happy boy who loves his people. He is a quick study, good on the leash but a strong boy. He is smart and knows several commands. He may be a tad shy initially but warms up quickly and makes friends whereever he goes. Oliver is fascinated by the tennis ball and will play fetch for hours! This is by far his favorite thing to do...and if the ball squeaks he will be in heaven! He enjoys going for long walks, a good game of fetch in the backyard and cuddling on the couch during a good show! 

Olivers ideal home would be as an only dog with a fenced backyard, someone who will take him on car rides and long walks to new places, and someone who is home more than not. His foster family works from home and he loves having them around. Oliver has his own FB page called Olivers BIG Adventures. Please join us there for more information and fun photos! 

Read more about Oliver and see more photos of him on his Blog.

To adopt Oliver visit our website for more details regarding our adoption criteria and complete the easy online no obligation adoption application at www.dsda.org/adopt. 

* Adoption Fees:
Puppies (12 months and under) - $325 (includes tax)
Dogs (over 12 months) - $275 (includes tax) 
* Home visit is required. For this reason we only adopt locally in the DFW area.

Qualifications for Adoption:
 Must be 21 years or older with identification showing present address.
 Must have the knowledge and consent of all adults living in the household.
 Vet checks are required. All resident animals must be spayed/neutered, up to date on
vaccinations and on monthly heartworm and flea/tick preventative (if applicable).
 Must receive proof of pet deposit and lease allowing pets if renting.
 Willingness and capacity to spend the time and money necessary to provide training,
medical treatment and responsible care for a pet.
 Applicant is home more than not or willing to provide daycare or pet sitter when away for long periods of time.

animal.description:
Bella is a gorgeous, affectionate Pittie/Lab mix who is 9 years old and weighs 60 lbs.  She was initially rescued 5 years ago from a kill shelter in AZ while her mom was a grad student in Phoenix.  Sadly, due to circumstances beyond her control, Bella's mom can no longer keep Bella and needs to re-home her girl.  Bella is an incredibly loving and loyal companion who wants nothing more than to be next to her person.  She has been well loved & cared for and would happily snuggle all day if you'd let her.  She is medium energy girl, generally mellow, but loves a good game of tug-o-war or the occasional run/hike.  Despite her age, Bella is still active and ready for new adventures. She is very smart, eager to please, and HIGHLY food motivated!  Bella has some on-leash dog reactivity which is helped with daily anxiety medication so a home with an experienced owner & a fenced yard where she can explore stress-free would be ideal.  She'd be happiest as an only dog, with no other small pets or children.  Bella is spayed, up-to-date on vaccines & monthly preventatives, and is in good health.  Her mom can provide all her vet records to confirm.

For more information about Bella, please call/text Selena at 404-838-7555 or email her at svmakrides@gmail.com.

animal.description:
Zoe is a beautiful mixed breed with a few different varieties. Approximately 1.5 - 2 years old.  Zoe is wonderful with children (big and small) and serves as a good barker when people approach the house.  Outside she does not bark and is friendly to all.  

Zoe was heartworm positive, but she is currently undergoing heartworm treatment to get rid of them.  She shows no adverse signs to being heartworm positive and the medication is only administered monthly.  

Zoe has a difficult time with new persons entering the home, especially adult males. She is not aggressive, but she is very timid and does not like the visitors in the home.  She would love a family or a single woman to bond with, but without a lot of activity in the home. Prefers quiet, stable and outdoor spaces to relax in. Zoe also loves to go for walks, hikes and appears to be drawn to water. She does like to fetch and run, but only in fully enclosed spaces as she can get distracted by squirrels or other dogs/cats.  

Zoe would make a good running buddy and she'll also be your tv and chill partner as she loves to just lay where the pack is.  Zoe will use a crate, but she prefers a bed where the persons are.  She also loves bones and stuffed animals to play with when left alone.  She would benefit from more training, but does adhere to many commands (sit, stay, off).

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Max, and I came from a Texas shelter. I am a healthy, active, playful, tiny 3-year-old guy who has some special requirements for a new forever or foster home.  You see, I was adopted for a while, but I became very fearful in the busy home with some really big dogs that were temporarily living there, so I became very bitey when the people interacted with me. So I came back to my familiar surroundings and people and relaxed again. So I'm ready to give it another chance to find the right home for me. Here's what I think will be best for me:

- 1 or maybe 2 adult humans in a quiet home, but would love people who are not first time small dog owners
- no children in the home
- as much as I love running around with other small dogs, maybe if I could be the solo light of my person's life would be best
- my new people need to be willing to give me a week or two to feel safe and comfortable before trying to do a lot with me. I promise I'll become happy, but I'm a little dude who scares pretty easily. Can you kindof ignore me for a little while and let me come to you when I know you can be trusted?
- a securely fenced area for me is a must! I may become a walker someday, but I am fine taking care of business and playing in a little yard. 
- I'm fine in a comfy crate, that actually helps me feel safe. Or if you have a kitchen or laundry room that can be gated off, I would like that when you are gone, or if I need some relaxation time.

?? Let me know if you may have room in your patient heart for a silly little guy like me. ?

I am neutered, up to date on all my vaccines, and am microchipped.  My adoption fee is $350.00.  You can find the adoption application (required) here: http://cominischnauzerrescue.com/forms/vintage-dog-rescue-adoption-application/

animal.description:
Note from PSBR: Sasha has undergone an operation to remove multiple tiny mammary nodules.  The vet reported that the nodules are benign, but they may occur again and they should be removed should that happen.   


Sasha is a very sweet and gentle little love bug with no signs of aggression whatsoever, even when my Cockatiel walked two inches from her nose, she didn't bat an eye.

Sasha loves to snuggle in bed and will not move an inch while receiving belly rubs.

She's very good about going outside to use the W/C. but will still need to be watched for subtle clues that she needs to go out, like looking out the patio door or window or pacing.

She does bark at the neighbors dogs as she feels they get too close to her fence but does not bark in the house at all.  Squirrels entertain her!  She can sit and watch them for hours.

It is important thought that she starts on dry food to protect those beautiful pearly whites she has since her dentistry.

NB:  A fenced/locked yard or a perfect fitting harness and leash for walking is a must.  This little girl was originally from a puppy mill and even though she obeys most commands in the house and in the yard, if she sees an open door or gate she's gone forever, and all her obedience training goes out the window.   So please if you are planning on adopting this little angel keep these things in mind.  Do not be fooled by her willingness to please or you will loose her.

PSBR is looking for a home where Sasha can be the only dog. She loves the attention!
