animal.description:
As always, Duffy's Friends requires a vet reference in your name, not your parents, homeownership, fenced yard, and children if they live in the home, will be over the age of 12 years.  The adoption donation request for this dog is $200.00 for a completely vetted and sweet dog.  If you see this dog as available she is still looking for a home.  

Poppy is a dog that is going to be matched with a home that does not expect perfection.  She is for adoption through PAWS of Long Island and Animal Behavior Specialities.  Duffy's Friends is acting as the media to place this dog.  
 
Together these dedicated people have pulled Poppy from a negative past and put her back together again so that she might have the most wonderful home that was due to her the first time.

We believe her to be a 20 lb Cockapoo with maybe something else.  This little girl is 4 years old and could be a poodle, Shih Tzu, Lhasa, or another small dog breed.   She is a young dog with a love of bringing back the ball, hiking, and swimming.  She would be too much energy for an elderly family or a senior.  

What Poppy Needs:
A home that does not expect perfection.  She likes dogs but would be better as the only dog as she is a dominant female. She likes kids but we want them to be over 12 to take direction and follow the rules.  What are the rules?  

No furniture, all four feet on the floor. Being a dominant female If you want her to move she may find the opportunity to tell you off.  What is that in plain English?  No furniture - no elevation, no sleeping in bed with you.
  This could be a raised lip, a snarl, or an air snap.  To place this is in English - her reaction maybe a bite.   This is not unusual many dominant girls do that - this is not surprising. She also resource guards food so the solution is after she eats to pick up the food.  Now we have a future problem solved.    She is the perfect dog in every way, sweet, housebroken, spayed, up to date with vaccinations.  She is playful, likes to walk, and has first level dog obedience placed on her.  She is totally trained.  It's the furniture she can not be allowed to take over or your bed. 

Do you have the love to offer and follow the trainer's directions?  This is a great girl.  The groomer said she was so good for her professional spa day.  


Please apply on our website @ duffysfriends.org - if you have questions are email is duffysfriends@gmail.com.  Poppy has all her vaccinations and is spayed.

Hi, I’m Destiny, but you can call me Miss Independent! I am 13.5 years young (born April 2007) and I weigh ten pounds.  CRT has made sure that I am up to date on vaccines, had my heartworm test, got my microchip and take my monthly heartworm preventative. 

I get along well with other small dogs as long as they are docile, but I am too feisty for larger dogs, cats, or small children. I’m sweet, but I have a sassy side and will give you a little warning nip if I need my personal space. I prefer to dine alone so I can enjoy my food in peace, away from the other dogs.

As an older gal, I’ve earned my share of pampering! I like to be carried up and down the stairs and will wait patiently for you to carry me across hard flooring to the carpet I prefer. I require a strict potty schedule to avoid accidents in the house. I’m mostly crate trained, but I don’t like to be left alone for long periods of time.

I have a loud bark, and I’m not afraid to speak my mind if I hear loud noises or see neighbors in the yard! I’m told I’m a bit hard of hearing, so my foster family supervises me in the yard to keep me safe.  I love it when they let me explore outside or take me for walks or car rides.

I might take a little time to warm up to you, but once I do, I will be a loyal lap warmer and will curl up at the foot of your bed for a cozy snooze. I’m currently living in Wixom, Michigan, but I’d love to live out the rest of my years with you!

If you are interested in adopting Destiny, please DO NOT SEND A MESSAGE TO OUR RESCUE GROUP.  We are too busy placing dogs in great homes to answer messages and inquiries through the listing site.

www.chihuahua-rescue.com/adoption-application
 
CRT requires an approved adoption application and a home visit for all adoption applicants.  CRT transports to OH, KY, IL, MI, MN, WI.

**A BIG THANK YOU TO JESSICA HARVEY FOR PARTIALLY SPONSORING TIFFANY'S ADOPTION FEE**

**PLEASE NOTE - ADOPTERS INTERESTED IN TIFFANY MUST HAVE SIMILAR BREED EXPERIENCE AND A YARD. TIFFANY IS LOOKING FOR A HOME WITH NO YOUNG CHILDREN**

Tiffany is a 5 year old spayed female Alaskan Malamute who weighs about 78 lbs. Tiffany came to All 4 Paws from a commercial breeding facility when she was no longer needed for breeding purposes. After spending her life in a barn, Tiffany is so deserving of a wonderful family that will give her all the love and care she deserves. We have loved showing Tiffany just how great a dog's life can be! After everything she's been through, Tiffany can be a bit nervous with quick movements or loud noises. For this reason, she is looking for a quiet home without young children who may overwhelm her. True to her breed, she loves exploring outside, so her forever family must have a yard and experience with Malamutes. Tiffany has done well with the other dogs she's met with a proper, slow introduction. She excels when she has a job to do, and will bond with her people through training. Malamutes are working dogs and she is true to her core. She needs a family that understands the way to her heart isn't pets and hugs at first, it's requests and rewards. Tiffany is incredibly intelligent and eager to please. This gorgeous girl is so ready to join a loving home that will continue to teach her what it means to be a beloved member of the family. Please help us find Tiffany the forever home she deserves!

Interested in adopting? Take the first step and complete an adoption application on our website: https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/
We are a foster based organization, so we do not have a facility to visit. Please read our FAQs to learn more: https://www.all4pawsrescue.com/faq

animal.description:
Major is a very handsome and happy 8-10 year old silver Lab who found his way on a transport to our Florida Gulf Coast from a New Orleans animal shelter in the wake of the hurricanes that devastated so many communities across Louisiana in late summer.   

Major is a loving and handsome fellow who has settled in nicely to his foster home.  He is super affectionate and loves a nice soft couch to curl up in and space to dash around in.  His personality belies his age as he is active and loves taking walks, chasing geckos and fetching tennis balls.  He loves to cuddle and is very smart.  Major is intact, suffers from a heart murmur and color dilution alopecia (CDA) which is an inherited skin condition in dogs that have been bred to a diluted coat and results in permanent hair loss. His condition requires a committed adopter as he requires frequent medicated baths, a special diet and medication to manage his heart condition.  This guy deserves a second chance in a very special home to be loved and well-cared for and in return you’ll be loved unconditionally and with great enthusiasm.  

This wonderful boy from the Big Easy needs your help.  If you can give Major the love and attention that he deserves so much, please complete and application, get your home visit done, and come meet him in Venice.

animal.description:
Name: Spanky
Breed: pug/peke mix
Sex: Male
Age: 6 yr old
Color: Fawn, 
Weight: 18 lbs
Location: Fostered in The Villages 
Characteristics: full of life

Spanky is ready to be adopted!  He is a 6 yr old, 18 lb pug mix (we believe Pug and Pekingese). 

He is looking for a dog savvy forever home with time, patience and love.  This adorable little buddy is full of life and just needs the right home.   Like lots of old pugs, he does have rear end weakness.  He is what he is, he just needs a human who can love him in spite of the fact he is not perfect.   

He needs to be walked regularly to keep his muscle strength up.  He is currently receiving acupuncture treatments and we are hopeful he will benefit from them like a lot of our fosters have.   

He gets along with most dogs, but he is part Pekinese and wants to be the boss.  So best thing would be an only dog home or one with an old small dog that doesn’t care if he’s the boss.   He is afraid and anxious of small children and we are afraid he will nip them so no kids.  

As you can see from his original bio, he does love his humans once he knows they can be trusted.   What happen to this boy in the past, we will never know but he is adorable and he will do good in the right home. 

Of course, when we got Spanky we did everything we could for him to give him the best forever life he could have and he is a happy little toy playing boy.   We made two trips to North Florida Neurology in Jacksonville and paid for Spanky to have an MRI to determine for sure what Spanky’s back issues were.  We were hopeful he could benefit from a stabilization surgery but after the MRI and discusses with the Neurologist, it was decided that the best course of action for Spanky was not surgery.  Therefore, he is receiving and will probably need to continue on a more holistic approach.  Exercise by his human and acupuncture treatments by a certified acupuncture vet.   Many regular vets have this service but not all are certified so we will be happy to help you find a good service provider in your area.

If you are the home Spanky is looking for PLEASE apply today to adopt him.  He’s ready to be loved by his forever human.  Complete an adoption application today: https://pugrescueofflorida.org/adopt

ORIGINAL BIO - June 2020
A few years ago he was one of our foster pups and was adopted by his loving mom. Unfortunately, his mom passed away -- the family tried to help by keeping Spanky, but it just wasn't a good fit, so they called us and we were happy to help. Since Spanky has been back with us we have worked to understand some of his issues and get him the care he needs. 

We determined that Spanky had some problems with his back which caused him trouble walking with his back legs. 

When Spanky came into PROoF he was also fearful and had little trust for humans. During the first 2 weeks in his foster home Spanky would growl, snap, and attempt to bite anyone that came near him (even his fur foster siblings), especially if they came towards his face. He would not allow his humans to wipe or clean him.  With time and patience, Spanky slowly began to trust his humans, allowing them to even cuddle and touch him. He even began to bond with the other pugs in his foster home and now goes on short walks with them outside. Currently Spanky allows his foster family to cuddle with him and rub his face and ears. 

As Spanky has started to trust everyone around him, his foster family as begun to see his adorable personality come through. He is a playful little guy -- he loves squeaky toys and chases them around the house. Despite his small size he has a big personality! He now enjoys belly rubs and rolling around on the floor to play with his toys. Spanky is very smart and quickly learns the house routine. With his short stubby Peke legs and stout Pug body, Spanky waddles along for short walks with his humans. He likes to sleep on the floor with all 4 paws pointing up in the air -- a very funny pose! 

Spanky's wonderful foster family is giving him the time and space to gain trust and confidence every day. In addition to helping him build his confidence it was critical that PROoF help with his medical care.  He will visit a neurologist soon to determine the best plan for helping him with his back end weaknesses.  

If you love me but can't adopt me please consider making a donation to rescue to help pay medical bills for not just me but my fellow foster brothers and sisters.

My Rescue friends are working very hard to find me and the other foster pugs new homes, so please be sure to submit an application before contacting them.

More information and  applications are available at WWW.PUGRESCUEOFFLORIDA.ORG

animal.description:
Sugar was adopted from a shelter in Texas after she was found roaming as a stray. She was adopted by someone who hoped to train them as livestock guardians but she decided that she liked living indoors rather than outdoors. Sugar made her way to New Jersey and was adopted, however Sugar never adjusted to “city living” she is a country girl through and through.

Sugar is back in Texas and still looking for that perfect home. Her ideal home would be a farm environment without a lot of visitors. She is looking for a place where she can lounge outdoors during the day while keeping an eye on the property, then hang with her people indoors at night.

Sugar is around 1.5 to 2 years old and weighs 75 pounds. She is crate trained and house trained. Sugar does well walking on a leash and does well in a vehicle. We would be willing to transport her to NJ, but it really has to be the perfect home for her. She cannot be in a home with children or even young adults. If you are a looking for a mellow independent dog please apply now and be sure to mention “Sugar".

Apply to adopt at bigdogrescueproject.org/adopt.

animal.description:
Name: Duchess
Breed: Puggle (Pug, Beagle)
Sex: Female
Color: apricot
Age: 10 yrs old
Weight: 33 lbs but needs to lose a few more to get to her goal weight
Location: Fostered in the Tampa area
Characteristics: Sweet puggle girl with lots of love to give!

This super sweet puggle girl is looking for a forever family to treat her like royalty! Duchess is 10 yrs and is ready to show her new family a lot of love. 

Duchess is a happy girl who makes friends easily -- she is enjoying the company of the people and pets in her foster home. She would do best with older kids and gets along well with other dogs. 

She enjoys car rides and is always up for a new adventure. She is also a fan of short walks when the weather is nice and true to her pug genes, is a velcro pup and likes to follow her humans around the house. She is happy lounging just about anywhere, but her favorite spot is on her dog beds (she would love to have one in every room!). 

When Duchess came into rescue, she was very overweight and had a honking cough which is a common condition with her collapsing trachea. The good news is that our foster families and vets are very experienced with these conditions and she is getting great care.  She is on medication to help control her cough and she is making strides to getting to her goal weight so she can live her best life.  Duchess is looking for a family that can continue helping her with her weight loss and cough management.  She is up to date on her vaccines, spayed, potty trained and is heartworm negative. 

Duchess would do well with other dogs, or she would be fine as an only dog so she can get all of the attention for herself.  If you are looking for a sweet puggle with a great personality welcome into your family, Duchess might me your love match!  You can complete an adoption application today at https://pugrescueofflorida.org/adopt

If you love me but can't adopt me please consider making a donation to rescue to help pay medical bills for not just me but my fellow foster brothers and sisters.

My Rescue friends are working very hard to find me and the other foster pugs new homes, so please be sure to submit an application before contacting them.

More information and  applications are available at WWW.PUGRESCUEOFFLORIDA.ORG

animal.description:
This sweet litter of 4 were rescued from a drainage ditch.  

With a guesstimated birthday in March 2020, these sweets ones have gone from scared to affectionate.  

Tag was adopted, but someone in his family developed allergies.  He's a happy guy and is enjoying the dogs at his foster home.  He doesn't seem to pay any attention to the cats.

Tag's becoming even more familiar with crating and leash walking.  He hasn't had an accident, but is being kept to a regular schedule of walks every hour to reinforce his manners.

April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs and adoption events aren't being held at Tractor Supply in Lenoir.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience through another rescue or your local government-run animal control..

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

animal.description:
Koala spent the first 5 years of her life tied on a chain in the back yard, being bred over and over and suffering from heartworm. Despite her bad past, she is a very loving dog. She absolutely loves other dogs and kids and will follow them around, just to be near them. She can be a little leery of adults, especially men, but she does warm up, especially if there is another dog around to show her everything is ok. Since she spent her first 5 years outside, she never had to worry about where she was supposed to go potty, so she will need someone to be patient while she learns to always go outside. She is doing well if taken out regularly. She loves to chew on toys and is very food motivated. She does know some basic commands and loves to give kisses to her friends.

Please visit www.handsheartspaws.org for an adoption application

All of our dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed/neutered, microchipped, fecal tested, heartworm tested, and they are all on heartworm and flea/tick preventative.

The adoption process is an application, a vet reference, a home visit, and a lifetime contract. The requested adoption donation for this dog is $350___.

We do not REQUIRE a fenced in yard (some dogs DO REQUIRE a fence.  Decide what is best for each dog), we do REQUIRE a means of safe outside containment.  We do NOT adopt to homes that use invisible fencing.  Invisible fencing is NOT a safe means of outside containment.

We are willing to adopt out-of-state, contingent on our ability to complete a home visit, but you must travel to Omaha to complete the adoption. We do not transport or ship our dogs.

animal.description:
Meet Magic, a very handsome English Cream Golden Retriever. His birthday is March 11, 2020, so still a puppy. 

Magic went to a home with kids from the breeders house but when the kids would start screaming and running around, Magic had the reaction of biting one of the kids. He was returned to the breeders home where the same thing happened again when the kids got running around screaming like kids do. So of course the home we are going to require for Magic should have no children at all. 

Magic is a great example of why we have an age limit with children for the dogs we adopt into great homes. Kids are no matter what going to behave like kids and dogs do not always appreciate the kids behavior. For many dogs, fast movements and screaming can be scary. Dogs do not necessarily think it is cute when the kid lies on top of them or tries to take things out of their mouth. The result is the dog losing their home or worse and sometimes a child ends up with a lifelong fear of dogs. 

Magic is housebroken, doesn't try to destroy the house when left unsupervised, and is just a sweetheart of a boy. He hasn't done any counter surfing at all. He does need a little work on sharing toys if it is something he values but with training this can be resolved. 

Magic was doing great in his foster home. He was living with 8 other dogs, but this was just too much activity for Magic. He will also need work walking on a leash. The family who would like to adopt him will be required to take him to a trainer. This is not because he is so unruly or bad, but so we know the lucky family that gets to adopt this boy will be committed to making sure Magic is the great family member we know he will be. He will also need a physical fenced yard. 

Magic is now in a foster home where he is going to a trainer and is doing great! He is figuring out he is not the boss and is doing well being in a much quieter environment with only one other dog that is older. He isn't ready to be able to be adopted yet, but is making excellent progress. 

We hope he will stay in his current foster home to be adopted finally when ready. If he becomes available for adoption, we will let you know both here and on our Facebook page. 

To adopt a Golden that you see here, please go to the Golden Retriever Rescue Resource website at www.gr-rescue.org  Read our adoption policies. If you qualify for this dogs adoption and the adoption policies, please write us for an adoption application at grrradoption@yahoo.com  Please provide your city and zip code. Please note, we only adopt to select areas within Ohio, Michigan and Indiana where we can do a home visit by a trusted volunteer. 

Please read our adoption policies on our website prior to inquiring for an adoption application. Thank you!

***COURTESY POST***

******These pets are NOT ASSOCIATED with NEVADA COUNTY PAWS *****

(PLEASE INCLUDE A BIO WHEN INQUIRING) - required 

Dakota and Mohawk - The Bonded Pair 

Come meet this “BEAUTIFUL” the brother - sister duo!  They are two of the sweetest and beautiful pups you may ever come across. These two will round out to be great companions and/or family dogs with minimal training and guidance. 

They are both very loving and get attached to people quite quickly even though they and they love “their” people.

Mohawk: 

He is very sweet, loves attention and seeks confirmation. He needs some training to teach him not to jump on you (which he has already improved on with just a little consistent correction) and needs ongoing socialization with other dogs. He is not outwardly aggressive but can be guarded at times. He has already improved in a very short period of time with his current foster.


Dakota: 

She is twice as sweet as her brother.. She plants herself in the cutest little sitting pose in front of you waiting for your attention.  

She is deaf and has not been taught any sign language but is beginning to learn and picking up cues quite quickly.  She always looks for her people When she is out of your site line even if she is with Mohawk.

She will continue to blossom if her new owner would be continue training her with sign language communication. 


Ideal Home:

Active family, they love to play and stay active and would be great hikers.  They like to be with their family instead of being left alone.  A family that would have 1 adult home daily for continued basic training.

They are both crate trained, eating well and settling in well. They had high anxiety in the beginning of being crated and separated from their handler, but are much more calm and settled now. 

We predict this pair will develop into obedient and loving pups that will make great.  They would most likely be great dogs to take camping, hiking, lakeside, park and beach excursions as they like to stay close to their people and could most likely be off leash dogs in appropriately safe settings with the EXCEPTION that Dakota would need to wear a remote response training collar for her safety as she can not hear verbal QUES.

These two will make really great dogs with little effort just some consistency and patience. IF you meet this criteria, please don’t hesitate to email to set up a meet and greet to further consider these two as new family members!

Ricochet Rabbit is a goofy boy that loves to play and has puppy-like energy. He is an extremely loyal, athletic dog, best in a home with lots of room to run with a fenced yard and a dog savvy adopter who will play with him and continue his training. His foster says he everyone that he meets. He is a hound mix estimated to be around 2 years old, weighing 50 lbs. His fosters also reports that he is the best behaved foster ever! Being a hound he does have a strong prey drive, so a fenced yard is a must but he is not a barky hound. Here's more awesome personality and behavior info about him.

 housebroken, crate trained, quiet in his crate, but excellent loose in the house
 loves mealtime & food motivated, sits for his food and attaching/detaching a leash
 knows sit, down, stay, comes when called , and shakes paw
 loves snuggling his humans to watch a movie and likes down time to chew a bone
 enjoys running his yard, playing with other dogs, going on walks or jogs but needs a strong owner to run with
 he is easy going where he loves a chin or belly scratch, does well being brushed and having his nails trimmed

Click here To see me showing off my tricks and here to see me having fun playing catch me if you can with my friends! 

 gets along great with other dogs that he has met and is very playful
 best with confident well behaved dogs in the home
 however can be protective on leash if he is with a passive handler.

 best in a home with older children since his energy level is high
 gets excited easily so best in a quiet neighborhood
 best in a cat free home


Does this adorably good looking guy sound like the right dog for you and your home?? If so, he would LOVE to meet you and go to a FOREVER home!
To adopt this dog, or any OPH dog, fill out the simple online application at https://ophrescue.org 
Operation Paws for Homes, Inc. (OPH) rescues dogs of all breeds and ages from high-kill shelters in NC, VA, MD, and SC, reducing the numbers being euthanized. With limited resources, the shelters are forced to put down 50-90% of the animals that come in the front door. OPH provides pet adoption services to families located in VA, DC, MD, PA and neighboring states. OPH is a 501(c)(3) organization and is 100% donor funded. OPH does not operate a shelter or have a physical location. We rely on foster families who open their homes to give love and attention to each dog before finding a forever home.

animal.description:
We were alerted to a very pregnant mama that we believe to be abandoned. A nice group of neighbors came together to care for this pup and had been feeding her and giving her fresh water for the last few weeks. Unfortunately, none of them were able to allow her inside, and she had been living unsecured on a front porch for weeks. As her belly became more swollen, they realized that she was about to give birth and reached out for help. We knew we needed to get mama to Grace quickly so she can give birth in a safe and comfortable environment. Roxy was the name given to her by the kind people caring for her, and we think it fits her perfectly. 

We think Roxy is about 2 years old and, like most pups we rescue, is heartworm positive. But she won't be able to start treatment until after her puppies finish nursing for the safety of the puppies. Roxy has likely lived her entire life on the streets and is bow-legged in the front due to malnutrition as a pup. Right now, we won't be taking any corrective action because it isn't causing her discomfort. We will be looking into additional options to help her after the puppies are weaned. We are elated that she is off the streets and will deliver her pups safely, surrounded by the love from our Streetdog Pack. 

On August 25, Roxy gave birth to 8 perfect puppies! There are 6 girls and 2 boys plus #sdftopaz who crossed the rainbow bridge shortly after birth. She is obsessed with her babies and doesn't even want to leave them to go outside. She rushes right back in as soon as she can! She has started barking at other dogs that walk by her kennel to let them know to stay away from her beloved babies but isn't showing any aggression. The vet tech team let us know that she remains very sweet and trusts them to enter her kennel and care for her puppies. 

Girls:

Amber 

Amethyst

Beryl (Beh-ruhl)

Garnet

Jade

Marble

Boys:

Mica

Slate 

*Behaviors not listed have yet to be tested.

animal.description:
Barks and Meows Rescue introduces Bruce.  He is an 8-year-old loving Coonhound who loves ever8-year-old has a short hair coat and weighs 72lb.  He was found as a stray. Bruce is hearing impaired but hears fine if you raise your voice.  He has done well in a home where he has other dogs to keep him company and someone home most of the time.  He currently lives in the country and has a large fenced property to go outside in.  He is good with the other dogs but ignores them.  This is unusual for a Coonhound so it may be due to his hearing impairment.  We believe regardless, he enjoys having other dogs around.  Bruce is very sweet and loves to be cuddled and kissed.  He is housebroken and prefers company when going outside in the yard, either the other dogs or the foster family.  Thunderstorms do not appear to bother him.  Bruce loves his mealtime and is fed twice daily both canned and dry.  He loves going for walks and car rides.  He is a creature of habit and will start barking if something changes in the schedule.  We have found it best to sneak out of the house so he doesn't bark at the door.  Bruce is a good boy at the vets.  He loves children of all ages.  He sleeps in an open crate but crating is not necessary for this boy.  He is not destructive in the home at all.  We are sure he has a typical Coonhound prey drive with cats but have not tested him with it.  In his current foster home, the only time he barks non stop is when his meals are being prepared. The ideal home for Bruce is one where the family is retired or there is a family member home full time.  Another dog is best but only for companionship as he doesn't have any interest in playing with other dogs.  He is good with all sizes of dogs.  Having experience with the Coonhound breed is an asset. Bruce is neutered, up to date with vaccines, 4dx tested negative, and has a dental cleaning scheduled Friday, October 9.  He is on heartworm/flea prevention monthly. A fully fenced yard, another resident dog in the home, someone home full time, and a Veterinarian History of Compliance are mandatory in order to apply for our Bruce.

Open to Canadian Residents only.

Visit barksandmeows.ca for an online application.

animal.description:
Seniors are the best! Meet Badger! Badger is an 8 year old male beagle who was relinquished by his owner with his buddy Missy (also available for adoption). Its taken Badger a bit to warm up to his foster family. He can still be very cautious and scared sometimes when approached too quickly or unexpectedly. Once he gets to know you he REALLY enjoys being loved on, petted and belly scratched. Badger may be a bit hard of hearing which may explain why he is easily startled.

Badger may be 8 years old but he still gets the zoomies about once a day and flies around the yard or house looking to play. Badger likes going for walks and is good on a leash, but prefers a collar rather than a harness. Badger does well with other dogs and has been with his friend Missy for sometime. Both dogs could be adopted together as they are already good buddies.

Badger is kennel trained but does fuss a bit when he is first put in the kennel. He does settle down after a little while. Pretty sure this guy had it rough before being rescued and you can tell he is just so happy to be loved and paid attention to. Badger is vocal, he grunts and groans and huffs and puffs. Its so cute.

Badger likes to lay around and snooze, but he does need something to do throughout the day. If left unattended for extended periods or left out in the yard for a long time he will start barking. Mostly out of boredom. Once you call him or pay attention to him for a bit he will settle down. Badger would do good with a family that is around and where there is some action, but he is not your running dog, his older hips and legs just can't keep up for too long.

Badger is neutered, microchipped, up to date on shots. He is fostered in the Omaha area and his adoption fee is $300.00. You can fill out an application today at https://www.bassetandbeagle.org/adoptionapplication/

animal.description:
Suki is a mixed-breed dog approximately 3 1/2 years old. She is friendly, knows basic commands and is house/crate trained.  She was released to us in September 2020 by her owner when they could no longer afford to care for her, then returned in mid-January 2021 because her adopter's roommate's dog wasn't getting along with Suki.
So Suki is in need of a truly forever home — a special human/family who will understand how stressful it is for her to be left at the shelter twice. 
Suki is a real sweetheart who is coming out of her shell (again!). She loves to cuddle, but she is not super outgoing and sometimes nervous and will need some nurturing to feel safe again. 
Suki will do best in a home with children over 12 and with no cats. She would prefer to be an only dog.
She has been heartworm tested negative, spayed, and is current on vaccinations. She has a docked tail and weighs about 60 pounds. You will receive health records and a bag of Science Diet food upon adoption. Adoption donation $120. 

The Clinton County Humane Society is a no-kill, nonprofit, volunteer-based organization. We do not receive county or government funding and depend on our adoption donations to fund the shelter. Please complete the pre-adoption questionnaire at clintoncohumanesociety.org. We will contact you via email.

animal.description: Hi my name is Sam! I am an amazingly intelligent boy looking for a master to please. I pick up commands really fast and will do anything you ask of me. I would make a perfect K9 buddy for law enforcement. I would pass any test you have for me as a top student. I have lots of energy as I am a working breed who likes to be active, but I’m also down for chilling on the couch with my person. I enjoy all the attention  I can get. Due to my strong build and herding breed, I would not do well with small children, they would be much too easy for me to accidentally knock down. I would prefer a single person or a couple without kids and the only pet. Cats & small dogs are not my cup of tea, so I cannot be around them or live with them. I am not a candidate for dog parks as I want to be boss of all dogs (hey, I'm a big German Shepherd, I cant help myself!). I need an EXPERIENCED dog owner, preferably one with a history of German Shepherd or Belgian Malanois ownership. I also require a fenced yard so I can run & play to my heart's content! Please adopt me so I can start the next chapter in life with my very own home! Sam is a male German Shepherd (appears to be purebred), weighs 80 lbs and was born approximately 8/18/2017. He is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, given flea/tick preventive, dewormed. Sam has been given life-saving treatment for heartworm disease. He will need to remain on heartworm preventive for life, as is recommended for ALL dogs, and retested in 6 months to ensure he is heartworm free. Adoption fee is $300 to help offset the many expenses we have for vetting costs. We rely strictly on adoption fees and donations to continue to save the lives of orphaned & abandoned pets; 100% goes towards their care. If interested in adopting one of our available dogs or puppies, please complete an online adoption application at https://dollyslegacyanimalrescue.org/adopt/ You will be contacted by our adoption coordinator via email after your application has been reviewed & approved to schedule an appointment.

Cooper is a 5-year-old, 80ish-lb hound mix. Cooper came to Mutts from a home where he was kept outside in a pen and ultimately abandoned. Despite his rough start, Cooper is an absolute love bug and a gentle giant. He is very sweet, people and dog-friendly, affectionate, housebroken, and crate trained. Cooper loves taking naps, but he also gets bursts of energy when he gets to go on walks or jogs. He also really enjoys spending time around people, snuggling, getting treats, going outside, saying hello to other dogs, and watching people and animals from his foster home's front window. Cooper would love to lay back and enjoy life with his forever family! Cooper would do best in a home without children

**BECAUSE OF OUR REQUIREMENT FOR A HOME VISIT, WE ARE ONLY ABLE TO ADOPT TO HOMES IN THE NORTHERN VA / MARYLAND / DC METRO AREA**

We have adoption events EVERY SATURDAY from 12-3 p.m. Please note that not all dogs can attend every event, so if you are interested in meeting a particular dog, please complete a no-obligation application on our website at http://www.muttloverescue.org/application.html OR write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

Upcoming adoption events:

Mutt Love Rescue is doing everything we can to ensure the health and safety of our volunteers and adopters while continuing our mission to find homes for as many dogs as possible.

Effective immediately, we will not be holding our weekly adoption events. Dogs available for adoption can be met by appointment only. Potential adopters should submit an online application at http://muttloverescue.org/application.html. Once we receive your application, we will contact you to let you know the next steps.

We are always desperate for foster homes, now more than ever. If you are interested in fostering during this difficult time, please complete an application... unless you are a previous adopter/foster, then you can just contact us via phone (703-988-2608) or email (adopt@muttloverescue.org) to tell us which dog you want to foster!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Golden Gate who is called "Cash" is one handsome boy. He was relinquished due to separation anxiety in that he just could not be alone. He is in a foster home with other greyhounds and doing well. He is not quite 2 years old. He will need a home with another greyhound and a fenced yard where he can relax and enjoy himself. He really is a very sweet guy.

Foster Update, November 2020

Cash is a tall, very handsome boy who loves people and toys. He gets along well with cats (with mild correction when he tries to engage them in play).

He suffers from separation anxiety and general anxiety. He will require a quiet home where someone will be home most of the time. He will also need a home with other greyhounds. He pulls strength from their confidence and lead. He does not like non-greyhounds and has a possessive/protective side as well.

Cash loves to run and do zoomies, so a fenced yard is a must. He also enjoys his walks once he is slowly introduced to his route accompanied with his pack. Their confidence helps him in all situations.

Cash sleeps like a baby, eats very well and accepts calm, patient direction. He does not react well to loud noises, new situations, etc. He truly is a sweet, loving dog who wants so much to please. Patience, structure and calm, experienced leadership will bring out his best.

___________________________________Original Posting_______________________

Golden Gate is a very handsome, good-sized boy. He is the sibling to Golden Globe who arrived with Golden Gate. He is a calm boy who is slightly reserved at first but warms up and will give little kisses. He is a baby at only 17 months of age, so he will need some TLC and he will learn. He is a sweet boy and was described as a "gentle giant" which aptly describes Golden Gate. He is cat tolerant with supervision. He walks nicely on leash but is somewhat fearful to cross door thresholds--with some patience, he will learn to not be fearful.

animal.description:
Bichon Frise
Female, 14 years old, 10 pounds

Graciela (aka Gracie) is the sweetest little thing! She will patiently allow you to pick her up and can meet just about any dog with no issues (other than quite a lot of eager excitement!) Gracie is clearly a dog who pines to be devoted to her human - she wants to know where you are and to be with you all around the house. She's the BEST snuggle buddy on the couch! Her foster mom says Gracie seems to be anxious when left alone, which may be related to adjusting to her new surroundings. This little pup is a perfect match for someone who is mostly at home and would like a devoted companion! 

She loves having free access to a yard, and knows how to use a doggy door. If you are looking for an excuse to get fresh air and exercise, Gracie is what you need! She happily goes on 2 mile daily walks at a brisk pace. Because Gracie was hit by a car 3 years ago, she has just the slightest wiggle in her gait, but this does not slow her down. She does love to stop to smell the roses, too, and thinks she's a mighty hunter when she spots squirrels. Gracie's a bit too fond of chasing cats, so a kitty-free home is probably best for her. Gracie's foster says "she sure doesn't seem like a 14 year old dog to me - I hope I age as well as Gracie!" Maybe you two could age "gracefully" together? 

Graciela came to us because her senior guardian's health is declining and she can no longer care for a dog.

animal.description:
Olivia von Oelsnitz is a beautiful 1-2 year old Shepherd mix. This is a fun, happy girl with a positive outlook on life. She comes out of her kennel happy, wagging her tail, and ready for new experiences.  She does great on her walks with other dogs,  meeting new dogs well, though retreating from the pushy ones, whom she finds a bit scary.  Olivia has such an affectionate and easy going personality and so loves attention that she follows you around in search of more! With her medium energy, she does great in play groups, joining them relaxed and comfortable and full of optimism. She loves to play fetch and appears to be a water dog, since she went directly into the kiddie pool the first time in playgroup. With her adorable play bow, she invites other dogs to join her in friendly games. She has a great time with dogs and people, as is just as she expects, given her sunny, rosy view of life.  You too will make new friends with convivial Olivia on the end of your leash! ( No cats for Olivia please!)

animal.description: Skye came to us very skittish with a litter of puppies. She was a transfer in from Mohave animal shelter and was seized from a hoarder house. She was living in an airline crate for most of her life and when she had her puppies they were in there together. Having very little social interaction with others, she is very shy and nervous with new people and dogs. She does like other dogs but gets overwhelmed easily. Skye lacks confidence and needs guidance in her next steps. At the shelter, she has been through leash training and understands for the most part but will occasionally roll and flinch at loud noises. Skye needs a home with someone experienced who will be patient with her and be willing to walk her through everything and help her build her confidence. She would thrive better in a quiet home without a lot of people coming and going. One minor issue we have not been able to break her of quiet yet is she nervously pees very often, for this reason it would be better for her to have a carpet free home. She also must be supervised while in a yard until she is comfortable as she can and will jump a seven foot fence. If you still think this blue- eyed- beauty is a good fit for your home, feel free to come meet her at the shelter. She is very worth it

animal.description:
Daisy - Female - 3-years-old - #802

Daisy is a 3-year-old Golden mix, 65 pounds, abandoned out in the country several months ago. A kind family took her in and cared for her as best they could before they reached out to GRRALL for help in finding her a forever family. Daisy, like many of our rescues, is heartworm positive. She is undergoing treatment and will be ready for adoption in a couple of months. Our vet thinks she likely had several litters of puppies before she was dumped by her previous owners. Daisy's foster family describes her as an outgoing and happy girl. She LOVES her humans and is always by their side and ready for snuggles. Daisy is currently in a home with another Golden, but we think she'd prefer to be the only pup in the home so she can be the center of attention.

If you are interested in adopting Nora or any GRRALL dog, please read our FAQs (https://grralliance.org/faq/) and submit an application at https://grralliance.org/applications/adoption-application/

GRRALL serves the Dallas-Fort Worth/North Texas area. We do not have the resources to adopt outside this region and do not ship dogs. If you are outside our adoption area please contact your local Golden Retriever Rescue, local independent adoption groups, shelters, humane society, or other group to find your perfect forever friend.

animal.description:
Meet Ace! 

Ace is a handsome dobie boy that is 3 years old. He was surrendered because he intimidated his original homes guests.  See, Ace tries to intimidate new people but he us actually a goof!  He has some insecurities which is why he will bark or growl at times. Once Ace knows you are not scared of him, he is a big mush ball. 

Ace is looking for a home to continue his training, socialization and confidence building. Ace loves his humans HARD.  We are looking for an experienced home for this boy.  One that has patience but also understands alpha dynamics.  Ace has really proven to be a great dog in foster care. He respects men more than women and needs a firm owner that can set boundaries.  

Ace is okay with female dogs, but he can be rude in his play. He will muzzle punch and play bow. The dogs in his foster home are older and are not appreciative of that. We would place him with a tolerant female potentially or as an only dog. Kids 15 and up for Ace. He is currently with children but is not very respectful of their boundaries.  Cats are a no go as this big guy has a prey drive. 

Ace is going to make an amazing addition for the RIGHT home. 

Application Www.zoeshouserescue.com 
Adoption fee $400

Akela is a 4 year old neutered male Akita/Husky mix.  He was placed into rescue after demonstrating some guarding issues which worried his family.  Akela is excited, independent and active.  He seems to be good with strangers and engages in attention and petting.  He will be too much for little kids as he is over exuberant on his greetings and does protect items he feels are high quality.  Akela is ok with other dogs but would prefer a home with a female dog or as a solo dog. Breed experience is required as Akita and Nordic breeds are not for everyone.  Akela can be aloof and uninterested in training and learning so really needs someone committed to understanding dog behavior and the use of positive training.  Akela is house trained and should be crated/confined when no one is home.

Adoption fee: $300
Date of birth: 10/2016
Weight: ~75 lbs.

animal.description:
My name is Juniper or Juni for short. I was found at Independence Animal Hospital one morning when staff arrived for work. Somebody threw me over the 6 ft fence after hours. I survived that physically uninjured and the next morning the nice people at the hospital found me and took me to the local shelter where I could be taken care of. The people who owned me had not been very nice to me as I was very shy and withdrawn. Thankfully the mean people did not come to get me and the shelter contacted my rescue to work with me on building trust so I would be ready for my furever home. 

My rescue thinks I'm a Great Pyrenees/Husky mix. I have one beautiful blue eye and one that's part brown and part blue. My eyes used to look sad, but my foster dad has really helped me come out of my shell. I'm still on the shy side but I've made a lot of progress! I enjoy attention and if my foster dad stops petting my me I gently nudge him with my nose. I love other dogs and enjoy greeting them and am learning how to play. High energy dogs make me a bit nervous so I would really like a calm dog to play with in my home. I need my people to have patience with my shyness and to use soft voices when speaking. Loud voices scare me. My foster dad says I never have accidents in the house and I will sit on command. I also really enjoy going on walks and am great on a leash. I will come to you spayed, microchipped, up to date on vaccines, up to date on heartworm and flea/tick preventatives. 

Applicants must have a secure and visible fence. In order for your application to be approved you must pass a home check and vet check which includes having at least a two year vet history. I can be adopted in Missouri and surrounding states: Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Nebraska, and Arkansas. My rescue is able to transport me to those states. If you would like to give me a Furever home, please fill out an application on my Rescue's website. 

Being fostered in Holden, MO

animal.description:
INDIE
DOB: 02.17.2019*

Indie was found wandering alone on the 106-degree streets of Bakersfield.  She was skinny, scared, seeking kindness and a safe place to stay.  She is one of the sweetest dogs you’ll ever meet and is always ready to shower you with affection.  She will happily sit her 65-pound body on your lap, cuddle up next to you on the couch and/or lay by your side in bed. She’s had a tough life and deserves to be in a home with a person/people who will appreciate these endearing qualities and give her lots of love and affection in return.

Her foster family fell in love with Indie but couldn’t keep her because one of their dogs was reactive. Indie was a sweetheart to him, but he wasn’t receptive.  Also, their 2nd dog was about to go through amputation surgery due to cancer and having a new dog in our home during her recovery would be too stressful for all involved. Indie stayed with this foster for one week, and then came to Paw Printz where she’s been able to interact with lots of other dogs.

Housetrained and crate trained. Good house manners (hasn’t chewed on personal items, taken food off counters, knocked things over or dug in the yard in our care).

Gets along well with dogs but would also do fine in a home without other dogs because she loves people so much. Has done well with young teenagers. Not sure about smaller children because we haven't had her around them.

She is a Pitty mix, possibly mixed with Plott Hound or Rottweiler. When she was first found, she was extremely stressed from being abandoned. She expressed her anxiety by going in circles, chasing her tail. We have been able to help her get beyond this stress-based behavior by providing her with a stable environment and through positive behavior modification. She is thriving now and ready for her forever home!  This incredible pup is full of unconditional love and is anxious to share it with her future adopters!

High energy, would be a good walking/hiking/running partner. Has a playful, goofy side. Loves to run around the yard and play fetch. Very smart, learns quickly, minds well.

Indie is spayed, she tested negative for heartworms and is now on Sentinel Spectrum to prevent heartworms, has been microchipped, cleared a veterinary wellness exam and is current on her vaccinations.

As with all Paw Printz dogs, we will provide free training, if any is needed in her new home, and we will take her back at any time if it doesn’t work out for any reason.

If you think Indie would be the perfect addition to your home, send an email to: PawPrintzRescue@gmail.com and request an application.

Adoption Fee: $200
Adoption Requirements: Application, Interview, Homecheck

THIS DOG IS LOCATED NEAR FRESNO, CA

*Age is always a guess with rescue dogs but here at Paw Printz we believe everyone should have a birth day so when the vet guesses at their age, we work out what would be a good birthday for each dog and make it so!

animal.description:
Tulip was an owner surrender along with Dak, however, they are not a bonded pair.  She is a very thin young lady.  We have been unable to have her spayed, due to her being so underweight.  Her fecal showed that she had whip worms, which has taken quite a bit of her calories.  We have medicated her for the whip worms and believe we will be able to spay her in November.  She needs to be the only dog or can be with large dogs, no homes with small dogs or cats.  Tulip is current on all vaccinations, housetrained and heartworm negative.  She is healthy other than being underweight and worms.  Tulip has more of a short to medium coat, which is a wash and wear Saint as she is easy to groom.  She knows her name and will come to you when she is called.  We believe her to be approximately 5 years old.  

In concern for families with small children, we will not adopt a dog to a home with any child under the age of 5. This is due to the large size of Saint Bernards and the safety of your children. Our Saint Bernards are not aggressive or mean in any way, they can just knock down children easily. If you would like to visit our pups please contact St. Cloud's Rescue at www.stcloudsrescue.org or call 972-679-5319. The first step in adopting from St. Cloud's Rescue is to complete an application. The application may be found OUR WEBSITE at www.stcloudsrescue.org. Please click on the application process, complete and then email it. Once the application has been sent please call us to confirm that we have received it. St.Cloud's Rescue maintains the right to deny applications to anyone for any reason we see fit. St. Cloud Rescue is a non-profit 501-c-3 organization. St. Clouds Rescue requires new owners to purchase a one year supply of heartworm preventative from us, which is at cost. We require a home visit prior to all placements. All our dogs must be microchipped at a cost of $20.00. There is a $250.00 donation fee. All dogs adopted through St Clouds Rescue must be indoors. St. Bernards can not tolerate the Texas heat.

animal.description:
****PETronus Rescue endeavors to include all pertinent information for each of the dogs within our organization with regard to approximate age, potty training status, kennel training status, temperament, activity level, dog/cat friendliness, etc in an effort to give those considering adopting as much information as we have.  Inquiries requesting additional information will not be returned, due to limited volunteers. Thank you for your understanding **** 

This is Jax.

Jax came to us after being put on “the list” at one of our local mandatory intake shelters that is constantly overcrowded. He is estimated to be about 4- 5years old, currently weighs 70 lbs, and is quite tall for his breed. He must be mixed with a dog that is traditionally taller than a staffy for sure!

Jax does well on a leash but will push his limits and accepts redirection like a champ, he is good with all people and female dogs, with a proper introduction of course and a bit of redirection if he gets over excited. He is a ladies man and says no male dogs please. He is not a dog park dogs but would do well with a semi-active to active family. Definitely not a couch potato but can be chill once his energy needs are met. Due to his size and energy, he would do best in a home with older children. 

He loves “playing” ball but prefers football vs fetch. I remedy this by having 2 tennis balls, 1 to throw and 1 to distract him with once he retrieves the first, so he will drop it. He is so much fun in the yard!

Jax does have storm anxiety but we can guide you on making him comfortable and keeping him safe during storms.  If he can be with you, he is fine. If he is in a crate or alone, he can be destructive and vocal. Wouldn’t recommend and apartment dweller for this reason and would require that he be kept in a crate when unsupervised.

All PETronus Rescue dogs receive basic vaccinations (distemper/parvo, bordetella, & rabies), spay/ neuter, and microchip prior to adoption. We also treat any know medical issues, including heartworms.

Our dogs live in foster homes while they wait patiently for their forever families to find them. This is beneficial in that they learn house manners, crate training, housebreaking, etc while they wait and we are also able to get a very realistic picture of their energy level, temperament, etc so that we can place them in a home that is the best fit.

Our adoption fees are $200 for dogs over 1 year of age and $250 for dogs under 1 year of age. Puppies receive 3 rounds of puppy vaccinations.

If you are interested in adopting one of our amazing dogs, please fill out our adoption application here http://bit.ly/PRAdoption and we will be in touch!

animal.description:
Honey is a beautiful one-year old female Pit Bull Terrier mix who was surrendered by her owner on October 1, 2020.

Honey has a milk chocolate short smooth coat with a small patch of white on her chest, a long tail, and a sweet-looking face with a wrinkled brow, expressive brown eyes, a liver-colored nose, and magnificent over-sized ears that she holds erect.  

Her previous owner told us that Honey loves her people friends but that she is not good with other dogs or cats.  We aren't sure how she would get along with children since her owner did not indicate that she had any experience with youngsters.

Honey has some separation anxiety issues and is looking for a compassionate individual who will work with her on those issues through positive reinforcement training.

Honey has been kept indoors and is housebroken.

Honey weighs 42 lbs lbs and is accustomed to wearing a harness when she walks with her owner.

Honey will be spayed before being adopted by her new family.

UPDATE: Honey was spayed on October 19, 2020 and was also given rabies vaccine.

animal.description:
Gidget and Malibu Stacy were both strays who came into our rescue in January and February respectively.  Both had to be treated for heartworms and have finished their treatments.  While in foster care together they became so bonded that we would like to adopt them together.  We would consider adopting them separately, but they play very well together and keep each other busy.  Their confidence seems a lot higher when they are together.

Gidget is 3 or 4 years old and lives in a world of sunshine and lollipops.  She is happy and playful and loving.  She tries so hard to get dogs to play, even if they have zero interest in her.  Rejection does not affect her.  She is housebroken and crate trained and loves to go for walks.  She would not do well being left alone for long periods of time.  After heartworm treatment Gidget experienced incontinence, but it is under control with Proin.   She is fawn with cropped ears that don't stand.

Malibu Stacy was running stray in Atlanta for a few days before she was caught.  No one reclaimed her so she wound up with us.  She is probably 1.5 to 2 years old.  She enjoys the company of other dogs and loves to play.  She is submissive to other dogs. 

Malibu Stacy is timid around people she does not know and takes a while to trust them, but she is very loving and affectionate once she trusts you.  She is housebroken and crate trained.  She will go right into her crate when you tell her to.  She loves to play with toys and other dogs and people, but she does not like going for walks.  She is fawn with natural ears.

Both girls have been spayed, microchipped and fully vaccinated.  We have not had much opportunity to socialize either due to quarantining and social distancing. Whoever wants to adopt them needs to realize they may not be warm and affectionate when they meet you.  This is how they were with their foster parents at first, but with patience and time to settle in, they are an amazing, fun pair of dogs.

They would do best in a calm, quiet home.  We will not place them further than an hour from Atlanta, or into a home with young children. Both have high prey drives and would probably not do well in a home with a fence they can see through, like chain link.  They would want to chase everything they saw outside the fence.  A wood fence would work much better for them.

Their adoption fees are $250 each.

animal.description:
ROSSI
DOB:  06.24.2020*

Several people witnessed Rossi being throw from a freeway overpass. A good samaritan contacted Paw Printz and now he is safe. The vet has checked him over and given him the all clear. He is in great health and spirits. 

He loves people and plays with the other dogs in his foster home. Just like any puppy he is learning the basics, 'no bite', 'sit', 'bring me the toy'. He is a sweet boy and eager to learn and please. Puppies take a lot of time and patience, and Rossi is no different. He has puppy energy that could wear down a 3rd grade classroom so lots and lots of playtime is needed. 

His is almost done with all his puppy shots and will be neutered and microchipped prior to adoption.

If you think Rossi would be the perfect addition to your home, send an email to PawPrintzRescue@gmail.com and request an application. 

Adoption Fee: $200
Adoption Requirements: Application, Interview, Homecheck

THIS DOG IS LOCATED NEAR FRESNO, CA

*Age is always a guess with rescue dogs but here at Paw Printz we believe everyone should have a birth day so when the vet guesses at their age, we work out what would be a good birthday for each dog and make it so!

Cha Cha is the sweetest German Pinscher and is the most loveable pup you've ever met!! She loves to give kisses and going on walks.

Cha Cha came to us from an organization that removes dogs from horrible situations across the border in the Tijuana area. Cha Cha was living in a broken down shack with many, many other dogs. We believe she was kicked in the eye by someone and that is how she lost one of her eyes. Her eye has completely healed and it doesn't affect her one bit!!

Cha Cha has a best friend, his name is Kibbles and we would like to place both Kibbles and Cha Cha together. Cha Cha feels much more comfortable with other dogs around and Kibbles is definitely Cha Cha's boyfriend (please see Kibbles bio). These two love to play together and don't leave each others' side since they met. 

Being  a German Pinscher, Cha Cha does not bark and listens very well.

If you're interested in meeting Cha Cha and Kibbles, please contact us. Due to COVID, we have suspended dog adoption events, but we do do meet-and-greets.

animal.description:
Hi my name is Otoe and some very nice people at AHeinz57 Pet Rescue and Transport saved me from the spring floods in 2019. I have never been socialized with people, but was living on the property with 20+ of my furry brothers and sisters. I came to the rescue pregnant, but I won't have to do that again. 



I have been in a foster home since mid August and am learning about the finer things in life. I love my foster siblings and will need another confident dog in my forever home. If left completely alone I have some anxiety, but I do just fine if there's another dog with me. 



Because I am still unsure about trusting humans I am considered a flight risk and require a secure physical fence. I have mostly overcome my fear of humans being too close and getting leashed up and can be leashed regularly. I have a fenced in yard at my foster home and now they let me enjoy being in the yard without a leash sometimes. Inside the yard I'm pretty comfortable and walk really nicely on a leash. I've been on a few walks/jogs and they are pretty scary still, but as long as we are in a quiet area I do pretty well.



I've been on a few car rides and they are super scary! My foster parents say I'm doing better, but I really do not like car rides yet.



I'm not ready to snuggle with people, but my foster parents are allowed a few pets once in a while. When they wake up or come home I will greet them at the door and like to sniff their heads to say good morning and hello.



I am learning life and will continue to learn what my life should be. If you're interested in meeting me please put in an application at AHeinz57.com.

animal.description:
Hello, friends! My "official" name is Chucho, but I have lotsa fun nicknames. My foster mom calls me Tempo because I'm a reliably good boy. I'm looking for a home with loving humans, a big couch, and maybe even a fursibling to help me make the most of my second chance. 

You might remember my story: I was dumped at the shelter with a gigantic, ruptured tumor on my belly. TLP saved me and rushed me to the vet, and now I'm cancer-free and as happy as I could be! Despite my past, I'm confident, trusting and super affectionate. I love everyone I meet. My favorite thing is to wiggle under your arm for a nap.

I love other dogs, especially if they want to run and chase and wrestle with me! I don't especially like sharing my toys, but I'm trying to get better. I carry my ball around with me like a pacifier, and sometimes I fall asleep with it in my mouth.

I know all my basic commands and I'm building up my leash skills. I'm suuuuuuper food motivated! Go ahead and buy a second (or third!) bag of treats for me. My foster mom says I can be "opinionated," but I just say that I like to talk. Besides, who needs a doorbell when you got me?!

Are you looking for a 70lb lapdog and cuddle buddy? You found me!! Apply to meet me now.

animal.description:
Chief is an 18 month old red merle Australian Shepherd and weighs about 50lbs. This lively, handsome boy is full of energy and personality. Like many Aussies, he really bonds with his person and he is a little hesitant when meeting strangers. Once you have his love and approval he greets you with a smile, a toy or stick in his mouth, and a great deal of happy enthusiasm.

Chief is smart, athletic, and needs an active family that will challenge him by doing lots of training and fun games to stimulate that smart brain of his. We will require that his new family be experienced with herding dogs, and have no children under 12. He is sharp, learns quickly, and will need lots of constructive playtime, training, and exercise. Chief needs someone that will take him running, swimming, or play some dedicated fetch with him. A couple of long walks a day are not sufficient for his level of energy.  It's difficult for him to settle down if he doesn't get sufficient physical and mental exercise.

Chief's hips have been x-rayed and evaluated. They are not perfect but have only a slight malformation. He would be able to do any normal fun activities, running, hiking, swimming, playing fetch. Competitive agility would not be a good idea, but Chief certainly could do agility training for fun.

He gets along with other active dogs, better with females than males, is good with cats, but not good with chickens. He is crate trained and doing well with housebreaking.

Chief is a high energy herding dog and his needs are different than an average family dog. We will not allow him to be adopted by anyone who lives in an apartment or townhouse. He needs a big yard, with a secure fence as he is an escape artist. 

Please fill out an application if you think you can meet the activity needs of Chief. Please note: we will not respond to inquiries or applications that do not meet our requirements.

Please go to our website for the adoption details: www.almosthomehdr.org

He's very sweet but will need a minute to trust you since he has his guard up. He is great with other dogs, however can get protective over his toys. Mace has never been tested with cats. He is crate trained and house broken. 

Adoption requirements are as such:


	Large breed experience

animal.description:
Tyler is a Lab/Pitbull mix, born 8/20/2020. 

Since this puppy may be too small to be altered at the time of adoption, the adopters will be provided with a voucher to have the puppy altered and microchipped by the time he is 6 months of age. This must be done at Nebraska Humane Society. If you prefer to take the puppy to your own vet, we will pay a PORTION of the cost ($69) to your vet of choice.

Before applying to adopt this puppy, you need to be familiar with your local breed-specific legislation regarding Pit Bulls.

The suggested adoption donation for this puppy is $450. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description: A167706 Lizzo loves everything. She loves walks. She loves toys (a bit too much). She loves snuggling in bed with her human. She loves treats. She loves routine. She loves learning new tricks. She loves playing and puzzles. Lizzo loves people and very few dogs (she'd like to be an only child - although she can ignore other dogs on walks.) Lizzo really loves cats, but not in the good way - so we're going to step in here and ask that her new home not have any kitties or small animals. Lizzo has been with us so long that we could write a BOOK about this peanut. This 50 (petite lb), 4 year old pittie is so incredibly full of joy - it's rather astounding that she hasn't found a home yet. We're so happy and grateful that she is now in a foster home while she waits for her forever to come along. She is reportedly the BEST houseguest (respectful, quiet housebroken) and is just looking for a family that wants an energetic goofball to be the center of their world. animal.description:
Honey is a sweet, sweet full Saint Bernard that is between 1-2 years old.  She was saved by some wonderful folks who kept her from getting hit as she was walking in the street.  As you can see from the pictures she has demodex mange.  This is due to the lack of proper nutrition and being completely covered in fleas and ticks.  She arrived at St. Cloud’s Rescue on 9/27/2020 and she has made tremendous improvement.  With the help of Dr. Gray and lots of love, attention, good quality food and many medications she is doing much better. Honey is current on all vaccinations, housetrained and heartworm negative.  She will need to be spayed, but we are unable to do that until sometime in late November due to her health.  Honey weighs approximately 90 pounds and is one of the sweetest and most loving dogs you could ever find.  If you are interested in meeting Honey, we would love for you to meet her.  We will be accepting a deposit for her, but will not release her until the first part of December unless her health improves quicker. 

In concern for families with small children, we will not adopt a dog to a home with any child under the age of 5. This is due to the large size of Saint Bernards and the safety of your children. Our Saint Bernards are not aggressive or mean in any way, they can just knock down children easily. If you would like to visit our pups please contact St. Cloud's Rescue at www.stcloudsrescue.org or call 972-679-5319. The first step in adopting from St. Cloud's Rescue is to complete an application. The application may be found OUR WEBSITE at www.stcloudsrescue.org. Please click on the application process, complete and then email it. Once the application has been sent please call us to confirm that we have received it. St.Cloud's Rescue maintains the right to deny applications to anyone for any reason we see fit. St. Cloud Rescue is a non-profit 501-c-3 organization. St. Clouds Rescue requires new owners to purchase a one year supply of heartworm preventative from us, which is at cost. We require a home visit prior to all placements. All our dogs must be microchipped at a cost of $20.00. There is a $250.00 donation fee. All dogs adopted through St Clouds Rescue must be indoors. St. Bernards can not tolerate the Texas heat.
animal.name: Honey

animal.description:
We see that award-winning smile, Zeke - we know it's gonna land you your forever family soon!

Zeke was transferred to THS from another shelter. He knows he's adorable and a bundle of fun - on his most recent field trip his field trip partner said: "I took Zeke out for a little trip today and couldn't have had more fun! He is a very sweet dog and instantly loved everyone he saw! He is such a good boy!" Zeke is actually a rockstar of our Tails Around Toledo field trip program, and gets rave reviews on all of his field trips! Volunteers describe him as an active and energetic guy, but when he's had a chance to relax, he loves to snuggle up and be held! He thinks everyone is his best friend! He also rides great in the car, too!

He recently spent a few weeks in a foster home, and the foster described him as affectionate, active, and friendly. He met another dog while out in foster that matched his size and play style, and within 15 minutes both dogs were exhausted! Zeke walks very well on a leash but is still working on impulse control when he sees another dog from a distance. He is so excited to meet that dog, he will pull on the leash while barking. He will need a patient family that can work on his leash manners. Zeke was housebroken on a regular schedule and is also crate trained! Zeke needs an active family that can provide him with lots of enrichment and an outlet for all of his energy! Currently residing in foster care again, Zeke knows his new family is just waiting to whisk him away for adventures!!

Due to his play style, Zeke should meet any resident dogs prior to going home to ensure they will be compatible. He should also meet any children in the home to ensure a good fit for you family! 
 
Zeke was recently treated for heartworm disease and will need to go home with a year of heartworm prevention medication. THS requires all adopters of heartworm positive dogs to purchase a 1 year supply of heartworm preventative at the time of adoption. 

If you are interested in adopting Zeke please e-mail foster@toledohumane.org!

animal.description:
(This is a courtesy posting. This do is not a CHEW Dog Rescue dog and we have not met him. If you are interested in this dog, please contact his owner Callie: 815-878-1719)

Mr. B is a sweet, loving, and super smart guy. He was adopted 8 years ago (he’s 9) and has spent an amazing life with his family since then. Unfortunately he gets too nervous around his toddler human sister so he often has as to be separated from his people and it is taking a toll on him. 
Mr. B only requires a 30 minute walk most days. He would still chase a ball for hours if his humans would let him but he will be very sore after. He has no problem going on a short jog or a long hike and the vet says he is in perfect health!  
Mr. B walks well on a leash, but gets a little anxious with strangers or in busy situations. He is VERY obedient and receptive to commands. In fact, he passed his Canine Good Citizen’s test with flying colors and his previous trainer called him his “pitbull ambassador”.
Mr. B needs a home with no other pets or children. He does bark at delivery drivers and visitors at the door but does well home alone. He will thrive in an all adult home, with a fenced yard (not invisible fence) and where he doesn’t need to be left alone regularly for long hours.  He needs a home with a family that will love him and understand that he really is the BEST boy ever when his environment is calm and steady.

Thank you Artful Gardener!

'Named for the 7th Annual Cabin Fever Party at The Artful Gardener. Once again this year the awesome, fun-loving, kind-hearted customers of The Artful Gardener in Rochester came together to show their support for Joyful Rescues. In addition to their participation, seven local artists donated their time and over 20 local businesses donated goods and services to the Raffle for Rescue. Thanks to every one of them, the animals in this transport have found safe haven while they await their forever homes!'' Jean Westcott

Winnie was born around August 19, 2019, and may top out in the 40 pound range. Winnie does wonderfully with the other dogs and is great with humans.

UPDATE: Winnie was adopted into a home with a lovely older couple and was returned because her energy level was a bit to much for the household. They mentioned Winnie was fine with children but may knock smaller kids over. We will be looking for a home with a fenced yard and perhaps another playful dog or older kids to play with.

The Adoption Fee for this dog is $500.00

Adoptions fees vary based on adoptability. In general, our fees include spay/neuter, all age-appropriate vaccines, Home Again microchipping & registration, worming & flea control - a 'complete' pet. We accept CASH or Visa/Mastercard ONLY. Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility. YOU MUST BE AT LEAST 25 YEARS OF AGE TO ADOPT A DOG FROM JOYFUL RESCUES We keep our pet list as up-to-date as possible. As soon as a pet is adopted, it is removed from the list. If a pet is still showing, it is still available for adoption. Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet

Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.
