animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Prince Peach
DOB: 11/14/19
Weight: 45
Adoption Fee: $375

Peaches is an energetic, inquisitive pup who loves to explore the world. His favorite things include playing with other dogs, gnawing on bones, snacking on literally any food you offer him, and all the water in all its forms. Peaches is exactly what a puppy should be: happy-go-lucky and curious about everything around him. He'll be a great guard dog, as he catches all the little noises and movements in his neighborhood and lets you know (he's working on being less vocal). In fact, he's on the hyper-alert side but is working on it with some daily anxiety meds (taken orally). As he matures, he's most likely to grow out of any need for them, but for now, they help him level out. Peaches learns fast and listens very well for a pup. If he gets into something he shouldn't, he'll usually leave it when told to, and is a good sport about having items removed by hand.

He's fiercely loyal and tends to bond specifically to one human as his pack leader. He is particularly likely to bond with men, but his first owner was female and he was quite attached to her as well. Because he's so loyal and protective, it can be difficult for this pup to bond with others in a household, though he does well with adults in general. However, Peaches is not interested in being around children. His ideal home would be a single person or an adult couple with prior GSD experience and a big backyard to play in (bonus points if it's fenced, he's still learning to come when called). His favorite pastime is getting wet, and would love to play in the backyard with a hose and kiddie pool. He hasn't tried swimming yet but would probably adore it. Peaches would love to go on daily walks and even have another dog to play with, though he's also able to be independent. This pup is still learning not to chew on objects beyond his toys and bones, so will need kenneling or supervision until he fully matures. Luckily, he doesn't mind his kennel much and settles in within 5-10 minutes (though he's bummed to be missing out on any action happening while he's cooped up). Peaches is almost 100% on potty training and will let you know when he needs to go out by going to the door or staring at it. He's got some basic commands down, like sit, wait, shake and lie down, and will only improve with more practice!

In the meantime if you have questions or are interested in me, please fill out an adoption application at www.ruffstartrescue.org.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Glory

DOB: 9/25/2019

Weight:38 lbs

Adoption Fee: 400.00

Hi, I'm Glory! I'm such a snuggly, fun girl, once you give me time to trust you. You see, I've had a hard start to my young life, so I'm a bit shy and fearful. I would do really well in a quiet, calm home with a settled adult that has time to give me plenty of attention. I don't do great with extra people and a lot of commotion, so I would love to live without other pets or children.
I love to be out exploring, sniffing all the smells, and getting some bursts of energy out, but I'm also a great lounger. I have some hip dysplasia, and a knee that gives me a little trouble, so my foster mom gives me lots of brain games that I love to do, and I don't have to be out in the scary world.
They say I am a mix of Lab and Pit, and a couple people that know Greyhounds, thought I look like that too. What a great combo-- but it will take a good leader and experience in my forever home. I have a high prey drive, and I am extremely fast, and can jump real high.
As I've been coming out of my shell, my foster mom says I'm becoming a "real puppy", because if I'm not lying right next to you, I'm into something, or wanting to play hide and seek.
I'm a pretty good listener, but you have to be sure you're the boss, because sometimes I like to push the limits.
Because I'm still a bit fearful, I have a hard time telling my foster mom when I want to go out, but I try by climbing on top of her. We are working on bell training, but that's a little scary too.
I know sit, come, and kennel-up, and we've been working on stay and down.
I think if you're a bit of an introvert, and want a great companion pup, I would be the best girl for you!
If you want to meet me, reach out to Ruff Start, and let me show you my stuff.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Sydnee
DOB: 1/14/2017
Weight: 55 pounds
Adoption Fee: $375

Do you find yourself thinking social distancing has been the best thing to come out of the pandemic? Does your hermit shell include grassy knolls for a loving dog to play? I introduce to you the one who goes by many names, The High Snuggler, Lady Pillow Stealer, Miss Snacks-O-Lot, but best known as Sydnee. She's all about the snuggles and loves to give kisses to her humans. She will keep you warm right through the bitter cold of winter. Don't let Sydnee's bite history scare you away, she was just ensuring that the household was protected from strange humans. You never know about the two-legged these days. She will need her humans to work with her through these fear tendencies. Sydnee is rather friendly off the established homeland. You might say, "But you said she's the perfect antisocial dog!" I hear you, but she is well worth the minor inconvenience of small talk. Don't worry, she will want to be off and away again soon! Sydnee does get along with other dogs, but not cats. It may take a couple weeks to a month of crate rotating for her to accept a new barkmate, this is sometimes just how things go. She appears happy and excited at first, but this can quickly change due to her fear response in the first weeks of introduction. She takes a daily allergy pill with peanut butter and does shed a bit. Sydnee has a great love for food and she finds it highly motivating. In the mornings, she dances around excitedly for her meal, but then again, who doesn't?? Sydnee has a passion for squeaky toys and loves to boop them. She is a great companion, is working on muzzle training, is potty trained, and will be a loving addition to a new home. She may do better in a non-apartment setting as she does bark at new sounds and movement.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Shiloh
DOB: 12/1/2016
Weight: 95 lbs
Adoption Fee: $375

Hey there, I'm Shiloh! I'm an extremely handsome and lovable guy who is on the hunt for a forever home that can provide me with structure, stability and lots of love, that's not too much to ask for right?

I'm a young energetic guy that loves to romp around outside and explore! I also enjoy taking a walk every now and then, but do tend to pull on the leash until I get into a rhythm so you'll need to remind me of my leash manners at first- I'm working very hard on them! I love to play with toys and I'm such a good boy that I don't even shred them, so feel free to spoil me with lots! I am looking for a home with a fenced yard, as I like my privacy from the other neighborhood dogs! I do need slow and proper introductions to other canines so having a fence will assure no unknown pups try to come for an unplanned visit, that's not my style. However, I have been working with an awesome team of people to try and help me feel more confident and comfortable around other dogs, I've started basket muzzle training and have been doing really great! I have some anxiety that causes me to feel uneasy from time to time, I take Fluoxetine to tone my nervousness down and will need a family that is willing to continue this for my well-being. Due to my anxiety, I will need a home without young children who may not understand my boundaries (16 years and older only). I am fully potty trained and keep my kennel clean! I also have some allergies that are easily managed by taking Benadryl in the morning and evening!

I can't wait to start on a new journey with a family that will love me forever, quirks and all! I promise to make a great companion and just need a home committed to helping me succeed and be the best version of myself! Please take a chance and come meet me, you won't regret it!

animal.description:
Welcome to the Wonderful World of Rescue Dachshunds. Look around and read their bios. Find a few whose personality seems to fit well. Consider one of our Well Seasoned Seniors who are truly wonderful and have so much to offer. Need help finding the best fit? We'll help with that too. Please fill out an application and let's get you all matched up with a loving new "furever' companion and friend. You'll find the application on the "Available Dogs" page.

NOTE:

Adoptions to Central/South Texas residents only

Standard Adoption Fee Adult Dog: $250 ea. Puppy Adoption Fee: $300 ea. Reduced rates for Seniors dogs (10 and up). Reduced rates for pairs (when adopted together). All adoption fees are subject to sales tax per the State of Texas. DDRTX only adopts in Central/South Texas.

Email: ddrtxinfo@gmail.com Primary Website: www.DDRTX.org

Wren is around 8 years old and weighs 12 pounds. He is low-to-medium energy, and a nice mix of couch potato and playful explorer
. He enjoys his squeakies or playing fetch with you for a few minutes. He likes getting affection with a gentle touch. Short walks are ok. He loves going in and out of the pet door multiple times a day, and is house trained using it. Due to his interest in prey, living with cats would need to be tested first.

He is good with other dogs, just doesn't really play with them. He would also do fine as an only dog. He likes calm and quiet and a steady routine.

Wren is smart, sweet, and willing to please. He does have storm anxiety, and keeping him busy with a squeaky works well. Instead of a kennel/crate, he does well in a small room or baby gated area when left alone.

Wren loves to sleep on the big bed. He burrows under blankets and will tuck himself in!

If you can share the big bed, have a yard, don't mind brushing his teeth, and are looking for a lower/medium energy dog who likes best to take it easy and be a companion, he is your guy! He likes to feel safe and loved, and is so adorable, it's easy to do.

Medical info: Wren has an auto-immune disease that can cause ulcers in his mouth if it's not kept clean. It is important that his people help him maintain his oral hygiene by brushing his teeth daily, and/or using a gel as a backup. He doesn't mind the brushings, and enjoys his flavored doggie toothpaste.

Love dachshunds and not ready to adopt or circumstances won't permit having a dog? How about being a sponsor or making a donation. Every one of our dachshunds receives excellent medical care along with day to day food, love and housing. Being non-profit, we rely on generous individuals like yourselves to help save these fur babies. You can do this specifically for one dog with the sponsor button on their webpage or a general donation on our "How To Help" page. Easy and quick through Pay Pal or your debit/credit card. You generosity is sincerely appreciated by all and is tax deductable. Need other ideas? You'll find tons of them on the How to Help tab. All contributions are tax deductable.

Diamond Dachshund Rescue of Texas is a non-profit 501(c)(3) volunteer organization with focus on rescue and adoption of pure breed Dachshunds. All dogs are fully vetted and housed on private property. Meetings are scheduled upon adoption approval. Thank you for your continued support to the rescue and shelter communities!
Opt to Adopt!

animal.description: Karra is a lovely, young female pit bull terrier mix. She originally was a transfer from a shelter in North Carolina. Whether her timidity was due to being naturally shy or to not being exposed to lots of experiences while young, Karra was extremely shy when she came to us. Gradually, with kindness, patience and gentle handling by staff and volunteers, she has become more relaxed and social. She loves spending time with people and playing in the yard. In new situations, however, she can still become fearful, so she needs a gentle owner with the patience to teach her about the world and to help build her self-confidence. She still doesnt like fast, unexpected movements and quick grabbing makes her uncomfortable, so we recommend that she not live with young children. Young kids can act unpredictably and often lack the maturity to recognize a dogs signals that he is feeling fearful or uncomfortable.Karra has been up at the front desk for a few hours at a time and was quiet, well-behaved, housebroken and okay around our office cat. She did live with another dog for about 7 months and did well with him. However, here at the shelter, when another dog played too roughly with her, she reacted negatively out of fear. Karra has been spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, and negative for heartworm. Karra is a special girl who just needs an understanding person and a loving home to help her blossom and thrive.

The stray hold, at the Toccoa-Stephens County Humane Shelter, is 5 days. That allows owners a fair amount of time to come looking for their pets. On the sixth day, the animal becomes the property of the Toccoa-Stephens County Humane Shelter and is offered for adoption. An animal may be pre-adopted, however, if the owner comes forward, within the 5 day stray hold, the animal goes back to the owner. The adoption fee is refunded at that time.
TSCHS Adoption Procedure
Adoption Fees: Adoption fee includes spay or neuter, current (age appropriate) vaccinations, and a microchip.
Hours of Operation:
 Tues.-Saturday, 11-6

Pricing:
 Dogs $100 - Puppies $125
 Senior dogs $60
 Cats $60 - Kittens $75
 Senior Cats $30

Contact Information:
Toccoa-Stephens County Humane Shelter
1747 Scenic Dr.
Toccoa, GA 30577
Phone: 706 282 3275
Fax: 706 886 7358
Email: Info@TSCHS.org

Adoption process:
 Fill out an application
 Fill out a contract
 Pay the adoption fee
*Stray animals may be Pre-adopted before the stray hold is up. If an owner comes forward, the adoption fee is returned to the adopter. If the owner does not come forward, the animal is scheduled to be altered. When that is done, the pet can go home with the adopter.
Unfortunately, we are not able to hold animals without the adoption process being completed.
That includes the payment of the adoption fee. Adoptions are done on a first come, first served basis. Applications can be emailed and payment can be made via phone and at WWW.PayPal.me/TSCHS.
Otherwise we can not hold animals. After the adoption fee has been paid, arrangements will be made to have the pet altered. No pets leave without being altered.

We are hoping for an adopter or rescue to take her to a new and better life!

animal.description:
FOSTER NEEDED

We are in search of a special foster for our very special boy Bernard.   Bernard is a rottie mix.  He came to us as a stray, found wandering the streets of Harrisburg.  He was a very skinny fella and a bit unsure of himself.   After providing Bernard lots of love and vet care, he was ready for adoption.  

Unfortunately, we let him down.  He was in the home for two hours, being stressed out and not able to decompress, he was pushed and there was a bite incident.   The person sought medical treatment and said that she wanted to pursue dangerous dog charges.   We are appealing these charges, but Bernard sits in his kennel day after day just waiting with no clue of what is going on.  He is stressed and licking his leg to the point of sores.  It breaks all of our hearts to see him in that condition.  Bernard also suffers from allergies and is showing signs of hip dysplasia.   All vet care would be covered by CRCPA.

Bernard needs a local family that understands the breed and willing to abide by a few stipulations.   Bernard, or Big Bernie, or Nardi, as some of the volunteers call him, would love a quiet home without kitties or children and located in the country.  Bernard is good with most dogs, so another canine may be okay.  

Do you have room in your home and heart for our Big Bernie?  If so, please email the pet placement team at adopt@crcpa.org or call 717-232-1644 and leave a message.

animal.description:
Meet Molly.  Molly is a one year old terrier mix from our shelter partner in Louisiana.  Molly does not like to share her food, after being homeless.  She will require eating separately from other pups in her home.

Molly enjoys being affectionate with her people, but requires time to warm up.  No one likes people they don’t know in their face.. and neither does Molly.  She prefers getting to know you well before she will give her affection.   Just like everyone, she has her limits on how much affection she is willing to give.  
Molly is athletic and will need lots of exercise to keep her happy and stimulated.  She would prefer a home with a fenced in yard where she can have some independent time on her own.  Just like every girl needs alone time, Molly is no exception.  She will choose to spend time alone on her doggie bed chewing on one of her toys or nylah bones.  She would prefer to be left alone during this time.  

Molly is looking for an understanding family with bully breed experience that is willing to continue her training.   She has resource guarding issues with her food, she will require eating separately.   She is a very loving girl that has soo much to give the right family.  She would prefer a home without children, as they might not respect her boundaries.   


Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

FOR PUPPIES: PLEASE READ!!
Homes considering Puppies must be prepared for:
Flexible Schedules for Potty Training. Puppies can only hold urine for one hour per month of age. Crate Training for the next 10 months to keep them safe from chewing on everything in your home. Supervision with Children and Obedience training. 
Socialization; both with new people, children and other dogs outside of the home.
Homes that want a well behaved dog, must be prepared to put the time, effort and costs associated to train a puppy. Well behaved dogs are not born, they are trained!  Please do not apply for a puppy if you cannot or do not have the time for a puppy.

Almost Home Rescue of New England is a 501 c 3 non-profit rescue; rescuing dogs since 2005. All Adoption applications are completed on line at www.almosthomerescue.net 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered. 

Imported dogs are transported on a USDA approved transport with a Health Certificate. All imported dogs are quarantined 14 days prior to getting on transport.

He can see,  , though his vision has some limitations.  He is great with the other dogs , but definitely has a  prey  drive,  so no cats !   He’s doing better with the house training but still will have an accident . Someone who is home most of the time will be best  for him, to let him out as needed .  
Soon he will be ready to go to his forever family

animal.description:
PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE BIO ON THIS DOG BEFORE REQUESTING AN APPLICATION.  MANY OF OUR DOGS HAVE STRICT REQUIREMENTS FOR THEIR ADOPTION.

Midna is a 4 year old female Lab/pointer mix, about 45 pounds. Midna can be a bit of an introvert and prefers spending time at home with her family. Midna loves cuddling with her people when she gets to be on the couch or the bed and will let you know when she wants to play.
Midna is potty trained and will stand at the back door when she needs to go out. She is crate trained and does well in the crate when left alone during the work day. She is great with people, but will bark at strangers until she gets the chance to meet them.
Would do best in a home as an only dog or with a low energy or large senior dog who will give her space. NO SMALL DOGS as her prey drive is solid and no cats. Midna is reactive toward other dogs on walks and will need an adopter that has experience with reactive dogs or is willing to learn or train with her. 
She can be energetic and needs exercise and structure to keep her happiest. Midna walks well on the leash and keeps excellent pace as a running partner. If you are looking for an adventure buddy, Midna also loves going on quiet hikes and walks and rides really well in the car.
She knows some commands and is very eager to learn new things. Would do best in a home with a solid fence and kids over ten years old. She was an owner surrender.

Adoption contract and fee applies.  All adoptable dogs can be met at adoption events hosted every weekend. For a list of scheduled events go to: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/events .  Smidget Rescue is not a shelter, and dogs cannot be seen at the Rescue location. All dogs are fostered throughout the Puget Sound area and are brought to the events where they can be met by prospective adopters. Additional pictures of adoptable dogs can be seen at: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/photos_stream?tab=photos_albums.   All adoptable dogs are spayed or neutered at 6 months of age or older, and always before being placed in their new homes.  APPLICATIONS CAN BE OBTAINED BY EMAIL ONLY. Adoption process includes application, meet & greet, home visit and reference check. Email Jamie at smidgetrescue@hotmail.com or click on the CONTACT link on this page.  PLEASE DOUBLE CHECK YOUR EMAIL ADDRESS BEFORE SENDING.  We get a fair number of incorrect emails and Jamie is not able to contact potential adopters.  Notice:  We do not ship dogs out of state.  If you live within a five-hour radius of Seattle, WA, (such as Portland, Vancouver B.C., etc.), we can arrange for a home visit.  If your home seems like a great fit for the dog you would like to adopt, you must then drive to meet the dog at one of our weekend events or at the fosters home.

FAST FACTS:
*1 Year Old - 75 Pounds
*High Energy
*Dog Friendly
*No Children
*Fenced Yard Required
*Training Required

BIO:
Hi future family! My name is Noodle, and I am a happy-go-lucky sweetheart who is ready for a lifetime of fun! I'm an energetic guy who would do well with an active family that also understands I am recovering from major leg surgeries and will make sure I don't overdo it. You see, I was hit by a car and have been on crate rest the past three months while I recovered from my surgeries. I am doing very well and healing nicely; my foster mom will be happy to explain about my recovery in further detail. I love to be outside and would appreciate a fenced yard at my forever home. I'm dog friendly and can be a bit excited when meeting new canine pals so I would do well with slow introductions to make sure our energies mesh. I love everyone I meet and my favorite activity is being near my people, but because I have puppyish excitement and manners (I am working on my mouthiness and bounciness) I would do best in a home without children. Speaking of manners, I need a family who will be committed to working with me on training to catch up on the stuff I haven't been able to learn yet because of my injuries and recovery. I'm a smart boy who is eager to please, so I bet we will be class valedictorians in no time! I am soooo excited to start my new, healthy life and I hope you are ready for lots of love and fun! 

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS, NO EXCEPTIONS:
*ADOPTION FEE: $300
*Be at least 21 years of age
*Live in a 50-mile radius of Itasca, within the Illinois border
*Have the knowledge and agreement of all adults living in the household
*Have approval from owner of residence (written in lease)
*Have a valid ID with current address (please provide proof of address if ID address is not up-to-date)
*Be approved as a suitable adoptive home by Fetching Tails Foundation
*Be prepared to make a lifetime commitment

animal.description:
This litter of little soda pops is hoping to fizz into a wonderful family.

With a guesstimated birthday in June 2020, these pups will weigh under 15 lb. 

Mello is a sweet boy who loves his people - once he warms up to them.  He's suspicious of strangers and timid in new situations, so should be taken out in public to learn that new sights, scents, sounds, and strangers are curious rather than scary.  He's house-trained when kept on a regular schedule (currently every other hour).

Mello enjoys adventures and sniff walks as well as playing with polite doggy friends.  He's leash savvy and is comfy in a 36" crate, which allows him room to sprawl and stretch out.  He will growl and snap at other dogs if they approach his food, so should be fed separately.  Considering they were left outside to fend for themselves at birth, this is understandable.  His foster feeds him in his crate.

April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs and adoption events aren't being held at Tractor Supply in Lenoir.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience through another rescue or your local government-run animal control..

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

animal.description:
Pearl & Diamond are looking for a forever home for retirement. Estimated at 10+ years of age and Chihuahua mixes. They are bonded senior ladies looking for a home to spoil and love them. These sweet ladies are avid snugglers and insist upon a lap while you are watching tv and at night love cuddles under the blankets. Pearl and Diamond are both on a daily joint supplement as one of them does have luxating patellas, currently she isn't painful but may be in the future. The ladies are beyond sweet and enjoy their person's company. Both ladies enjoy car rides and currently go everywhere with their foster mom. They especially like when they get pup cups at Starbucks. Both ladies are very easy going. They enjoy the back yard and exploring. While not at home their foster mom pens them and they do well. Due to their teeth they are currently on a soft foods diet. Both have lost some weight since arriving to Heartland, which is much better for their joints. 

All dogs are spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations, heartworm tested negative (age 7 months and older) and microchipped. A senior dog's bonded pair adoption fee is $200. There is a $5 fee for credit/debit cards.

If you are interested in adopting one of our dogs, please fill out an online application here: www.heartlandsmallanimalrescue.org/canine-application.html

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Beauty and I am about 7 years old, a bigger gal (shhh... about 34 pounds). I am a casual and low-key girl, looking for a home to spend my days relaxing and chilling with my people. Wherever I live, I might need to be the only dog, or be with very laid back others, and I will do just fine! I am very submissive with my people, and I live to please! I do well in a large crate if I need to be home alone. I had surgery to repair one of my hind legs and because of arthritis in that leg, I am not the kind to go for "long walks on the 'beach'" (er, I guess since this is Texas, it would be the sidewalk!), and I don't care for stairs or hard floors that might be slippery, but I make up for my special requests in my cuteness and great companionship! I can't jump up on furniture or get off of the couch if you have helped me up to lay with you. I do well in the car if you ever wanna take me places, though! I am on daily eye drops and also take CBD oil for my arthritis. I also have a habit now of walking on three legs as my one leg with arthritis hurts me from time to time. My medications run about $80 to $100 per month. I would love to find a home where my person or people are home a lot or can take me places with them. My adoption fee is $275. NEEDS TO BE AN ONLY DOG AND NO YOUNG CHILDREN.If you are interested in any of our Boston Terriers or would like to be eligible to adopt a Boston Terrier through our rescue in the future, please fill out an application. We are always looking for good foster homes. These homes allow us to rescue more Boston Terriers in need because we have a place for them to go until they are adopted. If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption questionnaire and e-mail it to adoptioncenter@homewardtrails.org

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1. 

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time.

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE: http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Rocky is a big boy with a lot of love to give. He loves to play fetch, loves treats and is happy for a kind word and a pet. Rocky endured neglect and mistreatment; he spent much of his life on a chain and then was at a rural shelter for over a year, before arriving at Homeward Trails. 

Like his namesake, years of hard knocks haven't kept Rocky down. Soon after moving into a foster home, his playful side emerged and he earned himself the nickname of "Butt Wiggles" for the excited, happy display he puts on when he greets his favorite humans in the morning. He has returned to the adoption center and is working with our behavior team. 

Rocky is super sweet and affectionate but he is fearful of new people and loud noises. It takes him a little time to trust new people and he'll need help getting more comfortable with urban noises. He is making progress and he is looking for a loving home with a family open to helping him on this journey. 

He will be happiest in an adult only home and as the only pet. Rocky gets nervous when other dogs get into his space so he will do best in a home as an only dog. He would LOVE a nice tall fenced yard to play in. Rocky is very athletic and can jump over a 6 1/2 foot fence! 

He is ready for his second chance and looking for a loving home. Please reach out to make a VIP appointment during the week to meet him!

Rocky is part of the Go Fetch Program! His adoption fee is waived and he comes with free bonus items when adopted!

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

We also provide free online workshop with a professional dog trainer at Fur-Get Me Not within the first 30 days of adopting - just for HT adopters in the Arlington/Alexandria/Falls Church/DC area. Start your new dog out on the right foot with this valuable, expert guidance FREE!

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. animal.description:
Chico is 13 yrs old.  He loves adults.  His behaviour has changed and his foster parents see him getting along with other dogs at a distance. so him being the only dog in the family may be a good idea. He does have a loving side to him.  He loves being cuddled. The food is the point when he gets aggressive. The foster parents say he sleeps with other dogs on the bed.


If the animal is under the age of 3 years old or has health issues, a vet reference is required which means you must own a pet or have owned a pet in your name.

Adoption fee of $250 covers all vetting including spay/neuter surgery, vaccines, microchip heartworm test and treatment if needed and any other medical that may be required while in rescue. 

We only do adoptions on Saturday and not all animals are able to attend so if you would like to see a specific animal please let us know so that we can make arrangements for it to be present at the event. Event locations do vary so please check the homepage to find out where we will be this week. Please do not ask us to reduce adoption fees since all fees help us to cover medical expenses for all of our animals, some of which can be very expensive.  Saving lives is not cheap so thank you for your understanding and helping us save as many as possible.

Please email lowcountryanimalrescue@ymail.com for an application.

animal.description:
THis beautiful girl did not have the best start to her young life. She was found wandering the streets of Puerto Rico along with another dog who looked identical and appeared to be her sister. One of our wonderful volunteers took them in to foster until they could make their way to safety with us. Well when Luna arrived we noticed her belly looked a little too big and sent her for an xray where we found out she had 9 babies inside! She gave birth to 9 beautiful pups in a loving foster home and was an amazing mama.
It is now her turn for her forever home. Luna is quite young still, probably about two years old and since she most likely grew up in the streets she very much needs some guidance and leadership. She is an extremely loving, sweet girl but can also be pushy and try to push the limits, so she will need a strong leader who will be committed to her continued training and socialization. She has been in training with an amazing training team who has offered to do a couple free sessions for the new adopter! Doberman experience preferred.

animal.description:
We are ready to find Calico Jack's home!!!  He has been doing rehab and has gotten so strong!   You will always be able to see a difference in the leg, but clearly it does not hold him back from doing his thing.  He is now about 7 months old, weighs about 40 lbs, is likely a bird dog/catttle dog mix.  He loves other dogs and is fantastic with older people, teenagers and up.  He has not been around young children and is honestly afraid of them.  He does have all the puppy energy you might find in a 6-12 month old if his breed mix, so he would do best with active owners and he would love nothing more than to have a canine playmate.  He has lived in a multi dog household, has been crate trained and rides well in the car.  
Also, because this is important...Calico Jack's super power is his stink eye.  He will literally always look at you like you just made the most ridiculous statement....and who knows....maybe you did!!!!  But he loves you none the less, because his other super power is absolute sweetness.   

Calico is up to date on shots and preventatives and is microchipped.  His adoption fee is $250 plus any additional donation you feel appropriate.  Our adoption fee is set to a level to make adoptions happen.  They do not cover our costs. Thank you for your generosity and interest in our dogs!   

All dogs adopted locally through SGDR receive a free six-week session of obedience classes and a lifetime of behavior support through our Project REWARD program with trainer Charlotte Blake.

You must have an approved application before being able to visit a dog. Visit our website below for an adoption application https://www.snootygiggles.com/dog-application/

If you expect to leave the dog alone for long periods of time, please do not consider adopting a puppy.  Puppies need lots of attention and companionship.  Thanks.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

animal.description:
This handsome young fellow is Bolt, a 1 year old, 50 pound Husky mix with stunning blue eyes and fur as soft as a bunny's.  Bolt is deaf and navigates his world relying mostly on visual cues and his superior sense of smell. He is a confident and curious boy ready for any adventure you may undertake. He is a quick and eager learner and is highly motivated to understand his people and what they want to communicate to him. He has learned to pay close attention to hands and body language and has mastered many hand signals for polite doggy behavior.  Some of the hand signs he knows are: sit, down, wait, shake paw, touch,  go out, go in, look at me, put the ball in my hand, come here, and good boy!  Bolt loves to learn new tricks and would catch on quickly to any organized dog activity, such as agility or nose work, that you may want to explore.

Bolt has been in his foster home for the last 2 months and has been a model houseguest. 

He is crate trained and sometimes chooses to take naps in or just hang out in his kitchen crate when everyone is in the room.  He sleeps comfortably through the night in his bedroom crate.

He is very reliably house trained and will wait by the door to be let outside.

He is affectionate but not needy or clingy. He loves to have his face and ears rubbed and can be instantly calmed, almost hypnotized, by ear rubs and shoulder and chest rubs.

He likes other similarly-sized dogs and really enjoys living with his resident foster brother. We think he'll do best in a home with another dog since he thrives when he has a companion dog near him.  

He has a medium energy level and enjoys fast trail runs, mountainous hikes, and long, sniffing walks and is learning to appreciate a good game of fetch. When he's not enjoying his outdoor fun he is happy to nap or watch out the window at the birds in the trees and the people walking in the neighborhood. Anytime after 6:00 pm he can be found curled up in a little white ball, asleep, until it's time for bed.

He has an intuitive sense of what is an appropriate object to play with or chew (dog toys) and what not to touch (shoes, furniture).

He likes meeting new people and is especially attracted to children, who seem to find him very interesting as well. He enjoys meeting them on walks and will sit politely to receive treats from them.

Because he may find them a little too compelling, Bolt would be best suited in a home without small animals, including dogs and cats.

Bringing a deaf dog into your life may seem like a challenge, but it's mostly just a matter of getting used to relying on other ways to communicate without sound.  We use verbal language with our dogs almost exclusively and it can get a little wordy and unclear sometimes. Communicating with a deaf dog keeps your signals more concise and clear and more consistent. Bolt is so eager to learn and understand what you want that his enthusiasm is contagious. Learning new things is his favorite game and will soon become yours, too.  Additional benefits of having a deaf dog include no distractions or drama from barking dogs, postal carriers and delivery trucks, thunder, fireworks, fire and ambulance sirens, doorbells, vacuums, howling cats and so much more.

Bolt is such a nifty fellow and is so ready to be someone's best friend and adventure partner.  If you want to see more of Bolt's daily life he can be found on Instagram @SoCok9fostermom 

Please read up on the Husky breeds and on deaf dogs' needs (https://deafdogsrock.com/ is a good place to start) as Bolt will be placed only in a home who has breed experience or is willing to do the research and understand the needs of a typical Husky and deaf dogs in general and is willing to train, socialize, and keep him both mentally and physically active.

If you are interested in adopting this handsome boy, please submit an adoption application online. https://www.rocketdogrescue.org/adopt/adoption-application/. A volunteer will contact you. (OA)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Rocket Dog Rescue is an all-volunteer nonprofit group dedicated to saving homeless and abandoned animals from euthanasia in overcrowded Bay Area shelters. We literally give them a second chance at life. And everybody deserves a second chance.

Adopting a rescued animal is a lifetime commitment! Adopters must complete an agreement (http://www.rocketdogrescue.org/adopt/adoption-application/) and a personal interview prior to adopting a Rocket Dog. There is a non-refundable $280.00 adoption fee which helps us defer the cost of spay/neutering, vaccinations and microchipping.
http://www.rocketdogrescue.org
https://www.facebook.com/Rocket.Dog.Rescue
http://www.petfinder.com/shelters/CA534.html

Ryder is a young pup, around 10 months old looking for his forever home. He's currently living in a foster home with cats & other dogs.  Ryder is cat friendly.  He is dog friendly as well.  Ryder is learning crate manners and is getting better every day. His foster mom is working on leash manners as well. Ryder has a very sweet and submissive personality.  Don't let this fool you though, he can still be very stubborn.  With continued training, he is going to be a great dog! Ryder has been great with people & kids of all ages. 

Please note:  Ryder has shown signs of resource guarding while in his kennel with his toys and food around animals only.  Ryder has growled at the dogs when they walk by and he has his goods.  Foster mom is able to take away food, toys and things he shouldn't have just fine.  With professional training (required for all adoptions) he will be a great boy.

PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO BEFORE RESPONDING.  SERIOUS INQUIRIES ONLY.  PHONE CALLS WILL NOT BE RETURNED.  EMAIL ONLY.

MEET SCRAPPY! - AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION

Arrghh Matey! It's me, Scrappy! I've recently become a one eyed pirate and am looking for a family to give me a loving home for my golden years! 

Scrappy joined our rescue end of August 2020 and is at least 10 years old & 20 lbs. He has multiple health issues but is a tough cookie! He was surrendered to a rural Texas shelter and flown to Idaho via Dog is my Copilot. He arrived with poor eyes that were clearly infected and one was bulging and very painful, he also has a heart murmur and skin issues with thin fur. We believe him to be an affenpinscher mix. 

Scrappy was neutered and had an single enucleation (eye removal) surgery Sep 21, 2020, his heart did well under anesthesia! 

Scrappy is looking for a calm home to retire in, full of love and ideally with a yard to explore! Scrappy does well with other dogs, has not been tested with cats. He would do best in a home without children as he is adjusting to life with one eye and could be startled by children's loud noises and quick movements. 

Characteristics: one eyed, pirate, Sweetheart, heartthrob, gentle disposition, happy, 

Background:  Pulled from Dallas Animal Services and joined our rescue August 22, 2020 via Dog is My Co-Pilot. Scrappy's surgery was sponsored by Stellas Shelter Fund. 

EMAIL US for an adoption application for Scrappy

animal.description:
Meet our handsome boy, Luke! Some might say his most distinguishing feature is the fact that he is three-legged, but we think it's his gorgeous smile. Being three-legged doesn't slow him down one bit; he loves exploring Long Island's beaches and racing around the Bideawee dog park! Lukey can be scared of strangers so it takes him a little time to warm up, but once he does, he's your friend for life! We think that Luke would flourish in a quiet home where it's just you and him. He bonds strongly to his person and wants to be your one and only. Once he feels safe with you, he quickly becomes a lap dog (just ask his favorite staff members and volunteers). He would do best with an experienced dog owner who is open to coming to visit him several times at the shelter so he can get to know you. Luke loves consistency and a routine, and we think he'll really thrive in the right home. Luke is a special boy who we have a real soft spot for because we know the companion he is capable of being if given the chance. Thanks to a generous donation, Luke's adoption fee has been covered; all he needs now is a home to call his own! If you're interested in this cutie, you must click "Apply for Adoption" to submit an online application.

animal.description:
PLEASE apply for the dog of your dream...
With out an application you cannot be considered.
Complete one at www.wowdogrescue.org and it will stay on file
with us for 90 days, for ANY dog of interest.
Time does not allow us to email everyone, and we prefer you read the information below,
as most everything we know is here

********PLEASE CHECK www.wowdogrescue.org DAILY for any updates

Fred is approx. 8 - 9lb. and a handsome chihuahua, that was a feral
boy with another chihuahua, both found untouchable.
Fred is around 1 yrs old and has been worked with
by a trainer.

The trainer had this to say about Fred:
"Fred is fun loving and enjoys learning new things.
He thrives on long walks and with confidence building exercises".

Fred will potty in the home, but he does use a doggy door too.
He is not a cuddle on the couch/bed type of dog.
In the morning he will jump up and play a little bit, but no cuddling.
He may never advance to a dog who cuddles.

The current foster has had him for 3-4 months and
she can pet him "sometimes"...not too often.
He is really only interested in the dogs in the home as they
seem to calm him and make him happy.
Having another dog or dogs would be best for him.
This is what we will be looking for, when we choose his forever home.
PATIENCE with him is the key. 
Fred is ready for his new home now. He is
Neutered, chipped, immunization shot, Bordetella and Rabies shot.
Fred's adoption fee is set at $200.00

If you are interested in Fred, PLEASE complete an application.
Most everything we know about our dogs is in the bio..so please read it
so you know what the dog is like and if it will fit your lifestyle.

Once an application is received, it will go in that dog's file for review.
IF you are chosen for Fred, you will get a call for him and will  have
3 hours to respond (if we get your answering machine)
before we go to the next person of interest.
*The ONLY way to be considered is with an application which is on our website:
www.wowdogrescue.org  

******CHECK DAILY FOR UPDATES on OUR WEBSITE!
Click on the picture and scroll all the way to the bottom of the following page.
THANKS for wanting to Rescue!!

**IF you are tired of loosing out on the dog of your dreams, know that
W.O.W Dog Rescue appreciates the fosters, and because they are
great enough to help out...they also have 1st chance at adopting the dog
they are fostering.
ALSO, we supply everything while they are in your care!!

animal.description:
I want you to meet a VERY SPECIAL rescue. This is Annabelle. She is a ten month old, beautiful chocolate brindle, Terrier/Basenji X. First, you need to know how much she has overcome and has learned in a very short period of time. Annabelle came from an abandoned house with very little people contact and no other animal contact. Her paw was injured, had a deep laceration and she needed immediate surgery to fix her wound.  She was leary at first but welcomed the kind touch of a person. Despite this beginnings and uncertainty, she has blossomed! Annabelle is a typical puppy with lots of energy. She thrives on being allowed to run in a supervised, controlled environment and lots of positive feedback. She does need daily active playtime/exercise.  She responds very well to her name, treats and lots of love. Annabelle needs a large fenced in area and an active individua/ family. She is doing well on leash training as it is work in progress. She has shown no signs of aggression with our persona dogs and would do great with another young, energetic playful companion or in "only dog home".. Due to her size and activity level, no children under 12 years old.

Annabelle is spayed, up to date on rabies, distemper/parvo and bordetella vaccines, heartworm tested, (negative), dewormed, current on heartworm and flea/tick prevention, and microchipped. Her adoption fee is $300. 


 you would like to be considered in adopting our pet(s), you must FIRST complete an adoption application. To submit an adoption application click on "More About Us", located on the right (bottom) of the page. This will route you to our home page where you select the "Adoption Application" tab located on right side of the page. The application will open in a "WORD" document format where you select "enable editing" on the top of the application, then complete the form and email to rhonda4care@gmail.com. Please make sure you answer all questions on the application. If you don't have WORD format, email rhondad4care@gmail.com and use "adoption application" in the subject line.

We are not a shelter. All of our animals live in private homes in foster care. Upon approval of your application, you will be contacted by the pet's foster parent to ask questions and to set up a time to meet the pet of interest.

animal.description:
JAMES - 6 years old, 55 pounds. Shy/reserved. Afraid of men, can be skittish with quick movement/loud noises. No other pets or young children.

James is a scared boy, and rightly so. He was abandoned by his owner, and then was in a situation where negative reinforcement training was employed. He then landed at VBACAC as a confused and shut down dog. But as he gets used to the faces he sees regularly, he has started to come out of his shell.

Underneath that nervous outer layer is a goofy, sweet boy! He is a decent size, sports a deep copper color, a cute underbite, and expressive brown eyes. When out in the yard with a familiar face, he shows that he is responsive to treats/food, and likes playing with toys! Throw a toy over his head, and he'll jump in the air before he realizes he can't reach it. Then he'll turn around and run after it. He loves to chase, but doesn't always bring the toy back, so it is good to have a couple toys handy to keep him engaged.

James is slow to warm-up to new people. Potential adopters should be prepared to have a prolonged meet and greet with James before he will approach them. He may require more than one meet and greet. It will also take time for James to get used to a whole new home and family. He will need his own safe space in your house that he can retreat to when scared. As he gets used to a new environment, he will come to you when he is comfortable. He would do better in a home that doesn't have frequent visitors as this is likely to cause him some stress. He is afraid of men. Small kids will also likely scare him as they can be loud and move too fast for his liking.

If you're willing to give this sweet, scared boy a chance, call us at 385-4444 or go to our Facebook page and make an appointment to meet him! We are open daily except for Tuesday's. Thanks for choosing adoption

animal.description: Meet Dior! Dior is a pit lab mix, shes almost 2 years old. She is a rescue bait dog that was put in a shelter due to be euthanized. She is so ready to find a forever home! She is so energetic and loves being outside! She has been through a lot, she needs someone who is patient and gentle, give her confidence and consistency. She loves cuddling on the couch. She absolutely adores car rides and hikes. she plays well with multiple toys and loves the color orange. She loves getting little training treats and is grasping commands such as (sit, wait/hold, lay down, and gentle). Dior would thrive in a home with NO other pets! Her current foster has smaller animals such as gerbils and reptiles, she has no issue with them in her space. But cats get her too overstimulated. If introduced properly and given the time she could live with one other dog her size, but that dog would also have to be submissive. Dior is potty trained as well as crate trained. She is a resource guard, but responds well to WEER DONE (with her attitude)! She is so sweet, she loves belly rubs. She loves kids. Loves walking in creeks, but does not like the hose. This princess can not wait find her family! Can you be my hero? Apply today to adopt this sweet girl at charliescrusaders.org PLEASE Note must own your home, have a fenced yard and have pit experience.

animal.description:
Bruiser is a beautiful, approximately 3 year old mix who absolutely loves to play!  He is in a foster home and doing very well with the two dogs he resides with.  

He is fine tuning his manners, and can now sit for a very short period waiting for permission to eat.  

He has a little toy possessiveness, but he is doing so much better with this already in his foster home. They are patiently teaching him that although he has never had things like toys, it is ok to share them with other dogs and that everyone should take turns. He is doing very well, and a new adopter would need to continue this patient instruction with Bruiser, teaching him how to be a dog!

Bruiser is a very happy, 52 pound bundle of love. He enjoys lots of love and attention, and his favorite thing is snuggling on the couch with his human foster Dad! He definitely thinks he is a lap dog when it is time to cuddle.

He would do best with a fenced in yard or with someone that has plenty of time for long walks to help him get out his energy. He does have lots of energy!!

Interested in adopting? Go on our website, triadspca.org and submit an application or call us at 336-375-3222.

Visit our FAQ webpage for commonly asked questions about our adoption/foster process.

Did I hear someone say ball?? Hi I'm Cliff but I am more use to being called Monty. I have a passion for balls, my favorite are the green tennis balls. I would love to have someone who would throw a ball or two for me in the yard. If you have a fenced yard better yet. I love playing but once I'm done I want that couch to snooze on.

I'm looking for a home where I am the only pet. Young children wouldn't be br best as I get very excited and could knock them over. I love car rides and walks. I am strong though so make sure you can hold me if we come across other animals. I am up to date on vaccines, crate and house trained, microchipped and neutered.

Take a chance on me and let me charm you! Looking for a forever or foster home. I cannot wait to meet you!

If you would like to meet me or adopt me please fill out an online application. Questions to my foster at cbrookszy@yahoo.com

Click here to watch a video of Cliff - Ql Litter.Last Day Dog Rescue now microchips all animals before adoption. Microchips are implanted between the animals shoulder blades and are a permanent form of identification. The microchips are registered to Last Day Dog Rescue with the adopter's info added once adopted. If the animal is ever lost and slips his/her collar/tags the microchip allows the finder to know who to contact if scanned for a microchip. Animals MUST still have a collar with tags on at all times. Per our contract, we take all our animals back if for any reason you can't keep your adopted animal.

Please understand the statements about this animal are based upon the foster home's evaluation of the animal. The animal might behave differently (negatively or positively) in your home. While the animal might be good with the current foster's dogs, cats, children, etc., it may not be with your animal(s) or children. The animal may be housebroken or litter trained in the home of the foster but may relapse in your home. The animal is represented to the public as it performs in the foster home and any statements made regarding the animal are conditional to that foster home setting. Please understand that statements made regarding this animal are simply overviews and are not guaranteed.

The Petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our animals. Visual breed identification in animals is unreliable so for most of the animals we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each animal as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our animals based on personality, not by breed label.

Thank you for looking through our list of animals needing forever homes and choosing rescue first. We appreciate you stopping by.

animal.description:
Name: Hank
Suspected Breed: German Shepherd Mix 
Approximate Age: 1-year-old
Approximate Weight: 60lbs
Personality: loyal and playful 
Observations with Dogs: Reactive on leash, but has done well with other dogs with proper intro
Observations with Cats: not good with cats
Observations with Kids: Best in a home without children
Currently Living at: Foster Home in the DMV area

Check out my adoption video here: https://youtu.be/LX61iUsMziE

Hank is a handsome German Shepherd mix from South Carolina who is approximately 1 year old. At 60 lbs, he is smaller than most male German Shepherd dogs and we think that he's a mix. Hank finished 2 months of heartworm treatment and is ready to get back to business (aka playing). This fun-loving guy still has some puppy energy and absolutely adores playing fetch - any toy that you toss he will happily chase and bring back to you so you can throw it again and again. And again. And maybe one more time. He also loves chewing on bones and if you smear a little peanut butter on one... *chef's kiss*

Hank is a sweet boy and has a lot of love to give. He enjoys snuggling but sometimes he will use his charm and good looks to try to turn a cuddle session into playtime, which his foster finds hard to resist. During work hours he will sometimes press his forehead against your leg to ask for pets, and if you give in (editor's note: how could you not?) he will often flop over to encourage additional belly rubs. Mostly he is content to nap nearby as you work, although as soon as you get up from the desk he's checking to see if it's playtime again. Or snacktime. Either is cool with Hank.

Hank is a very smart boy who is eager to please his human. He responds very well to commands, although when he's excited it's a little harder for him to maintain his focus. Hank also learns new commands and tricks super quickly: he picked up ""paw"" in only one morning! His foster thinks that the sky's the limit with what you could teach this smarty-pants to do. After some time to adjust to a new home, Hank also does very well in his crate. He gets in willingly (excitedly, even, if treats are offered!) and will hang out quietly while you're at home or when you head out for a bit. He will sometimes choose to hang out in his crate even when the door is open, and you may even see him sitting in there quietly with his paws crossed ever so daintily - what a gentleman!

Hank's biggest challenge is his leash reactivity on walks. Currently, his foster uses tasty chicken pieces to distract him when he sees other dogs. It works pretty well, but Hank will need to work with a trainer to make sure his leash reactivity is managed over the long run. Hank has also displayed some protectiveness of his foster when people come over (which admittedly is less of a concern during COVID-19). DC Paws has a trainer who will be working with Hank and his foster on both of these issues, and we have confidence that his perfect person is out there and that Hank, with love, patience, and dedicated training, will be a truly wonderful dog.

He is very protective of ""his"" human and may lunge/bark at visitors and other people who enter the home. He is also sensitive to noise and frequently barks if he sees people in the hallway of a building or hears them walking by. For this reason, Hank would do best in a quiet home that is strongly committed to working with a professional trainer and who understands that he needs to be introduced to new people slowly. Hank will need help to learn that it's ok to have more than one human friend and he has been working with our trainer on this. He also will need lots of playtime and exercise - we have found that leashed walks are not enough for him and that he needs to get his heart rate up each day. With the right support, we believe that Hank will make a great family member and friend for a lucky adopter. 

Since Hank was previously treated for heartworm, he will need to be retested in 8-10 months to confirm his treatment was successful in eradicating all heartworms (treatment rarely fails). And like most shelter dogs, Hank may need a refresher on housetraining and crate training. We ask all of DC PAWS' fosters to work on both house and crate training with their foster dog.

The adoption fee for this dog is $350. If you are interested in adopting Hank, please submit an adoption application at http://dcpawsrescue.org/adoption-info/.ABOUT US & IMPORTANT DISCLOSURES:

Please note that you must use our official adoption application in order to be considered for adoption. Applying through other sites (i.e., Petfinder) will not work. The following are our applications:

Dog application: https://service.sheltermanager.com/asmservice?account=bg0781&method=online_form_html&formid=1
Cat application: https://service.sheltermanager.com/asmservice?account=bg0781&method=online_form_html&formid=6

DC PAWS Rescue does our best to provide accurate and complete information about our adoptable animals. Please note that we cannot make any guarantees about age or breed; we rely upon our rescue partners and their veterinarians to make those assessments. We also cannot make any guarantees about housebreaking and animal temperament, as animals can behave differently through transition and in different environments.

Our shelter partners provide a basic vet screening for each animal we rescue, which includes necessary vaccinations, deworming, microchipping, and spay/neuter (unless the animal is too young or otherwise deemed by the vet to not be a good candidate for surgery). Please note that this is not a comprehensive medical exam and as such, may not identify any and all medical issues, though our goal is to flag any obvious health issues through the basic vet screening. We share all medical records with adopters and are completely transparent about any known issues prior to adoption finalization. 

ABOUT DC PAWS RESCUE

Our rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based dog and cat rescue in the DC area. We rescue locally from Prince Georges County, MD, and from rural shelters in the south (presently Pickens County, Anderson County, and Greenville County in SC, and Raleigh County, WV).

We partner with a local rescuer in Pickens County, SC, who saves adoptable cats and dogs from the three area shelters. For the animals in this rural area, rescue is a critical lifeline, and often the only lifeline. Our rescue partner not only works with DC PAWS to save as many dogs and cats as possible, but she has also established a successful spay/neuter program in the community to decrease the number of homeless and unwanted animals over the long term.

FOSTER AN ANIMAL IN NEED

Fosters make it possible for DC PAWS to save and care for homeless, neglected and abandoned animals! To learn about fostering dogs or cats for DC PAWS Rescue, please visit: http://dcpawsrescue.org/volunteer/fostering/foster-application

SPONSOR AN ANIMAL IN NEED

For any of our animals! Sponsors help us provide critical medical care, food, boarding, and other support for animals facing euthanasia. Individuals who sponsor a dog or cat receive special recognition on the animal's profile. Sponsorships can also be made in honor or memory of a loved one, and you may designate to whom DC PAWS Rescue should provide notice of your gift. Sponsorship levels of $250 and $150 include ""naming rights"" for a future dog or cat (respectively) that we rescue.

To learn more about sponsorship, please visit: http://dcpawsrescue.org/donate/

animal.description:
6 year old female Chihuahua mix, about 7 pounds. Ky was formally Pearl who was adopted out as a puppy. Hi! My name is Ky! I have some special needs but let me introduce myself first! I love my people. I want all of the attention that you can give me! I also love giving kisses and hugs. My favorite places to be are on the back of the couch, curled up under a blanket, or laying in the sun! The occasional toy is good fun too! Im currently being fostered with another small dog and a cat, I mostly ignore the cat, but I have tried to play with the dog on rare occasions! I can be a bit growly when the dog gets too close to my stuff, but it is mine after all! Im also good with kids, but only if they know how to treat me respectfully and move carefully so I dont get scared. Older children would be preferred. Im really just a happy and sweet little girl looking for a home. Unfortunately, I have narrowing discs in my spine that make me very sensitive to certain things like being picked up or squatting. I can also be a bit timid, especially around new people, and I may scream out and submissive pee in anticipation of pain. Currently, I am on pain meds that help me feel normal and let me do zoomies pain free! These will need to be given intermittently for a while, and my adopters will need to provide me with continued vet care for my condition. It takes a while to gain my trust, and certain actions like putting on my leash or my harness can make me feel tense and scared. Once you do gain my trust I will feel much more at ease. Im very adjusted to my foster home now but it can take some time before I settle in. The more I trust you, the better I will get, and the sooner I will blossom into the wonderful pup that I truly am! All that I ask is that my adopter is willing to give me lots of time, care, and love, because I really am a special little girl and my foster mom says that I deserve the best of the best!

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS FOR KY:

NEEDS DAILY MEDS, POTENTIAL EXTRA VET CARE.
NEEDS SOMEONE WITH PATIENCE WHO GIVE HER THE TIME AND SPACE SHE NEEDS TO SETTLE IN AND TRUST.
OLDER CHILDREN OR ADULTS.
NEEDS DOGS SMALLER THAN HER SO SHE WON'T GET HURT, OR NO DOGS AT ALL.

If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility..

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
*ADOPTER OR FOSTER NEEDED ASAP*
 
This adorable, smiley boy is 2 year-old Happy.  Happy has been in and out of the shelter several times in his young life due to his humans’ lack of experience and training...this is likely to be Happy’s last chance.  If we can’t find him a foster or adopter, there’s a very good chance that he won’t make it out of the shelter alive.  PLEASE READ ENTIRE CAPTION FOR ADDITIONAL INFORMATION.
 
Happy has been wonderful with everyone at the shelter, but two of his previous families have stated that he can get protective of people in the family.  The families didn’t know how to stop that kind of behavior, so they allowed it to continue unaddressed until they decided to dump Happy back at the shelter and now Happy’s life is in the balance. 
 
Happy has never hurt anyone or even come close; he gets defensive and fearful so he just needs a patient, loving family willing to work on his confidence and socialization skills.  He doesn’t deserve to languish away at a shelter until he’s euthanized because his humans have failed him.
 
At this time, Happy needs to be the only animal.  He lived with a baby in his last home and did great with her, but she was one of the people that he was very protective over, so until he receives more structure and training, older children would be preferable.
 
Happy is currently at Front Street Animal Shelter in Sacramento.  Approved fosters/adopters may have to provide transportation, but the shelter is willing to help in any way that they can to ensure Happy gets another chance at a long, HAPPY life.  Please help us rescue him before it’s too late. 

Please help us get sweet Happy into a safe, loving forever home!  If you're unable to help by adopting, sharing this post or donating is always appreciated.  Don't forget, Passion for Pitties is a 501(c)(3), so all donations are tax-deductible!…every little bit helps!
 
If you would like to adopt loving Happy, please fill out an application at www.passionforpitties.com under the “Adorable Adoptables” heading.

animal.description:
Adoption info can be found in the last paragraph of this pet's profile or by visiting this direct link:   https://www.dfwpuppatrol.com/info/adoption

Rocco is a super sweet Pitty boy who found himself in a rural high kill shelter. Some volunteers networked him to help him get seen and a volunteer for Pup Patrol offered to foster so we got him out! Rocco is around 2 years old and weighs a little over 50 lbs. He has undergone heart worm treatment and is  now healthy and ready to find his forever home! He is a pretty laid back dude for the most part, but he does suffer with containment phobia and hates to be crated. Currently his foster mom leaves him loose in the house while she’s at work and although he likes to check out what’s in the trash can, other than that he does fine. Rocco has been introduced to other dogs and really doesn’t pay them much mind. He will be fine in a home as an only dog or with other doggy companions. No cats though...he is not a fan. Rocco is good with children although he doesn’t respect their space and might knock little ones over. He has been working on his manners and will even sit and wait before going outside. He loves his walks and does pretty well on leash. He is a super sweet guy who loves attention and will whine to get it.

If you are interested in adding this pup to your family, please click here (or copy and paste https://www.dfwpuppatrol.com/info/adoption into your browser) to view our adoption info and where you will find the link to fill out our online Pre-Adoption Application.  Any questions can be directed to us at info@dfwpuppatrol.com.  All of our adoptable pups have a minimum requested adoption fee of $250 + tax  (pups 6 months and older) and $350  + tax (pups under 6 months old), regardless of our expenses, and it includes vaccinations, spay/neuter, heartworm test for pups 8 months and older, heartworm treatment if tested positive, deworming and/or fecal test, parasite treatment if tested positive, microchipping, any immediate known health issues, and pups 3 months and older are kept current on monthly heartworm prevention.

 INTERNAL
PSTD 09/30/20 TSELF
CNTC DFWPPR

animal.description:
Dory came to us after the hurricane from a Louisiana shelter. She has made so much progress and is ready for a place to call home. Dory is an 8 year old yorkie with special needs, so she will need an experienced adopter. She has type1 diabetes which is well controlled with a strict diet and Insulin injections twice a day. She is also heartworm positive but has already begun the process of slow kill treatment. She came to us weighing only 4lbs and is now up to 6lbs of pure sweetness! She also has cataracts and mild vision loss. Dory is potty pad trained but she will also do her business outside. She does well in a kennel, but truly prefers to be right next to her person at all times. A nice warm lap is her favorite place to be. 

ALL adoptions require a completed application, vet check, home check and final contract.  The application to adopt can be found at www.camorescue.com.

Adoption fees are variable. Up to date vaccines, microchip, spay/neuter are included in the fee.

Once your application has been approved, we will put you in touch with the foster to set up a  meet and greet. We are a foster based RESCUE, not a shelter. All of our dogs are in individual foster homes. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We select the best applicant for each dog, based on the dog's needs. 
For the safety of our small breed dogs and based on our past experiences, we will not place our dogs in homes with large breed dogs.    

CAMO rescue is a 501c3 whose primary focus is rescuing small dogs from the euthanasia list from high kill TX shelters.   
EIN # is 46-5486022
We rescue 800+ animals a year.

Follow us on Facebook at www.facebook.com/camorescue

Our donation link is http://www.paypalme/camorescue 

We are strictly volunteer based, no salaries are paid and 100% of donations go towards rescuing dogs.

animal.description: *SPECIAL ADOPTION PROCEDURE* *6 FT FENCE REQUIRED* Birdie is considered to be a feral dog. Through the crucial developmental period she was not exposed to things that normal pet dogs get exposed to. She lived in an shed with other dogs and had very minimal exposure to humans other than feeding time. Here in the shelter she has found a couple people that she tolerates being around but has no real interest in interacting with them. She follows the lead of other calm, mature, stable minded dogs. Birdie can not go to a home with cats. Birdie's family should understand that she may never be a normal family pet and may never bond to the people around her. She will need time, patience, and working with her will be a very long, slow process. Working with feral dogs can be rewarding but can also be frustrating and requires great dedication. Birdie's potential family also needs to be aware that she may have an issue with her lower GI tract. Her foster mom found a food that is good for keeping Birdie's stool formed and she will need to stay on that food after she finds a home. She also needs frequent potty breaks. If she gets too excited when she hasn't been outside for a while she can't seem to be able to hold it all in! Otherwise, she is housebroken and has not had other accidents in the foster home. *Preferred: A secure 6 foot fence is a must as Birdie is a flight risk. Another calm dog in the house would be preferred to help Birdie adjust. A home with no children would be the most successful. Birdie would probably appreciate a family of homebody introverts who understand her personality! The Adoption Fee Includes: - initial canine distemper combination vaccination - first worming or stool check - rabies vaccination (for animals over 3 months of age) - AVID microchipping - flea treatment/preventative - spaying or neutering Adoption fee: $175.00 Per state law, ALL ADOPTERS must purchase a non-refundable 2021 dog license at time of adoption for any canine three months and older. The cost of the license is $7.00. (Senior Citizen or Person with Disability-$5.00) All dog adoptions come with free leash and collar.
